 width=\"97\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">11/10/54</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"101\">\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1130000</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"44\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">35</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"97\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">11/10/55</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"101\">\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1130000</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"44\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">36</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"97\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">11/10/56</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"101\">\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1130000</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"44\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">37</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"97\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">11/10/57</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"101\">\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1130000</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"44\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">37</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"97\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">11/10/57</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"101\">\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">15000000</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"44\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"97\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>XIRR</strong></span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"101\">\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5.892%</strong></span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Oh my God, the return is only 5.892% for the tenure of 37 years. Now again I would like to ask my readers &ndash; How does it sound? Some of may be confused in determining should we invest in HDFC Life Sanchay Plus?&nbsp; So we analyse the product under various arena and following are the results:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Arena 1 &ndash; Wealth creation product</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Definitely No due to poor return of such long period. In such a long period even considering 6%-7% product as an option should be considered foolish. Equity is best asset class for long term where investor can expect 12%-14% CAGR.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Arena 2 &ndash; Insurance</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Traditional plan are not a good choice. Rather we should consider Pure Term plan for life cover where the premium is very less for significant life cover.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Arena 3 &ndash; Retirement planning</strong>&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Again retirement planning at 5.8% ROI where inflation is near to 6%, does make this product fetch negative real rate of return. Again since retirement planning is long term planning, therefore targeting 6%-7% isn&rsquo;t wise.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For me or my clients portfolio, I would suggest to not invest in such products. I would rather suggest to invest in equity or equity related product for 37 year time horizon (very very long term) and start SWP (systematic withdrawal plan) from same for retirement planning, if needed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Akhil Bharadwaj</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687941892/lqjmgvcug4arw3tyqfts.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"HDFC Life Sanchay Plus – Analysis & Review","seo_keywords":"HDFC Life Sanchay Plus – Analysis & Review","seo_description":"Oh my God, the return is only 5.892% for the tenure of 37 years. Now again I would like to ask my readers – How does it sound? Some of may be confused in determining should we invest in HDFC Life Sanchay Plus?  So we analyse the product under various arena and following are the results:","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687941890/xebvefs6pexwe7pdnqjn.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"139","title":"Can Cryptocurrency be considered as an Asset Class?","slug":"can-cryptocurrency-be-considered-as-an-asset-class","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1634201105","published_date_view":"Oct 14, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The global financial crisis of 2008 had made several investors and finance pundits raise their eyebrows regarding the shortfalls of the current global centralized financial system. Bitcoin, the first cryptocurrency in the world, took birth in 2008 soon after the financial market fiasco. The credit partially goes to the distrust of the current centralised financial systems all over the world.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The idea of Satoshi Nakamoto &ndash; the pseudonym of Bitcoin&rsquo;s inventor &mdash; was to create a decentralized, peer-to-peer monetary system that would eliminate the inefficiencies of the current centralized global financial systems.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Blockchain Technology</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cryptocurrencies are built on Blockchain technology with the idea of a decentralized online cash system that allows financial transactions without a verification from a third-party like a central bank. It is a database that is shared across a global network of computers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is very difficult to tamper or merely edit a record once it has been added to the chain. The blockchain network conducts constant verification to ensure the authenticity of all the copies of the database.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Apart from supporting cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin, blockchain technology can also be efficiently used in the fields of banking, supply chain, healthcare, voting, and keeping property records.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Cryptocurrency, An Asset Class?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Today, cryptocurrencies have turned into a topic for heated discussion all over the world and are considered by some as the &lsquo;currency of the future&rsquo;. As days pass by, more and more people take cryptocurrencies as a tool for investment rather than a medium of exchange.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Adoption of cryptocurrency is rising fast in India. The businesses involved in the cryptocurrency sphere not only take cryptocurrencies as an asset class but also try to convince the financial regulators of the country against banning them.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Liquidity, stability, value, and a low transaction cost are the four major factors that determine a good asset class. The aim of this article is to point out whether cryptocurrencies possess all these four factors to consider them as a good asset class. The decision to take a plunge in the world of cryptocurrency investing or trading rests solely at the discretion of the reader.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>A Deflationary Asset</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Now let&rsquo;s take up the first factor: Liquidity. Most of the cryptocurrencies including Bitcoin come with a limit in production. For Bitcoin, it is 21 million. Some cryptocurrencies don&rsquo;t have a market cap but hold limits on their annual production. For instance, as of now, nearly 19 million Bitcoins have been generated, that means, 83 percent of the limit of Bitcoin production has been reached. Today, the Bitcoin market capitalisation has hit roughly $866 billion (approximately ₹64,35,270 crores).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cryptocurrency enthusiasts aren&rsquo;t concerned about the deflationary nature of cryptocurrency supply. As far as Bitcoin is concerned, the infinite divisibility feature stands as an advantage. As Bitcoin gets more valuable in future, it can be transacted in smaller units named Satoshis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Fiat currencies, in contrast, can be printed and distributed by the central banks of respective countries. But if this additional creation of the paper currency doesn&rsquo;t sync with the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) growth of the respective country, it may lead to a surge in inflation and related economic issues.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>A Highly Volatile Cryptocurrency Market</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cryptocurrency market, as everyone knows, is highly volatile and notorious for reckless speculative activities. Even the expert cryptocurrency enthusiasts and investors find it hard to deal with the unpredictable volatility of these digital financial instruments. Abrupt market crashes resulting from sudden selloff by &lsquo;whale&rsquo; investors or technical glitches at cryptocurrency exchanges have troubled the unregulated cryptocurrency markets since the day of their inception. Therefore, a higher market risk, a by-product of cryptocurrencies, stands against the stability factor required for a good asset class.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Cryptocurrency &ndash; a liquid, or illiquid asset?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Liquidity refers to the efficiency or ease with which an asset can be traded or converted into cash without affecting its market price.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cryptocurrencies, with no doubt, have generated lucrative returns for early investors. But along with higher volatility in prices, cryptocurrencies also suffer from abrupt illiquidity. An unstable market and a lower number of cryptocurrency users are among the few factors that contribute towards the illiquidity of cryptocurrencies.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The introduction of Satoshis in Bitcoin has greatly improved its liquidity, but it is not the case with other cryptocurrencies &ndash; they remain vulnerable to abrupt drying up of liquidity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cryptocurrencies have a long way to go. These New Age financial instruments, though moving ahead in an unpredictable trajectory, are gaining acceptance worldwide. The cryptocurrency-friendly approach of countries such as the United States, Canada and Australia can be taken in a positive note that helps to reduce the liquidity risk of cryptocurrencies in future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Higher Transaction Costs</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Most cryptocurrencies including Bitcoin and Ethereum come with higher transaction costs in the form of exchange fees, network fees, and wallet fees. The higher amount of electric and computational power required to generate cryptocurrencies also adds to the cost.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This higher transaction costs works against cryptocurrencies when it comes to taking them as a good asset class. It also keeps traditional investors away from considering cryptocurrencies as an investment avenue or using them as a medium of exchange.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>A Doubtful Storage of Value</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Today, the global cryptocurrency market crossed $1.7 trillion capitalization. However, many still are sceptical about the ability of a cryptocurrency to act as a stable storage of value. Crediting its limited supply, some term it as &lsquo;digital gold&rsquo; while others doubt it as &lsquo;digital Tulipmania &lsquo;. According to popular author and risk analyst Nassim Nicholas Taleb, the true value of cryptocurrencies including Bitcoin is zero.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">All these mixed responses are mainly because of the high volatility and unpredictability associated with it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The Sunnier Future</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Many institutional investors and Fortune 500 companies like Tesla and MicroStrategy are adopting various cryptocurrencies including Bitcoin as a hedge against their speculations of higher inflation in future and &lsquo;black swan&rsquo; events like the Corona pandemic. Globally, Tesla is among the one of the first companies that have already converted a great part, or their entire balance sheet cash into cryptocurrency.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Amid abrupt market crashes and notoriety associated with cryptocurrencies, financial regulators in some countries have shown a willingness to consider cryptocurrencies as an asset class. They also allow asset management firms to launch financial instruments such as exchange-traded funds (ETFs), and crypto-backed bonds that give access to investors in a regulated environment.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In India, the proposed cryptocurrency law of the Finance Ministry is about to take a more calibrated approach towards cryptocurrencies. Let&rsquo;s hope all these optimistic developments can lead to the birth of the foundation of a stable financial asset class.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Justin Raj</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942105/t5jjg8t39onx16cviii8.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Can Cryptocurrency be considered as an Asset Class?","seo_keywords":"Can Cryptocurrency be considered as an Asset Class?","seo_description":"The global financial crisis of 2008 had made several investors and finance pundits raise their eyebrows regarding the shortfalls of the current global centralized financial system. Bitcoin, the first cryptocurrency in the world, took birth in 2008 soon after the financial market fiasco. The credit partially goes to the distrust of the current centralised financial systems all over the world.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942102/yjxaw2hxhozd29qfpm4y.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"140","title":"The Enigmatic Relationship of Stock Market & GDP","slug":"the-enigmatic-relationship-of-stock-market-gdp","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1633682918","published_date_view":"Oct 08, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Warren Buffett states the ratio of market capitalization (market cap) to GDP as &ldquo;probably the best single measure of where valuations stand at any given moment.&rdquo; Undoubtedly, investing community uses it worldwide to judge whether the market is over/underpriced. However, I have my reasons to be wary of using this indicator. This ratio has the market cap in the numerator, a stock concept (at a particular time) and GDP in the denominator, a flow concept (over some time). Having said that, is there any inference we can draw from this indicator?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To begin with, let&rsquo;s look at the graph of the world market cap to GDP. Sourced from the world bank, it spans 1976 till 2020. It indicates that the two peaks when the Market Cap / GDP ratio crossed the 100% mark represent the two massive peaks of 1999 (Dotcom bubble) and 2007(global financial crisis). In 2017 market once again touched the 100 mark but corrected quickly. However, since 2020, amidst the worldwide pandemic devastation, the markets have been above the 100 mark.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942253/moepwaro5sxoml1s4k1x.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 553px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Source: World Bank data</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Looking at the same numbers for India exhibits an interesting pattern. The peak was observed in 2007. Interestingly, 2020 saw India&rsquo;s market cap / GDP ratio crossing the 100% mark after a gap of almost ten years amid the pandemic. Roaring stocks in the struggling economy brings to the forefront a disturbing disconnect between the stock market and real economic growth. So, if the past is any prologue and we are to learn anything from history, then this is something that the world markets need to be cautious about, but not be scared.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942281/vpsm2gm8kvqhlzi1ovuu.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 656px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to the original Buffet Indicator, the Stock Market is Significantly Overvalued. However, In India, particularly demonetisation, Goods and service tax (GST) has brought more and more Indian businesses into the mainstream, which is gradually reflected in the market cap / GDP ratio. To that extent, there may not be room to worry. We all have been living with the belief that economic growth and the stock market are correlated. A higher economic growth/ recovery is reflected in higher stock market returns. In the present situation, however, this relationship seems to be failing. So how can one make sense of the long-term relationship (or the lack of one!!) which runs counter to our received wisdom.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Examining the factors of this tremendous increase, following pointers are to be kept in mind.&nbsp; The recent IPO glut (roughly A lakh crore of raised money) has added to the market cap without disturbing the GDP.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Another vital factor is that the stock market is (or at least attempts to be) forward-looking while GDP is backwards looking. It implies that the higher prices we are witnessing today anticipate higher economic growth (GDP).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors&rsquo; expectations that &lsquo;the GDP is already at its bottom and what worse can happen further&rsquo; is driving these returns. On the other hand, GDP indicates what has happened in the future, more recent quarter &ndash; the economy&rsquo;s actual performance. As the investor&rsquo;s greed and fear emotions dominate the market- it has decoupled from the fundamentals. Stock returns somewhat move with economic growth but have a life of their own driven by greed, fear, optimism, and emotions. And because these emotions tend to fluctuate more than the economy does, so do stock returns &mdash; this is a significant reason why stocks are more volatile than economic growth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942306/jqobksgaudxos7jbbh7u.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 586px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Considering India, positioned as one of the fastest-growing economies, the investor&rsquo;s community&rsquo;s exuberance may not be totally unfounded. In their attempts to moderate the impact of covid 19 pandemic, liquidity being pumped into the economies globally by the to fight the recession and to moderate the economic consequences of the Covid-19 pandemic. Foreign capital is finding its way to the Indian markets, contributing to high stock index values.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942331/cbhsod4xpuptudwh9ynr.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 444px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Another possible factor contributing to the dismantling of the relationships in the last few years is the economic imbalances. Few companies/ sectors like Information technology and pharmaceuticals are fueling the stock market. Typically, the ones who were not much affected, or were quick to recover and adapt in these unprecedented times. For example, companies with economies of scale-like Reliance and Hindustan Unilever or an IT company like TCS or Infosys, are not overly impacted by physical supply chains. Hence, these stocks are gaining value much faster.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is rightly said that FAANG stocks (Facebook, Apple, Alphabet, Netflix and Google) are not the economy; they represent just a fraction of the total economy. At times, the stock index could be heavily weighted towards the companies with the futures that everyone is most excited about rather than the ones whose presents have the most significant impact on the current economy. The market is not the economy. Its job is to tabulate investors&rsquo; consensus views about the future of listed companies, with no attention paid to the private businesses, MSMEs, government and other vital parts of the economy. In sum, the stock market&rsquo;s buoyancy is echoing the revival in the organised sector.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On the other hand, GDP reflects the pain in the informal sector, where the recovery is painstakingly slow. &nbsp;The impact of Covid 19 has been more severe on the informal sector. One can still see the flashes of the sight when thousands of migrant labourers were forced to travel on foot.&nbsp; Specifically in India, though the contribution of agriculture and industries to GDP and their representation in the stock market performance is declining over the period, it is still the largest employer.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Another reason for the unexplained optimism in the market, despite the pessimistic GDP forecasts, is the strong household balance sheets, which is often a common outcome of the recessions in the past.&nbsp; This is partly due to the fewer spending and borrowing opportunities, greater control on expenditure, coupled with financial stimulus/ relief packages. Suppose you leave out the most vulnerable sections. In that case, most people are still employed and earning close to their pre-recession income but spending a lot less. Increasing number of Demat accounts corroborates this fact. With low bond yields, investors are left with little room to invest in assets other than equities. This triggers the fundamental demand-supply dynamics in the stock market and pushes the stock prices higher.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A poor GDP forecast adds fuel to the equity demand. Investors expect RBI to maintain an easy monetary policy stance.&nbsp; Nationwide vaccination drive, easing out of lockdown curbs, and signs of economic recovery in the future are possible reasons the market to celebrate. But this celebration is only for fundamentally strong companies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This confounding dichotomy might not be surprising anymore if we look at the broader picture. The differential impact of lockdown on the organised and unorganised sector is the main reason for this seeming disconnect between the stock market performance and the real economy. Given this, the future will belong to resilient companies which are agile and efficient.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">I leave you all with hope. I hope that the Indian economy will return to robust growth in the near future, indicated by Moody&rsquo;s sovereign rating upgrade. I hope that the policymakers will find innovative ways to address the pain points in the informal sector. I hope that a rise in stock prices would bring about a wealth effect, which increases consumption. This increased consumer spending would give a fillip to economic growth. The increased use of technology would improve the data collection and analysis, gradually reducing the underreporting of revenues to save taxes, giving a more realistic picture of the GDP. And I hope this sharp rise in market capitalisation to GDP ratio is not temporary, but a new normal for the Indian Economy!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942464/gspj3cvrzrttdpfucuwt.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Enigmatic Relationship of Stock Market & GDP","seo_keywords":"The Enigmatic Relationship of Stock Market & GDP","seo_description":"Warren Buffett states the ratio of market capitalization (market cap) to GDP as “probably the best single measure of where valuations stand at any given moment.” Undoubtedly, investing community uses it worldwide to judge whether the market is over/underpriced. However, I have my reasons to be wary of using this indicator. This ratio has the market cap in the numerator, a stock concept (at a particular time) and GDP in the denominator, a flow concept (over some time). Having said that, is there any inference we can draw from this indicator?","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687942462/q3nvpzsafvqqvosoyshm.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"141","title":"The Top Five Technology Funds for Investment in 2021-22","slug":"the-top-five-technology-funds-for-investment-in-2021-22","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1633597407","published_date_view":"Oct 07, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The whole world is running on the shoulders of technology, particularly, since the Corona pandemic. Technology has deeply penetrated into the fields of Communication, Health Care, and Finance to name a few that have closer relation with day to day human life. Henceforward, Information Technology (IT) would be the forefront where most of the innovations and breakthroughs would take place. The exponential technological advancement we witness today, with no doubt, is here to stay and going to drive human life and businesses on a long-term basis.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With this rapid technological advancement comes lucrative investment opportunities since IT has turned into one of the key drivers of the global economy. Today, Digital Transformation is the buzzword among most of the enterprises all over the world. Small scale industries to larger corporations are embracing technology to enhance their productivity or at least to survive in the current disruptive digital environment. The demand for the stocks of the businesses focused on digital services, Industry 4.0, Artificial intelligence (AI), Machine Learning and Data Science are rising.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Most of us know about the digital technology revolution and how it is going to transform the world we live in. But only a very few know how to make their wealth grow along with this inevitable technological revolution. At times, even the experienced investors, fail to pick the right technology stocks to grow their wealth. This dilemma over technology equity investment has been taken away to a greater extent by Technology Funds, the privately pooled and professionally managed funds that focus on the equity of rapidly growing Information Technology (IT) companies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The investment in IT related stocks or Technology Funds would be a wise investment decision. But like any other investments, they do come with risks. Technology funds are risky in nature as their performance solely depends on the performance of the IT business sector. On the brighter side, these Technology Mutual Funds can also deliver more than 100% returns in an investment timeframe of 3 to 5 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This article aims at giving an overview of the top five Technology Funds that have delivered double digit returns to investors in 2021-22 and a few factors to consider while investing in these Technology Funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>ICICI Pru Technology Fund</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since its launch in March 2000, ICICI Pru Technology Fund has generated 1190% returns for the investors and in last year alone, it has delivered 134% returns. Credit Rating Information Services of India Limited (CRISIL) has given a three-star rating for this mutual fund.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Managed by expert fund managers, this fund has 88.38% of its capital allocation in Indian technology stocks of which 53.61% is in large cap stocks like Infosys, HCL, TCS and Tech Mahindra. The fund allocates the remaining 8.52% and 20.12% in mid-cap stocks and small-cap stocks respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This Technology Fund that comes with a higher expense ratio is suitable for investors with up-to-date knowledge of macroeconomic trends and remains selective in picking up funds with higher returns compared to other Equity funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">ICICI Pru Technology is not suitable for risk averse investors as it may be possible that the fund can bring moderate to heavy capital drawdowns in spite of better performance of the overall market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Tata Digital India Fund</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Tata Digital India Fund, another high performing technology fund, launched in December 2015 has generated 118% returns last year. 80% of the pooled investment of Tata Digital India Fund is allocated in direct equity of large-cap IT companies such as Infosys, L&amp;T Infotech, HCL, Tech Mahindra and Persistent system.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Aditya Birla Sun Life Digital India Fund</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Aditya Birla Sun Life Digital India Fund, a higher performing Technology Fund in the country, was launched in January 2013 and has been generating double digit returns since then. CRISIL has endowed the fund with a four-star rating.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Aditya Birla Sun Life Digital India Fund focuses primarily on large-cap Indian IT companies like Infosys, TCS, Tech Mahindra, HCL Technologies and Cyient. Last year, the returns from this fund stood at 113% while it has generated 210% returns for the last 5 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>SBI Technology Opportunities Fund</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">SBI Technology Opportunities Fund, an open-ended direct equity scheme in the Technology sector, is from the stable of State Bank of India Mutual Funds. The fund which was launched in January 2013 has generated 94% return for the investor in last year alone.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">SBI Technology Opportunities Fund comes with a slightly higher expense ratio. The fund allocates capital in Indian technology stocks as well as in international ones. Top technology stocks that have taken the major share of this fund include Infosys, TCS, HCL Technologies and Alphabet, the parent company of Google.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Franklin India Technology Fund</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Launched in August 1998, Franklin India Technology Fund is one of the longest running Technology Funds in the country. The major investment objective of the fund is an above average capital appreciation through investments in fastest growing IT companies. Last year, Franklin India Technology Fund generated 74% returns for the investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This fund has major investments in large-cap IT companies like Infosys, HCL and TCS. Though this fund has delivered above average returns to the investors, it has been categorized as a risky fund by various investors and rating agencies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The Major Factors to Consider When Investing in Technology Funds</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The frequent boom and bust of technology companies will be a norm of the day in this Digital Age. The advent of disruptive technologies also adds fuel to the fire of risk in direct equity investments in the Technology sector. This simply means the technology funds are not for investors who are looking out for higher return generating lower risk investments. It is highly advisable that only the investors with higher risk profile should enter this investment arena.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Technology funds require a time frame of 5-7 years to generate higher returns. An investor should also be required to monitor the performance of these funds on a regular basis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Picking out a mutual fund would be a difficult task to some investors. A little bit of research and understanding of one&rsquo;s financial goals can solve this problem. Along with due diligence in selecting a mutual fund, an investor can also take up the service of an expert financial advisor. Or, if an investor prefers to go solo in this investment venture, it is highly advisable that he or she should take the Systematic Investment Plan (SIP) route towards Technology Funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Justin Raj</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687943489/s1fnxtkn1jcjvyo2n2qe.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Top Five Technology Funds for Investment in 2021-22","seo_keywords":"The Top Five Technology Funds for Investment in 2021-22","seo_description":"The whole world is running on the shoulders of technology, particularly, since the Corona pandemic. Technology has deeply penetrated into the fields of Communication, Health Care, and Finance to name a few that have closer relation with day to day human life. Henceforward, Information Technology (IT) would be the forefront where most of the innovations and breakthroughs would take place. The exponential technological advancement we witness today, with no doubt, is here to stay and going to drive human life and businesses on a long-term basis.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687943487/evb1wprpg7hlg4741ce2.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"142","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories On Markets And Investing","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-investing","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1633425806","published_date_view":"Oct 05, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please find below the 5&nbsp;charts&nbsp;that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) London Bridge is Falling Down:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">FTSE 100 (Top 100 Companies listed in London Stock Exchange) has not given any return in the last 20 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944343/sunz5ojmfw2z7e2danmv.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 750px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">No return from equity despite buying and holding for 20 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Buy, hold and forget doesn&rsquo;t always work in equity. You need to buy aggressively when market falls.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Keeping dry powder (Debt Funds) to buy equity when market falls is important.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) 7-Year Asset Class Real Return Forecasts:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944375/rwsdiosrbm1zkxyds1yj.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 811px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">GMO has predicted the worst real return for global equity &amp; debt in the coming 7 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Equity is expected to deliver annual return of -8%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Emerging Value Equity is the only asset type which is expected to deliver positive return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Debt real return is expected to be negative.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Robert Kiyosaki &ndash; Rich Author, Poor Readers:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944401/cvguvdjx25twjdqafhpi.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 510px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the last 10 years, Robert Kiyosaki has 7 times predicted big crash in stock market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And every time he has been wrong.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Take expert predictions with a pinch of salt. Do your own diligence with eyes wide open.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Asset Allocation of US Endowments:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944430/rsjdg2azgojmigscghvw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 673px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Endowments have delivered phenomenal return in the last 1 year beating the benchmarks significantly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">They have invested 56% in Equities and 31% in Alternates to boost the return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With a time horizon of 100 Years, Endowments are comfortable with short term volatility.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Top 10 S&amp;P Companies in 1980&ndash;2020:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944453/x1lqnf9pbysucf1ip2pf.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 549px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The top companies list is very dynamic &amp; keeps changing a lot even in 5 years period.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Change is going to be even much faster going forward due to tech disruption.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investing and picking companies is going to be interesting with lot of opportunities.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944571/mpytjceofunlightpa1t.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories On Markets And Investing","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories On Markets And Investing","seo_description":"GMO has predicted the worst real return for global equity & debt in the coming 7 years.\r\n\r\nUS Equity is expected to deliver annual return of -8%.\r\n\r\nEmerging Value Equity is the only asset type which is expected to deliver positive return.\r\n\r\nDebt real return is expected to be negative.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944569/illaiqgiy4ylujoycmlb.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"205","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (Research)","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-research-2","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1632767400","published_date_view":"Sep 28, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please find below the 5&nbsp;charts&nbsp;that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Indian equity market is reverting to long term average:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034457/rx922aamtwb4dgoxvmzh.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 800px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The past decade has seen the lowest compounding of return for India, compared to the preceding three decades.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The current secular bull run in India is a catch up to revert to the long term mean average.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity market is expensive now but not in bubble zone yet.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) RBI has flooded the market with liquidity:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034476/ep6azt0pieem7q6ottq0.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 422px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Liquidity surplus in banking system has surged to new historic peak at Rs. 11 Trillion.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">RBI has been aggressively buying bonds through OMO and has been buying dollars to keep bond yields low and to limit INR appreciation respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With economy showing healthy recovery, RBI will hopefully reverse the liquidity soon which should lead to increase of interest rates.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Investors need to accept higher volatility for better return:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034514/upo6ye2q9p9c0zjdfntf.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 946px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors grappling with lower interest rates have to take bigger risks if they want to equal return of two decades ago.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Earlier, investors could get high return with 100% bonds portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Now to get similar return, considerable amount needs to be invested in Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&ndash; Data for US</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) US S&amp;P 500 &ndash; From 2000 to 2013:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034536/lbyu33uw0ebpifvekmgd.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 707px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2000 &amp; 2008 were the years of big crash in US market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It took market 6+ years to come back to pre crash level.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity is not for short term. Only Invest that money in equity which has a time horizon of at least 7 years especially when market is expensive.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Future Tech is a secular theme for investment:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034555/e7pc4u1op3rxabznzo0i.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 627px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Future Tech &ndash; 6G, Emotional AI, Immorality, Wireless Electricity, Metaverse etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">These new tech developments are all going to happen in the next 10 years and are going to transform our life.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Majority of this work is happening in US. Invest in US Tech for next 10 years and forget.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034665/anel7qplpsxluj5evcfp.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (Research)","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (Research)","seo_description":"Future Tech – 6G, Emotional AI, Immorality, Wireless Electricity, Metaverse etc.\r\n\r\nThese new tech developments are all going to happen in the next 10 years and are going to transform our life.\r\n\r\nMajority of this work is happening in US. Invest in US Tech for next 10 years and forget.\r\n\r\nDr. Mukesh Jindal CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688034663/e9v5qpdegjiriijywaba.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"143","title":"8 Investment Options with Higher Returns for HNIs","slug":"8-investment-options-with-higher-returns-for-hnis","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1631871020","published_date_view":"Sep 17, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is a matter of common sense that both active and passive investing are two proven ways to grow your money rather than keeping it idle in a savings bank account. If you are a High Net worth Individual (HNI) still confused about how to invest your wealth, let&rsquo;s take a look at the 8 investment options that can generate higher returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Fixed-Income Funds</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Fixed-income funds also known as debt funds or credit funds are the most popular and time-tested investment options. These asset classes, the darlings of the middle-class population, can also play a greater role in the diversification of large sized portfolios. These classic investment avenues consist of Fixed Deposits (FD), Triple-A (AAA) Bonds, and Government Bonds that can generate steady cash flow with higher security for your capital. The investors with a conservative risk profile can safely bet their money on fixed-income funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Direct Equity</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">After fixed-income funds, direct equity or stock market investments are the most popular investment avenues with higher returns but with higher risk. If you can invest a little bit of your time to study the fundamentals of the securities and analyse stock market trends, you can easily pick out lower risk, higher return yielding securities.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If you are an HNI with little time or interest to contribute towards investment research, you could always choose an expert Portfolio Manager. He can help you to pick stocks with meticulous risk assessment, and the expertise on fundamental and technical analysis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Financial markets are evolving rapidly during this digital era. Powerful Artificial Intelligence (AI) technology and algorithms predict financial market trends giving lesser room for human emotions while trading. In this scenario, if your technical expertise permits, you can deploy your own algorithms. Otherwise, it is highly advisable to get an expert quantitative trader on board to make financial market investment decisions for you.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Real Estate Investment Trusts (REIT)</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Real estate is another classic investment avenue that offers safety of your investment and yields higher returns. The dawn of the digital age has transformed this time-tested investment avenue for the better.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Emulating the model of mutual funds, a Real Estate Investment Trust (REIT) company pools the capital from various investors and invests it into income-generating real estate properties. Without bearing the pain of buying, managing, or financing any real estate properties by himself, an individual investor can earn dividends from real estate investments through REIT.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As REIT companies offer real estate investments as digitized stocks that earn dividends, they offer greater liquidity &ndash; if you sell your stock, the money is credited to your bank account the very next day. It is a greater development from the traditional real estate investments that require capital intensive yet time consuming real estate deals.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Currently, Mindspace Business Parks REIT, Embassy Office Parks REIT, and Brookfield India Real Estate Trust are the only three REITs available in India. In coming days, other leading names in the Real Estate Sector such as Godrej and DLF are also expected to enter the REIT arena.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Gold</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Gold is another traditional investment avenue that has been greatly transformed by digitalization. Today, an investor can easily invest in digital gold or gold backed funds without worrying about the safety of holding actual gold in hand. This digital gold backed investments acts as a hedge against inflation and unpredictable financial market shocks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Alternative Investment Fund (AIF)</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alternative Investment Fund (AIF) is an unconventional investment avenue. It is a privately pooled fund from both Indian and foreign investors incorporated in India in accordance with a well-defined investment policy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The asset classes of an AIF may include private equity, precious metals, derivative contracts, and even real estate among the few. AIF, an excellent investment option if you have an investment corpus worth a crore and above, is also a great diversification tool in a portfolio. This investment avenue showcases innovation of financial products and customized services as its hallmark features.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Private Equity</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India is a rapidly developing country that has turned into a hotbed of start-ups in various promising business sectors. Start-up culture is essential for our country&rsquo;s economic growth as well as to give wings to the dreams of the young populace. In India, there are a good number of talented and skilled entrepreneurs who face the dearth of capital to launch their promising business projects.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">An HNI can invest directly in a start-up or if it is the first time, he can provide capital to a start-up through a network of angel investors. HNIs can also invest in the private equity of the promoters of start-up companies and pull their money once the business project turns viable and set for Initial Public Offering (IPO). Always remember that successful private equity investments require some diligent research and market analysis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Antique Trade</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If you are a lover of art and culture with a deep pocket; then antique trade is an excellent investment avenue for you. Artworks of renowned artists and artifacts with historical relevance are great long-term investments. Modern and contemporary arts also garner investor interest these days. Art funds, though a young investment class, offer liquidity and can also be used as a significant investment tool to diversify a portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Crypto Currency</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Crypto currencies are widely considered to be a very risky asset with tons of speculation surrounding them. The decentralization of the global financial system, and the attempts of governments worldwide to regulate the cryptocurrency market are among the few rumours in the air.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Anyway, the digital age is all about decentralization and democratization of most of the traditional establishments and professional sectors. Gauging the popularity, trends and growth of disruptive technologies &mdash; cryptocurrencies, without doubt, are assets of the future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is advisable that you should at least invest a tiny portion of your portfolio on the &lsquo;currency of the future&rsquo;. You can start investing in popular cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin and Ethereum. Then add new currencies to your portfolio whenever they are introduced to the market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Bottom Line</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The truth is most of the investors are in constant watch for investment avenues that can earn over the top returns as quickly as possible. That too, without the risk of losing the principal amount. In reality, an investment product that comes along with a combination of higher return and lower risk, unfortunately, doesn&rsquo;t exist. Risks and returns are directly proportional in the market; that is, lower the risk, lower the return and vice versa.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The investment options described above are some of the best investment classes available in the market today. But, like every other investment venture, they have their own advantages and disadvantages. It is highly advisable that an investor should always choose the assets and allocate the capital carefully in accordance with his financial goals and risk profile.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&ndash; Justin Raj</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944830/aicldrjchfaskfyegd3x.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"8 Investment Options with Higher Returns for HNIs","seo_keywords":"8 Investment Options with Higher Returns for HNIs","seo_description":"It is a matter of common sense that both active and passive investing are two proven ways to grow your money rather than keeping it idle in a savings bank account. If you are a High Net worth Individual (HNI) still confused about how to invest your wealth, let’s take a look at the 8 investment options that can generate higher returns.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687944828/uzex4hnrxazyvuomddo9.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"144","title":"A Few Tax Saver Investment Routes for High Net Worth Individuals (HNIs)","slug":"a-few-tax-saver-investment-routes-for-high-net-worth-individuals-hnis","category":"Tax Planning","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1630575259","published_date_view":"Sep 02, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&lsquo;In this world, nothing can be said to be certain except death and taxes.&rsquo; These 18th-century words of wisdom from Benjamin Franklin, one of the United States&rsquo; founding fathers, hold even in the 21<sup>st</sup>&nbsp;century.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Individuals with a taxable income of ₹ one crore or above &ndash; High Net worth Individuals or HNIs &ndash; are entitled to a two percent additional surcharge. It was proposed by the Finance Act of 2015. Recently, the Budget 2019 introduced a broad 22 percent rise in surcharge rates for individuals with taxable income of more than ₹5 crores. The tax proposal has widened the tax bracket for HNIs to nearly 43%. These adverse Indian taxation policies on HNIs have made most of them look out for other ways to transfer their revenue sources and financial assets, particularly to tax haven countries.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Yes, death and taxes are certain. Though we can&rsquo;t save ourselves from death, in the case of taxes, we can save a great deal of it through proper financial planning.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Here are some legitimate ways for the HNIs to save tax on their revenue from various asset classes.</span></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Equity Investment</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The Indian equity market, with a total market capitalization of more than $3 trillion, offers a number of tax saver financial instruments. Equity investments in listed securities for more than a year and long-term investments in debt instruments (Bonds, Debentures, Certificates of Deposit, etc.) for more than three years generate revenue as long-term capital gains and dividends. Both revenues are tax-free in India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Informed equity investment decisions can provide a tax-saving investment opportunity with greater liquidity. Consider a fixed deposit of ₹1 lakh with a Fixed Maturity Plan (FMP) of three years. An investor who comes under the 30 percent tax bracket invites a tax amount of more than ₹10,000 for the mentioned fixed deposit scheme. On the other hand, if the same amount of money is invested in a debt mutual fund with a 3-year FMP, the investor has to pay only a meager sum of ₹600.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity investments, though an attractive investment option for HNIs, are not for investors with a conventional mindset and greatly rely on the investor&rsquo;s risk appetite.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Home Loans</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A home loan is a hidden tax-saving tool for HNIs that can also help them to build their wealth. Section 24 of the Income Tax Act allows the deduction of interest up to ₹2 lakhs on home loans as a tax rebate. High net-worth individuals with more than one residential property with rental provisions can take home huge tax savings as the standard 30 percent tax deduction is allowed.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Non-Resident External (NRE) and Foreign Currency Non-Resident (FCNR) Deposits</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A risk-averse non-resident Indian HNI with a deep pocket and a keen eye on tax benefits can plan for NRE or FCNR term deposits in India that can also earn tax-exempt interest. However, the investor should evaluate the tax implication of his or her country of residence regarding these international investments.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Bonus Stripping</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Bonus stripping is a tax-saving practice in which an investor buys mutual fund units or shares of a company that has announced a stock bonus. He or she later sells the shares soon after the bonus date and books a notional loss. This notional loss can legitimately be adjusted against the short-term or long-term capital gain from any financial assets of the investor. The Income Tax Act of India provides the provision to carry forward this unadjusted loss for up to eight financial years. This is a good tax-saving strategy for HNIs who come under a higher tax bracket.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Hindu Undivided Family (HUF)</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Under the Income Tax Act of India, HUF is considered a separate legal entity that invites income tax only at individual levels. Hindus, Buddhists, Jains, and Sikhs are entitled to form HUFs in India. The income from the assets like ancestral property or a will, life insurance policy, and salary of its members receives tax deductions under section 80C of the Income Tax Act of India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Limited Liability Partnership (LLP)</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">HNIs with entrepreneurial itch can consider setting up companies as LLPs. LLPs enjoy separate legal entity status and open various ways to infuse capital into the partnership. Partners to the LLP can invest in their company via revenues from their property, loans from banks and Non-Banking Financial Companies (NBFCs), or monetary donations. Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) norms have been relaxed, over the years, for LLPs allowing hassle-free investment avenues for non-resident HNIs. Additionally, income distribution among the LLP partners is exempted from tax. LLPs enjoy a tax rate of about 35%, while HNIs generally are entitled to the current income tax rate of 43%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The LLP structure has been widely accepted among professionals and entrepreneurs alike for its tax efficiency. All these tax benefits and ease of administration of the LLP structure boosted its popularity in the investment world. Coupled with increased efficiency and cost savings, the LLP structure stands as a bridge for new-age entrepreneurs to sail smoothly through the current tumultuous pandemic days and firmly on the &lsquo;new normal&rsquo; post-pandemic entrepreneurial era.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Family Trust</strong></span></span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A family trust is a permanent institution independent of its beneficiaries that enjoys greater flexibility in managing its assets, be it investments, acquisitions, disposals, or any other financial dealings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In a family trust, &lsquo;settlors&rsquo; transfer the assets and revenue to the &lsquo;trustee&rsquo; who is held responsible for the benefit of the &lsquo;beneficiaries&rsquo;. In a typical family trust structure, every asset of the trust, including residential properties, cash, bank deposits, and shares, can be transferred to the beneficiaries in a tax-free mode. Along with upholding family harmony, a family trust can preserve wealth, protect assets, and restrict third-party involvement in the family business. However, the revenue earned by the family trust will be taxed as per the specific and discretionary nature of the trust.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The efficiency and convenience of family trusts are gaining popularity nowadays. If structured and maintained prudently, a family trust can be a great institution that can efficiently manage assets, finances, equity investments, and revenue earned by the family trust to benefit its beneficiaries.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The entire investment world is significantly transforming, and now is the time to rethink and plan your investments wisely yet legitimately.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945117/ialxynh29cotcbfqrhff.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"A Few Tax Saver Investment Routes for High Net Worth Individuals (HNIs)","seo_keywords":"A Few Tax Saver Investment Routes for High Net Worth Individuals (HNIs)","seo_description":"Individuals with a taxable income of ₹ one crore or above – High Net worth Individuals or HNIs – are entitled to a two percent additional surcharge. It was proposed by the Finance Act of 2015. Recently, the Budget 2019 introduced a broad 22 percent rise in surcharge rates for individuals with taxable income of more than ₹5 crores. The tax proposal has widened the tax bracket for HNIs to nearly 43%. These adverse Indian taxation policies on HNIs have made most of them look out for other ways to transfer their revenue sources and financial assets, particularly to tax haven countries.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945115/gzobph0lhlsw9nwsuf0l.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"145","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-5","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1630489577","published_date_view":"Sep 01, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 charts that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Valuation of Equity Market in India:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945334/tnyvtpo559xjtaawbokf.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 571px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Nifty 1 Year Forward PE Ratio is at 22.6. The ratio is closer to long term average.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Both Nifty and Nifty 500 companies have seen good earnings growth in the last 2 quarters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to good earnings growth, the overvaluation of equity market has come down considerably.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity Market is expensive but not in bubble zone.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Earnings Analysis for Q1 of 2019, 2020 and 2021:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945363/an7ewmoohjnfmbgsxtv9.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 374px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1) Net Sales in 2021 are back to 2019 level. We have lost 2 years of sales growth due to Covid.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2) Employee cost has gone up by 16% in last 2 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">3) Interest cost and fuel cost has fallen.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">4) Overall, profit has gone up by 34%</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) US Real GDP is back to the Pre-Covid Trendline:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945386/ny66mguvvzbxxemmxua1.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 808px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US economy has seen a super bounce back. The Real GDP is back to the pre-covid trendline.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India is going to come back to Real GDP trendline next year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US is now talking about spending additional USD 3.5 Trillion in Infrastructure.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US should hopefully do well in years to come.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Performance of IPO Companies in US:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945413/nvpvge5fdju3nphkwvme.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 638px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In US market, IPO boom happened few months back. Now most of the IPO companies are underperforming the broader Index S&amp;P 500.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Be careful about IPO euphoria.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Most IPOs comes at higher valuations and IPOs in the last cycle of bull run are definitely extremely overvalued.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Return on Investment &ndash; Simple but Powerful:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945438/a79mkzd74lfzurlwgfle.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1080px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Bonds deliver worst ROI but people feel most comfortable with it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Any money spent on Self Education, Relationships and Health delivers huge return. Don&rsquo;t think twice before spending money here.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945580/nkmusvacbb5rfxc4nulf.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_description":"Nifty 1 Year Forward PE Ratio is at 22.6. The ratio is closer to long term average.\r\n\r\nBoth Nifty and Nifty 500 companies have seen good earnings growth in the last 2 quarters.\r\n\r\nDue to good earnings growth, the overvaluation of equity market has come down considerably.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945578/lnk1zymsav2epzoiceyj.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"146","title":"Do-It-Yourself (DIY) Investing – Join the circus!!","slug":"do-it-yourself-diy-investing-join-circus","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1629279996","published_date_view":"Aug 18, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Let me share an interesting story with you all. It all started in 1973 when Princeton University professor Burton Malkiel claimed that a &ldquo;blindfolded monkey could throw darts randomly and select a portfolio that would do just as well as one carefully selected by experts.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Then in 1999, a chimpanzee actress named Raven&nbsp;rose to fame when her ten dartboard picks reportedly quadrupled the performance of the Dow and doubled the performance of the Nasdaq composite.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 2010, a&nbsp;Russian circus monkey&nbsp;named Lusha picked an investment portfolio that &ldquo;outperformed 94% of the country&rsquo;s investment funds&rdquo; to great acclaim. In 2013, Orlando the cat, a fierce new competitor, joined the rest of them in stock picking.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Hearing these stories added fuel to the lockdown boredom, powered by the rise of DIY platforms and trading apps. Thousands have started dabbling in the stock market actively. Most of them have made a killing from the one-way ride over the past 18 months.&nbsp; More often than not, many confuse this winning streak for talent. As a result, many investors prefer to invest directly in stocks.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, nothing lasts forever!! Consider the other side of the story of our dartboard investors.&nbsp; Where there is extra return, there&rsquo;s usually an additional risk. For instance, in 2000, when the trend in the market reversed, Raven faced severe losses than the professionals.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Here, I agree with Chris Sacca</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945696/e1tjieeacvbaa3htrx6h.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 515px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It makes the trick behind this dartboard investing clear. Any portfolio of randomly selected stocks from the universe is bound to include mostly smaller companies. Since small companies have more risk than the market as a whole, they were able to beat the market in the bull run.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Academia recognizes the small-cap premium (Fama French asset pricing model eloquently deconstructs it). Small stocks offer an extra return for taking the additional risk. These companies may not be well known, global, or well-capitalized. They often pay more for borrowing money.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">More often than not, bull markets are characterized by irrational exuberance. Psychological effects and speculation also play a prominent role in the markets. Typically, companies that are a few notches below in the quality curve run the fastest in a bull run.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If you are someone who is longing for experimentation and turning life experiences into learnings, then maybe this time around, you learn from someone else&rsquo;s mistake (and avoid making expensive errors yourself)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We simulated the dart-throwing monkey model for Indian market by randomly selecting stocks from the one listed on the exchange over 2015 till now. In the next step, we create equally weighted portfolio and repeat this exercise over different periods. Next, we compare the average return of the random stock portfolio with a portfolio of&nbsp; ten diversified mutual fund schemes and the market benchmark &ndash; Nifty 50.&nbsp; Results are offered in the table. Amazed? Shocked? Surprised? We all were.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945719/bwliecp28quvzranxvac.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 328px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">I would request your attention to 3rd row (Jan 2018 &ndash; March 2020), which was different from all the other periods and which highlighted the huge drawdown in random portfolio.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Till the time market rally continues, investors with a random portfolio may benefit. Still, as soon as the trend reverses, one should be prepared for the volatility to play out.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Another figure to note is the return 10 MF scheme portfolio offers for Jan 2015 till now. It will not be wrong to say that 10 MF scheme portfolio gives consistent return with lower volatility vis a vis random portfolio (as per expectations)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To cut a long story short, invest in asset classes that reflect your personal ability to withstand volatility. It&rsquo;s not about a choice of investing directly (DIY) or indirectly. Both approaches are not at odds with each other. You can do both focusing on how to derive maximum benefit. Identify gaps in the current portfolio and fill them with exposure to countries and sectors that the portfolio currently lacks. Current euphoria is scary; Play it safe, plan how you will act in a bear market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\nDr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Supported by Manjeet Singh for Data Analysis</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945791/k1paida8dppeyhyjz5ql.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Do-It-Yourself (DIY) Investing – Join the circus!!","seo_keywords":"Do-It-Yourself (DIY) Investing – Join the circus!!","seo_description":"Let me share an interesting story with you all. It all started in 1973 when Princeton University professor Burton Malkiel claimed that a “blindfolded monkey could throw darts randomly and select a portfolio that would do just as well as one carefully selected by experts.”","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687945789/f9vnyeuwpqmdydmy1cot.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"147","title":"Chak De India – Learn the ‘S’PORTfolio Rules!!","slug":"chak-de-india-learn-the-sportfolio-rules","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1628157026","published_date_view":"Aug 05, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Games have always been an essential part of our lives. Be it the Olympics, UEFA, or Cricket. Tokyo Olympics 2020 is the talk of the town. Indian Olympic Team is doing wonders, and our Indian Hockey Team, today defeated Germany to win an Olympic medal after 41 Years.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sports are essential &ndash; not only for physical fitness (which is very important) but also for imparting some key life lessons. It teaches how to be a team player, sportsmanship, discipline and the importance of consistency.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Stop staring at your portfolio.</strong>&nbsp;</span>When my inner sports enthusiasts meet the investor in me, I cannot help but observe simple principles common to both. In my young days, I would frantically scrutinize every game, player, and strategy. Similarly, in my initial days of investing, I would track my investment portfolio day in and day out in an attempt to time the market. Often, the fervent fan and a biased investor overpowered my rational thinking. The logic was left far behind, especially when faced with a loss.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Know your time horizon.</strong>&nbsp;</span>For any sportsman, the objective is to win. For any investor, the aim is to maximize return and attain financial goals. When players are picked up for a team &ndash; their past and current performance, track record, etc., are studied carefully. A choice is made based on the requirements of the different formats in cricket &ndash; ODI, T 20, or test match.&nbsp; Time horizon is critical. Similarly, some asset classes are best suited for a short time horizon and some long-term.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Diversify according to your goals.&nbsp;</strong></span>A look at our cricket team or football team would also underscore the importance of diversification in our investment portfolio. Each player has a role &ndash; its unique role to play in the game. (Remember the 2011 movie &ndash; Moneyball &ndash; how a baseball team is assembled using a computer-generated analysis to acquire new players &ndash; Watch it on Netflix if you have missed it). Similarly, the debt portion of our investment portfolio is for safety and capital protection; equity is for growth; gold is for hedging; cash and liquid investment is for liquidity. Solely relying on fixed income instruments will not give the best result in times of growth but when the market corrects, it is the debt instruments that provide a cushion to the portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Mental strength is important.&nbsp;</strong></span>A gymnast wins not only because of the strenuous physical training but also because of tremendous control over the mind and flexible body.&nbsp; One needs to be mentally strong when making investment decisions and not be swayed by emotions and biases. When an athlete runs, it&rsquo;s the speed, endurance, and patience that results in success. Like a marathon, investments often are meant for the long term, which requires patience, and often the investor gives up just before the finishing line. Reckless batting is never desirable &ndash; losing wickets could translate into losing the match too.&nbsp; Similarly, poor investment decisions might result in losses and even capital erosion. One should always make an investment decision based on thorough analysis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Be flexible.</strong></span>&nbsp;A player who can make changes in the playing style as per the changed format is the one who emerges victorious. Similarly, an investor needs to be flexible as per different financial goals and make asset classes choice. Changing economic and financial environment warrants an investor to review the decisions made in the past and be flexible in asset allocation. A good player should have the ability to hit sixes and consistent running between the wickets to win the game. A single strategy is not necessarily the best way &ndash; neither for a sports player nor the investor. One needs to be flexible in changing the game and making choices according to different time horizons.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">Continue that monthly SIP/ STP.</span>&nbsp;</strong>The ability to finish the race is vital. The winner will be the one who can withstand unfavourable situations and crosses the rocky/ bumpy road leading to the finish line with composure and not panic. A winner investor will be the one who is not going to lose sight of the financial goals during the market correction or heightened uncertainty (like the one we are facing in the COVID times).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&ldquo;The intelligent investor is a realist who sells to optimists and buys from pessimists.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>―&nbsp;</em><em>Benjamin Graham,&nbsp;</em><em>The Intelligent Investor</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Start early.&nbsp;</strong></span>In the game of cricket, an early catch often influences the final match result. On the same lines, an early start to investing also bears a considerable influence on the final corpus accumulated and how soon you attain your financial goal. An early start provides the scarcest resource &ndash;&nbsp;<strong><em>TIME</em></strong>&nbsp;(to see the power of Compounding, the 8th wonder)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Know your game well.</strong></span>&nbsp;Understanding the game &ndash; rules, strategies, environment, and participants will always work in your favour. Like a true fan, don&rsquo;t despise the game but live to watch it win</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, my dear readers, let&rsquo;s not be a sports fan who discards idol with every game and creates a new one. Just like one game doesn&rsquo;t define the player, one market slump cannot determine the credibility of the investment decision. It is over a period of time when the true character is shown. Do analyze long term performance, including at least one market downturn. Look for consistency in its performance and vis a vis peer. Only invest if it aligns with your long-term financial goal, not just because it is popular.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Congratulations to our Hockey Team and all of us. Cheers!!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\nDr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687946020/qfzskuoo1at8mmznwylk.jpg","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Chak De India – Learn the ‘S’PORTfolio Rules!!","seo_keywords":"Chak De India – Learn the ‘S’PORTfolio Rules!!","seo_description":"Games have always been an essential part of our lives. Be it the Olympics, UEFA, or Cricket. Tokyo Olympics 2020 is the talk of the town. Indian Olympic Team is doing wonders, and our Indian Hockey Team, today defeated Germany to win an Olympic medal after 41 Years.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687946017/g6yyjassjjbq3xiicuob.jpg","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"148","title":"Innovative Technology – The New Age Investment Hotbed","slug":"innovative-technology-the-new-age-investment-hotbed","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1627379634","published_date_view":"Jul 27, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Our world has been transitioning from the Industrial Age to the Information Age for the last few decades. The outbreak of the Corona pandemic has accelerated the pace of the transition for the better. Some of the prominent statisticians, economists and sociologists predict that our world will not be the same after the close of the pandemic days.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is certain that our world will undergo a greater transformation, and the worldwide macroeconomic conditions follow suit. Widespread digitalization, automation and the penetration of disruptive technologies will shatter the fundamentals of every traditional business model. This colossal shift in the economic paradigm comes with a great number of new investment opportunities. The field of innovative technology opens such a lucrative investment avenue.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Innovative technology, as the name suggests, is a new or improved product or process. The technological characteristics of the new or improved product or process are significantly different and capable of bringing radical transformation to its field of application.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the economic world, every enterprise competes to bring better value creation to the customers and innovation is the key to create value. Every enterprise in the whole world strives day in and day out to bring out new products or services to keep up with the competition in the market. The position of every business in the market is determined by the level of innovation they bring into the field. According to recent statistics, 84% of global business leaders place innovation at the number one position in their growth strategy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Globally, many industries, both small-scale and large-scale, have taken the plunge to invest heavily in innovative technology looking forward to a significant return on investment or ROI in the brave new post-pandemic world.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Here are some of the major areas of innovative technologies that offer safer bets with higher ROI.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Internet of Things (IoT)</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Internet of Things or IoT is an innovative technological space in its infancy that connects physical devices such as home appliances, automobiles, and sensors using data. IoT improves performance of the device, fuel efficiency, economic benefits and brings down human involvement in operating these devices.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The vast potential of IoT along with impending widespread usage of 5G technology has already been leveraged by most modern enterprises to simplify and automate most of their routine tasks. In 2020, this innovative technology has helped to generate an additional revenue of $344 billion globally and is currently witnessing an exponential rate of growth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Artificial Intelligence</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The unprecedented developments and exciting news in the Artificial Intelligence (AI) arena are making rounds for years all over the globe. Truth be told, a large number of small-scale and large-scale enterprises, all over the world, are chasing this innovative technology to boost productivity and profits.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 2018, AI has a global market value at $21.46 billion. It is expected to grow to approximately $190.61 billion by 2025 at a Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of 36.62 percent. According to a 2019 report by Data Science and Machine Learning Market Study, 40 percent of respondents related to marketing and sales professions believe AI will be a crucial part of their future business strategies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Robotic Process Automation (RPA)</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Robotic Process Automation or RPA is an innovative software technology that creates digital robots that emulate human behavior and response in operating software and digital systems. RPA, just like humans, can conduct various activities from systems navigation to data extraction, but with greater consistency, accuracy, and speed than humans.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The 2019 Pegasystems survey concludes that RPA accelerated digital transformation and turned businesses more profitable, adaptable, and responsive. No wonder major businesses and industries all over the world are striving to get a bigger bite of this innovative technology. It has been estimated that the implementation of RPA in the transport sector particularly as autonomous vehicles will revolutionize the way we travel.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Augmented Reality (AR) / Virtual Reality (VR)</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">While VR allows us to explore an entirely different virtual world with the help of computer-generated graphics, AR enhances the view of our current environment with the aid of computer graphics. Both innovative technologies have greater potential to transform the training system of most of the enterprises and enhance the learning experience offered by online classes and mobile applications. The Coronavirus outbreak has brought the relevance of the web-based online learning and mobile learning applications to the forefront and plays a significant role in the education of the future generations.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Blockchain</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Blockchain is an innovative technology that brings credibility to the transactions or exchange of value in the digital ecosystem without the need of a centralized authority. Many industries all over the world have already adopted blockchain technology into their business processes. Gartner, one of the leading global research and advisory companies, expects blockchain to create a market value of $3.1 trillion by 2030.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Social Networking and Collaboration Technologies</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Social networking and collaboration technologies have been transforming the way we communicate and interact for more than two decades. It also possesses the potential to transform our day-to-day interaction and business communication in the decades to come. In recent years, technological advancements have increased the number of collaborative tools with enhanced performance at affordable rates.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">These radical changes in the sphere of social networking and collaboration technologies have made it accessible to small and medium-sized businesses all over the globe. With increased mobility and centralized solutions, advanced social networking and collaboration technologies have the potential to improve business productivity and boost revenue.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Digital Health, Biotechnology and Genetics</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Health industry, along with greater growth potential, is also a recession proof sector. The recent advancements in digital technology simplified the collaboration and communication processes in the health industry.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Biotechnology &ndash; biology powered by technology &ndash; provides breakthrough technologies and devices to combat rare diseases, reduce carbon footprint, eliminate starvation, and impart safer, cleaner, and more efficient energy for industrial and domestic purposes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Genetics opens new avenues to cure various infectious diseases, beat the odds of life-threatening medical conditions, and tailor medical treatment for individuals using deeply researched and analyzed data from our genetic makeup.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">All these innovative medical technologies minimize health risks associated with once incurable diseases that affected millions around the globe and guard them from the side effects of modern medications. It also aids in creating more advanced medical devices for early detection of diseases, combat fatal illnesses and everyday health risks associated with millions particularly in the developing world.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>On-Demand Platforms</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On-demand platforms allow &lsquo;on (your) demand&rsquo; delivery of the products and services of your choice. Netflix, Uber, Zomato are among the few popular on-demand platforms available today. Hundreds of on-demand applications and platforms are being introduced every single day all over the world adding millions of users every year. On-demand platforms powered by innovative technological developments are breaking the conventional business models while opening new avenues for lucrative investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Justin Raj</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687946199/abmpt2zvjziop4ck3arm.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Innovative Technology – The New Age Investment Hotbed","seo_keywords":"Innovative Technology – The New Age Investment Hotbed","seo_description":"Our world has been transitioning from the Industrial Age to the Information Age for the last few decades. The outbreak of the Corona pandemic has accelerated the pace of the transition for the better. Some of the prominent statisticians, economists and sociologists predict that our world will not be the same after the close of the pandemic days.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687946197/opi9y1izpy1xdafxpceo.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"206","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (Research)","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-research-8","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1626777478","published_date_view":"Jul 20, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 charts that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><b>1) Current Yield Curve of Indian Fixed Income Market:</b></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035451/owkd05vz2kgf0gxttomf.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 441px;\" type=\"image\" />*Source &ndash; IDFC</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Yield on 1 Year AAA debt paper is at 4.21%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If we want to increase the yield then we have to either move to low quality paper like AA &nbsp;or have to increase the tenure of papers.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Both are dangerous right now because of expected rise in interest rates and expected increase in Non Performing Assets (NPA).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">2) Chinese Tech Companies to US Tech Companies:</span></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035505/fi1myzlqd9rizzaaiokn.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 681px;\" type=\"image\" />*Source &ndash; Compound</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Chinese Tech Companies to the US Nasdaq 100 has hit new all-time low.<br />\r\nValuation Gap between U.S. Tech Firms and Chinese Tech Firms have increased significantly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Chinese Tech companies have been affected due to regulatory crackdown. Hopefully, the correction in Chinese Tech Firms is temporary.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>3) Market Cap &amp; PE Ratio of Top 1000 Profitable Companies in India :</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035538/c8okewybb3j2lor1ltff.jpg\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 439px;\" type=\"image\" />*Source &ndash; Axis</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since Dec 19 (pre pandemic), market cap of 1000 Companies have grown by 50%</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Profits of these Top 1000 Companies have also grown by 48%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Despite huge rally in equity market, market is not extremely expensive due to increase in corporate earnings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>4) Nifty Earnings Growth:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035560/nw3joii3cs8u5hcyc83v.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 989px;\" type=\"image\" />*Source &ndash; ICICI Securities</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 2020-21, Nifty Earnings grew by 15%. In 2021-22, Nifty Earnings is projected to grow by 31%</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Increase in corporate earnings will help in reduction of overvaluation of equity market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Financial, Auto, FMCG, Metal &amp; Pharma companies are expected to do well</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">5) Equity Market is Full of Reasons to Sell :</span></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035591/hgbfpaiq2kfydo1qgktq.jpg\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 545px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">he above chart shows so many reasons since 2009 to sell equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Despite all the reasons, equity market keeps going up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Too much of information sometime dissuade investors from holding equity for long. Buy and forget your equity investment.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035747/sqyl8oxpyoa3fk7jydax.jpg","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (Research)","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (Research)","seo_description":"Despite huge rally in equity market, market is not extremely expensive due to increase in corporate earnings.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688035745/fe3ktltr0us2jw0o7gbv.jpg","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"150","title":"The Recent Drop in Chinese Tech Stocks and Investment Opportunities Hiding Behind It","slug":"the-recent-drop-in-chinese-tech-stocks-and-investment-opportunities-hiding-behind-it","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1626429845","published_date_view":"Jul 16, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On July 8<sup>th&nbsp;</sup>2021, a ruthless bloodbath was witnessed on Chinese tech stocks in broader Hang Seng Index sending it&rsquo;s ripples across stocks trading in the Asia-Pacific financial markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the afternoon trade in the Hong Kong stock market, shares of Tencent, Alibaba, and Meituan plunged 3.74%, 4.13% and 6.43% respectively. The heavy weight plunge also brought the Hang Seng Tech index to 7,321.98, a 3.71% drop on an index that represents the 30 technology giants with highest stock market exposure.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Japan&rsquo;s Nikkei 225 and Topix Index witnessed 0.88% and 0.9% decline, respectively. The Kospi in South Korea closed at 3,252.6 with a decline of 0.99%. MSCI&rsquo;s broadest index of Asia-Pacific shares recorded a 1.6% slump.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Major Chinese shares also bear the brunt of the bloodbath on Chinese tech stocks. The Shanghai composite fell to 3,525.50, taking a heavy 0.79% punch while the Shenzhen component collapsed to 14,882.90, a 0.382% decline.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The Trigger Behind the Recent Chinese Tech Stocks&rsquo; Drop</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The resurface of regulatory fears is cited as the cause of the recent drop in Chinese tech stocks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And, why do investors fear the new Chinese regulations on its tech companies?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">During recent years, technology giants like Tencent, Alibaba and Baidu have grown into some of the world&rsquo;s most valuable companies mostly through the loopholes of the feeble Chinese regulatory framework.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">But since 2017, China&rsquo;s foggy digital technology regulatory landscape has begun to transform when Cybersecurity Law was passed by the Chinese government.&nbsp; On June 10, 2021, the Data Security Law (DSL) was implemented by China with new rules on the collection, storage, process, and transfer of data by the technology companies in the country. To grant more control for users over their data, a Personal Information Protection Law is also underway in legislation procedure.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Data drives the technology industry and economic growth in the digital age. Chinese regulators keep a keen eye on the supervision of the domestic tech firms listed overseas, mainly because of data security and cross-border data leaks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Beijing&rsquo;s focus has very much been on the regulation of financial technology and to crack the monopoly of these technology players. The recent announcement of Beijing to step up the regulation over the Chinese listings in the U.S. stock market brought a heavy blow on tech companies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Chinese authorities, citing antitrust and data security concerns, have been bringing strict restrictions on its native technology giants over the last few months. The nullification of $34.5 billion worth listing of Ant Group and an antitrust penance worth $2.8 billion on Alibaba are some noteworthy events.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On Friday, 2nd of July, Didi Chuxing, a Beijing based ride hailing giant, was brought under regulatory investigation alleging that the company carried out illegal collection and usage of personal data. The Cyberspace Administration of China (CAC), rumoured to be a watchdog of Chinese President Xi Jinping, ordered the removal of Didi&rsquo;s mobile application from Chinese app stores.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">All these fateful events happened just four days after the shares of Didi had been ushered to the New York Stock Exchange, raising $4.4 billion in an Initial Public Offering that took the value of the company at $67.5 billion. On 6th of July, the regulatory action brought a massive decline of nearly 20% on Didi shares.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To add fuel to the fire, on Monday, 5th of July, CAC initiated a cybersecurity probe into Boss Zhipin, a US listed company, and Full Truck Alliance.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On 8th of July, all these perilous events gradually culminated as an abrupt collapse of the value of Chinese tech stocks in broader Asia-Pacific financial markets including Hang Seng Index.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The Good Investment Opportunities Hiding Behind the Recent Crash of Chinese Tech Stocks</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&ldquo;Predicting the future is difficult&rdquo;, says Alexander Davey of HSBC Global Asset Management. He urges the investors to look at the valuations of the tech companies with discipline. &ldquo;The timing is more important than the nerve of the investor. Fundamentally, it is a very strong business (technology)&rdquo;, Davey concludes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The boom and bust on the price levels is just the noise. The dubious concern over increased Chinese regulatory scrutiny is going to linger on for a short period. According to Alexander Davey, the technology companies with strong fundamentals offer buying opportunities whenever their stock prices drop amid investor fears.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In today&rsquo;s Information Age, technology drives the future of every enterprise. The technology stocks with strong fundamentals and their derivatives are highly performing assets in every portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Pros And Cons of Investing in Chinese Technology Financial Assets</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Every financial market crash offers greater investment opportunities only an investor with the right mindset can spot and profit from. Here, Alpha Capital brings to light some of the risks and rewards of picking Chinese technology financial assets to your portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Pros</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The Unique Macroeconomic Situation in China</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The prominent US based online platforms like Google, Facebook, Twitter, and YouTube are banned in China. This unique macroeconomic situation keeps the door of the Chinese market wide open for local online companies that provide services like ecommerce, entertainment, social media, and online content.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The lower penetration of most Chinese tech companies offers a lot of potential for growth. Today, China leads the world in online payments and is better equipped to transform itself to a cashless society than other countries in the world. The Chinese tech companies have developed more diversified revenue streams that can be more defensive in the future than their Western counterparts. Moreover, an unprecedented rate of growth of China&rsquo;s middle class set the growing user base for these online services.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Greater GDP Growth and Impressive Infrastructure</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to the World Bank, China showcased 10% average GDP growth since 1978 representing nearly 19% of the world&rsquo;s population. The infrastructure development in China is expected to continue at its current phase past 2030.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Growing Disposable Income</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The growing Chinese middle class increases the rate of disposable income in the country. IPOs issued by many rapidly growing Chinese tech companies on US exchanges provided them with the access to global investors that drove large chunks of investment capital to China.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Today, the Chinese tech giants may not be garnering enough media attention like Silicon Valley tech giants do, but in the near future, chances are high that the most valuable company in the world might be one of these Chinese tech giants.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Cons</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Trade Wars and Communist Regime</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Like some of the prominent global tech companies are banned in China, certain Chinese tech companies like Huawei and online services like TikTok have been banned in several other countries. This along with the ongoing trade wars between the U.S. and China poses investment risk in Chinese tech companies. The totalitarian, communist regime also raises concerns on the long-term economic growth of the country and its relationship with the world economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Low Standards in Bookkeeping and Accounting</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Low bookkeeping and accounting standards in China is a fertile ground for Ponzi Schemes, insider trading and financial frauds. This situation demands greater attention from the investor to conduct an in-depth study of the fundamentals of the tech company he plans to invest in.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Justin Raj</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687946849/dhwb5qpcceswyjecmrjr.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Recent Drop in Chinese Tech Stocks and Investment Opportunities Hiding Behind It","seo_keywords":"The Recent Drop in Chinese Tech Stocks and Investment Opportunities Hiding Behind It","seo_description":"In the afternoon trade in the Hong Kong stock market, shares of Tencent, Alibaba, and Meituan plunged 3.74%, 4.13% and 6.43% respectively. The heavy weight plunge also brought the Hang Seng Tech index to 7,321.98, a 3.71% drop on an index that represents the 30 technology giants with highest stock market exposure.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687946842/vslubbakfpnsjzk1knco.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"151","title":"Unicorns Knocking at the Dalal Street","slug":"unicorns-knocking-at-the-dalal-street","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1626170863","published_date_view":"Jul 13, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Be it the line-up of financial services, mouth-watering food companies, or the fashion labels&rsquo; ramp walk, or the debut of the financial behemoth LIC &ndash; the D-Street is witnessing all.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Zomato&rsquo;s much-awaited Rs 9,375 crore initial public offering (IPO) is lined up this week. Soon after, Paytm is planning to raise INR 21,800 Cr ($3 Bn) in an initial public offering (IPO).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">There is exuberance among investors looking to invest in desi unicorn startups to hit Dalal Street. Everyone wants to be a part of the new economy stocks growth story, which have an outsized impact in other countries.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For example, technology commands the richest valuations in the US and Chinese stock markets. However, these profitable companies are also decades-old (Amazon, Facebook, Alibaba, Tencent, et al.)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">But the picture will be incomplete if we miss noticing the likes of the UBER debacle. In India, IPOs of Reliance Power, DLF, Gammon Infra have all destroyed investors&rsquo; wealth in the past. Nevertheless, during this gloom and doom story, IPO of companies with solid business fundamentals have fared well in the markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947010/upw9ottirws2azfmqmnw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 705px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The present IPO avalanche has been triggered by a strong bull run in the Indian stock market.&nbsp;Increased liquidity, owing to money being pumped in by the central bank and the government, rising capital flows, and previous IPO success stories have contributed to this optimism.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In a bull market, people want to latch on to a good brand and have an exciting story. This, coupled with relaxed SEBI norms, has led to an IPO Boom, which is hard to ignore. Moreover, one can see an incredible increase in the number and size of issues globally.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947035/fvfu07ahjc2xm1apwh3p.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 660px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As this euphoria peaks, investors pay little attention to valuations amid a media frenzy, turning this IPO boom into IPO mania. Familiarity bias and herd mentality overcome the rationality while investing in IPOs. Retail investors hear, see these names day in and day out in the ordinary course of a day. Familiarity bias quickly leads to consumers becoming shareholders too. But it&rsquo;s essential to remember that not all companies are investment-worthy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">These days one is flooded with IPO news &ndash; newspapers, experts at news channels, emails, social media &ndash; essentially everywhere. It becomes increasingly difficult to resist participating in them. Fear of missing out (FOMO) and herd mentality catch up with the investor.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In a bull market, an increased number of IPOs leaves investors with hardly any time or resources to analyze offers. Not only this, the information access to the retail investor is limited.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A good company comes out with an IPO. It gets hugely oversubscribed, and allotment is not guaranteed for all retail investors (such a waste of time and effort). The word of caution for the investors is to not be lured with the mirage of listing gains.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947058/evqskb3sxqqujxogv4ux.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 744px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One should never forget that IPOs are never meant to be cheap. A team of well-qualified people out there is paid to sell the IPO to the investors at the highest possible price, thus making the odds of you losing your money much more elevated. Data highlights that the odds of winning to losing in IPOs are 40:60 for the last decade. As a result, value investors like Warren Buffet generally dismiss IPO as a gamble.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Always invest for the long-term prospects, looking at the fundamentals. And if the company is good, good opportunities will always exist post listing too. Either buy it in the secondary market post listing or invest in mutual fund schemes to benefit . Don&rsquo;t rush into an IPO.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Be mindful that whenever one invests in a new company, be it through a pre IPO, an IPO, or post-IPO, what determines returns is the Quality of Business, Growth prospects and Valuations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Zomato, in its DRHP, said it expects costs to increase over time. &ldquo;Our losses will continue, given significant investments expected towards growing our business.&rdquo; As a result, Zomato will have to be valued differently. Zomato and other startups (barring NYKAA) planning to list in the coming months are still in the phase where the companies are burning money. Up till now, these companies have been valued based on the future projections and hope to become profitable soon. But it may have to happen quickly to justify the stock market valuation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors might also change the lens while valuing such stocks. For example, Dalal Street has always approached stocks based on net profit, EBITDA, discounted cash flows, etc. However, absolute valuation metrics do not hold ground for loss-making new-age tech firms. Moreover, relative valuation is also challenging as hardly any tech companies are listed on Indian bourses to compare.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One of the most famous cases to be quoted in the startup space is AMAZON. It is the most competent example that shows that losses might lead to revenues<strong>.</strong>&nbsp;HBR mentions that Amazon trained its investors how to behave and taught Wall Street. Amazon was listed in its early stages; as a result, investors showed patience for more than two decades for Amazon to be profitable.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Because the Indian unicorns have existed for a reasonably long time, investors probably would not be willing to ignore the profitability for too long. The emergent need to evolve new parameters for valuing the new-age tech firms appropriately in the evolving scenario cannot be overlooked.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, how does one values a loss-making firm? The answer to this question can be found in the way private equity/ venture capitalists perform valuations. Several methods exist like &ndash; Berkus method, venture capital method and scorecard method.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947087/ce2lgk4pfqtmzgacvjsx.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 270px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Simply put, invest when you believe that in the long run these tech firms will graduate to a profitable, sustainable enterprise to survive and deliver returns to investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For assessing this, look at customer lifetime value (LTV), customer acquisition costs (CAC), the payback period on CAC (The money you spend at this stage will be made back over the lifecycle of each customer), average revenue per user (ARPU), repeat user rate, etc. makes more sense.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Unit economics is the new mantra &ndash; where the focus is on profitability on a per-unit basis. The point to note is that the new economy stocks are valued at multiple of revenues, not profits. Keep in mind the stage in which the startup company is for defining growth milestones. Look at the market potential (TAM/SAM/SOM, trends, drivers), competitive advantage (IP, partnerships, clients, competitors). Value of founding team, promoters is crucial &ndash;&nbsp; proven experience and commitment would impact its trajectory to success.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947109/susw9lxzcmnbrincukkt.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 613px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, my dear investors, whatever be the strategy, certain factors are imperative. Fundamentals are essential, whichever lens is used to value. Read the DHRP (though tedious), analyze the fundamentals (using any method you like), and be rational while investing (beware of familiarity bias and herd mentality). Identify IPOs to create wealth, not to destroy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\nDr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947217/ztxe7ex0iczc9btjqpzf.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Unicorns Knocking at the Dalal Street","seo_keywords":"Unicorns Knocking at the Dalal Street","seo_description":"As this euphoria peaks, investors pay little attention to valuations amid a media frenzy, turning this IPO boom into IPO mania. Familiarity bias and herd mentality overcome the rationality while investing in IPOs. Retail investors hear, see these names day in and day out in the ordinary course of a day. Familiarity bias quickly leads to consumers becoming shareholders too. But it’s essential to remember that not all companies are investment-worthy.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947214/xgdqjf5sfdzyijuy1agm.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"152","title":"Why International Investments Are Important In A Portfolio","slug":"why-international-investments-are-important-in-a-portfolio","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1625825657","published_date_view":"Jul 09, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India, being one of the world&rsquo;s emerging economies, represents only 3% of the international equity market. A portfolio with international investments gives the investor exposure to both developed and emerging markets. It also provides wider room for diversification.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What Is International Portfolio Management?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">International portfolio includes stocks, bonds, cash, or other portfolio assets in a foreign country purchased by a non-resident through a cross-border transaction. For instance, if an investor based in India bought shares in a Japan based company, it would be considered as a foreign portfolio investment. It is different from Foreign Direct Investment or FDI &ndash; a financing endeavour of a non-resident to an enterprise in a foreign country solely to obtain an ownership stake or some degree of business management control.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Why Foreign Portfolio Investment Important?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A well-designed foreign portfolio investment is very significant in today&rsquo;s highly volatile domestic and international markets. Every investment comes with a risk &ndash; both depreciation and volatility risks. An astute investor should take considerable effort to add additional wealth creation sources in his portfolio while diversifying the investment risk.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Foreign portfolio investment provides an excellent arena for both wealth creation and diversification. The global financial markets go through numerous yielding, stagnant and losing investment time periods spread across wide geographical areas and economic systems. It provides a wider room for risk management and wealth creation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Every single economy comes with a wide variety of investment opportunities. For instance, while Indian economy is dominated by Information Technology and Oil &amp; Gas, international markets like the US are driven by Artificial Intelligence, industrial automation, and block chain. So foreign portfolio investment provides the investor with a greater exposure to both old and digital economy themes. It also offers freedom to the investor for wider asset allocation.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Benefits Of International Portfolio Investment</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Here are some of the benefits of international portfolio investment worth considering before taking the plunge.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Mitigation Of Both Depreciation and Volatility Risk</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A well-diversified foreign portfolio mitigates investment risk. If the domestic assets in a portfolio underperforms, it can be compensated by the gains in the foreign investments in the portfolio. A good symmetry between assets from both developed and emerging markets in an international portfolio is a great hedge against the uncertainty in the domestic investment sphere.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Diversification of Currency Value Risk</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">An investor purchases stocks, bonds or other assets in an international portfolio using the currency of the respective country. For example, if an investor purchases shares in London Stock Exchange, he uses British Pound as the medium of transaction. Thus, the ups and downs of British Pound can bring volatility to the value of the stock he purchased. The volatility of the US dollar, in general, affects every international asset in a portfolio across the globe. The investments made in different currencies in different countries can mitigate currency value risk.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Varying Market Cycles</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Market cycles vary in different countries or economies. An avid investor who manages an international portfolio can take advantage of this varying market cycles. An investor who identifies market tops or overvaluation in US stocks or dollars can divert his investments to developing economies like Latin America or Asia. It can aid capital inflow and supply-demand factors in that economy as well.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>A Well-Diversified Portfolio</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Foreign portfolio investment offers a unique opportunity for the investor to diversify the portfolio assets on a global scale that, in turn, empowers the portfolio to achieve a higher risk-adjusted return. The macroeconomic factors that drive the financial markets all over the world vary at any given time. This factor gives lesser volatility for a portfolio with foreign investments than the one which focuses only on domestic assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>A Wider Credit Base</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A foreign portfolio investor has access to credit sources of the foreign countries in which he has investments. It can be greatly beneficial when his domestic credit sources turn expensive or unavailable. The availability of the credit determines the ability of a business to expand its operations and to invest in new projects.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Exchange Rate Benefits</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Currency exchange rates fluctuate every single second, seven days a week, 365 days a year, all over the world without a holiday. The currency rates can turn weak or strong in accordance with ever-changing global political and economic factors. A foreign portfolio investor can greatly benefit from the stronger currency exchange rate of the foreign country in which his portfolio operates.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>A Wider Market</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Wider the market, less the competition and volatility. Domestic markets are highly competitive as most of the companies offer similar products and services. On the other hand, foreign markets offer wider headspace for the investor and lesser competition for the companies that gives away greater opportunities for diversification.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Liquidity</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The easy buying and selling of an asset in a portfolio is carried out by the liquidity offered by the cash market. Higher liquidity boosts the buying power of investors. Foreign portfolio investors are blessed with higher liquidity offered by international cash markets. A ready cash flow enables a foreign portfolio investor to tap a profitable investment opportunity as soon as it arises.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Risks of International Diversification</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Nothing comes without a risk in the portfolio management universe. The trump card of an investor that determines the success or failure of his investments including international portfolio investment is his risk management skill.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Here are some of the risks associated with international portfolio investment and how to tackle it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>An Efficient Flow of Information.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The flow of information plays a critical role in an information age. Financial markets in developed nations like the US have very efficient information flow. As a result, active market funds, most of the time, fail to consistently outperform the benchmark.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Standard Poor&rsquo;s Index Versus Active (SPIVA) 2020 report states that active large-cap funds have underperformed the S &amp; P 500 for the past 11 years in a row. It not only brings greater risk of depreciation but also carries higher cost.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To eliminate the depreciation risk and bring down the transaction cost, passive investment products like Exchange Traded Funds or an ETF would be better suited as an asset in a foreign portfolio. Further, passive investments mitigate the fund manager risk that can result in underperformance. It also provides an opportunity for an investor to invest a large amount of money through mutual fund route or as little installments through Systematic Investment Plans (SIP) or Systematic Transfer Plan (STP).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Political and Economic Instability.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Political and economic scenarios change with the countries. Developing or emerging countries don&rsquo;t have the similar political and economic stability of developed nations. A political coup, civil war or a rumour of a Ponzi Scheme can bring 50% drawdown in an international portfolio. Many risk-averse investors can&rsquo;t tolerate the political and economic instability in many countries all over the world.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Higher Transaction Costs</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Higher commission and brokerage charges along with taxes, stamp duties and exchange fees should be paid by the investors when they buy and sell international financial assets in their portfolio. It can reduce the overall returns of the portfolio.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Again, mutual funds or ETFs come to the rescue. These financial assets can significantly reduce or eliminate higher transaction costs in an international portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">An investor who deals with foreign portfolio investment should be aware of his investment objective and risk profile. A fund that aligns well with an investor&rsquo;s investment objective and risk profile offers lower risk and higher returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Justin Raj</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947504/lfe3zqk6ktsglp3ebr1i.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Why International Investments Are Important In A Portfolio","seo_keywords":"Why International Investments Are Important In A Portfolio","seo_description":"India, being one of the world’s emerging economies, represents only 3% of the international equity market. A portfolio with international investments gives the investor exposure to both developed and emerging markets. It also provides wider room for diversification.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947501/ztusjxrpe9rxqznqeetr.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"153","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-4","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1625135042","published_date_view":"Jul 01, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please find below the 5 charts that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Top 50 Innovative Companies of the World:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687947984/bdzstwxebiwhwwbor8lb.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 2031px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Visual Capitalist</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Innovation is an important predictor of good return from a company in the future. High innovation leads to higher return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Chart shows the top 50 Innovative Companies in the World. These are the companies which carry high probability of doing well in the coming 10 years.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Price Changes for Different Categories:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948012/ipvuvcscdlb4wfm18wxt.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1263px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Marc Andreessen for US Data</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Medical, Education and Housing are 3 essential needs of everyone.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Unfortunately, Inflation is significantly high for all these categories.&nbsp;Growth in wage is not enough to match the inflation in Medical and Education.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We need Tech innovation in Medical and Education to reduce the cost.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Percentage of US Workers Quitting their Jobs:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948036/xnejwlxazel0qbw35mta.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 686px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Compound for US Data</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The percentage of workers in the US that are quitting their jobs is at the highest level.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As economy is opening in US, the workers are being asked to join back in office. Workers are preferring to quit then go to office.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Covid has permanently changed the way we work. This is negative for Commercial Real Estate and positive for Residential Real Estate.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) India&rsquo;s net FDI as a Percentage of GDP:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948068/kztzhx1brei2dcbndjpg.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 760px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; RBI</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">From 2014-15 to 2020-21, India&rsquo;s net FDI as a percentage of GDP exceeded 1.5% in five out of seven years whereas it exceeded 1.5% of GDP only once in the previous fourteen years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1.5% of GDP is not big but it is far better than our historical performance</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Global Central Bank Policy Rates:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948093/borlropjmcsnotydtspm.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1428px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Compound</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Brazil, Russia, Sweden, Denmark and Turkey have hiked the interest rates in 2021.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Interest rates are expected to go up for most countries in the next 12 Months.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Interest rate going up is good as it indicates growing economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We may see some volatility in equity market as hot money may flow out but this will be fundamentally good for markets in long term.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948216/webykfspf7naanuzywsc.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_description":"Chart shows the top 50 Innovative Companies in the World. These are the companies which carry high probability of doing well in the coming 10 years.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948214/quunrwquc1qfttypnp4h.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"154","title":"The Evolving Investment Demographics – Meme Stocks, Cryptos and NFTs","slug":"the-evolving-investment-demographics-meme-stocks-cryptos-and-nfts","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1624271507","published_date_view":"Jun 21, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2021 is not the typical regular year in any sense, much like its predecessor. The same can be said about the recent trends in the financial markets. Meme stock, meme coins, and NFT are the common parlance. Yet, surprisingly, none of these terms exists in the traditional finance theory.&nbsp; If you follow global financial news, for sure you have heard these terms. All of these have indeed become a fad and are inching up in the investment avenues ladder, despite tough competition from traditional asset classes like equity, debt, gold, etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948375/cq5zhkttxuago9zpnkre.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 675px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Though investing in them blindly may not be a wise financial strategy for most investors, learning about the phenomenon can help understand the risks associated with the stock market. Overlooking the impact of the new developments could potentially be an expensive oversight.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Meme (pronounced as &lsquo;meem&rsquo;) is ubiquitous in today&rsquo;s digital world. Social media plays a highly influential, dominant role in our lives, leading these memes to permeate our financial world. One can see several posts on Twitter, Reddit, and several other platforms relating to different stocks and other asset classes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Defining meme stocks is not easy (at least not in the same manner as growth and value stocks discussed in textbooks). Meme stocks are often characterized as overpriced and highly volatile stocks (high speculative interest). Their valuations are done based on the future potential and not the fundamentals in their true sense. However, what dominates everything else is the sentiment of the small number of players in the market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In short, meme stock would be any stock that can be artificially manipulated in the trading world. These stocks often find their place in trading-related posts on social media platforms, online discussion forums, news articles, etc., and popular among younger traders.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It will not be entirely correct to assume that all the meme stocks (probably some) are trash, not to forget the GameStop episode in Jan 2021. But, all of them are riding on media attention. These stocks&rsquo; attention is often due to their presence in the future relevant industry or a new visionary CEO. The problem with the meme stocks is often that the price changes soon outpace their fundamentals, attributed to two factors &ndash; inexpensive trading and online investing groups.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The trading volume explodes due to the social media frenzy. It brings to the forefront the power of the crowd, coupled with unprecedented coordination among the investor&rsquo;s actions. The undertone behind this phenomenon is the tug of war between small retail investors and big institutional investors, disrupting the power dynamics of the stock market, transitioning the power. It shows the amount of change that can occur when the 99% (small investors) band together against the 1% (institutional players). The belief that till the time like-minded small investors stick together, they&rsquo;ll be able to protect each other and the stock&rsquo;s price.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The best game plan for meme stock investing is identifying the difference between deserved hype and hot air.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, it becomes challenging when the celebrities support these meme stocks. Elon Musk, CEO of Tesla, has become the most significant influencer with his posts on Twitter. Brief History of Elon Musk&rsquo;s Recent Market-Moving Tweets &ndash;&nbsp; be it &ldquo;use signal&rdquo;; &ldquo;Gamestonk!!&rdquo;; &ldquo;Sandstorm is a masterpiece.&rdquo;; &ldquo;Ethereum&rdquo;; &ldquo;One Word: Doge&rdquo;; &ldquo;Dogecoin is the people&rsquo;s crypto&rdquo;; &ldquo;ultimate hodler&rdquo;; among others. (PS: HODL is not a typo &ndash; but means &ldquo;hold on for dear life&rdquo; in the crypto space)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This article would be incomplete without the mention of Dogecoin (Shiba Inu), a meme coin. It started as a joke, about a meme, with a dog in it on December 6, 2013. So why are we talking about it when there is Bitcoin, the largest cryptocurrency to discuss?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The main reason is that this meme coin has witnessed a rise of more than 800% in January 2021 in only 24 hours. As a result, it reached the highest price of $ 0.74 on May 7, 2021 (more than 13000% gain in 2021 itself) and was the fourth-largest crypto in terms of market cap.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948402/utj4kpq9yc1fen7numxf.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 661px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Source: coinmarketcap.com</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Don&rsquo;t you find it mind-boggling that an eight-year-old Dogecoin is as big as household names like ITC or Ferrari in market cap? Of course, it will be impossible to ignore the rise of cryptocurrencies, which is soon becoming a part of the everyday vocabulary of the millennials and many of the boomers (older generation).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cryptos are in vogue primarily because of the astronomical rise in their price and their growing utilities. For example, in May 2021, India received a donation of more than 50 trillion Shiba Inu coins. However, it led to a price fall and raised concerns among policymakers, who are already wary of cryptocurrencies. Moreover, there is a lot of skepticism around it in the absence of a stable legal framework in India. Therefore, it is expected that the Cryptocurrency and Regulation of Official Digital Currency Bill, 2021, will see the light of the day.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">I am sure cryptocurrencies often cross our minds when planning investments. But still, we disregard it either because we think it&rsquo;s illegal or due to lack of awareness. So at the outset, one should know that cryptocurrencies are not banned as an asset class but as a legal tender. Like all new trends, developments in the crypto space will be a thing to pay attention to and may tempt some to participate in the frenzy, but not blindly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Therefore, it is a good idea to acquire knowledge before testing the waters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Another buzzword is NFT, Non-Fungible Token, a new digital asset class that lives in the blockchain ecosystem. NFTs can be anything digital (such as drawings, music, tweet, and much more). Nyan Cat, the First tweet of twitter&rsquo;s founder &ndash; Jack Dorsey &ndash; on sale, are a few famous examples of NFTs. The use of technology to sell digital art contributes a lot to the emergence of NFT.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Art as an alternative asset class has often been incorporated into portfolios for diversification because of its low correlation with the equities market. But, the volatility, irrationality, and illiquidity of the art market make it hard to compare with more conventional investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As an investment opportunity, NFT, like any other speculative asset, makes sense only when considering its resale value, hoping the price will go up in the future. Thus, the payoff depends on the price you pay to acquire the NFT and how much more you can sell it for if at all you can sell it in the future. Globally, platforms like OpenSea, Rarible, Grimes&rsquo; choice, Nifty Gateway, etc. These allow people to buy and sell NFTs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Unfortunately, this is relatively a new investment avenue with no guidelines on how to value these NFT (how much a meme or a GIF, or a tweet is worth).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So dear investors, maybe it&rsquo;s time to get acquainted with the new members in the investment world &ndash; it may not taste for now, but it&rsquo;s good to be aware of the season&rsquo;s flavor. Always invest in what you know, enhance your knowledge, broaden your investment horizon, diversify your portfolio and limit your exposure. Those with a greater risk appetite may consider investing about 2-5% of their portfolio in meme-stocks or meme-coins. They are the future for sure &ndash; so may ride on cautiously!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\nDr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948502/kpvd0mwgwc7jabkfvf7h.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Evolving Investment Demographics – Meme Stocks, Cryptos and NFTs","seo_keywords":"The Evolving Investment Demographics – Meme Stocks, Cryptos and NFTs","seo_description":"2021 is not the typical regular year in any sense, much like its predecessor. The same can be said about the recent trends in the financial markets. Meme stock, meme coins, and NFT are the common parlance. Yet, surprisingly, none of these terms exists in the traditional finance theory.  If you follow global financial news, for sure you have heard these terms. All of these have indeed become a fad and are inching up in the investment avenues ladder, despite tough competition from traditional asset classes like equity, debt, gold, etc.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948499/t3pe7ttqwwyi1eey9tfk.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"155","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (15/6/21)","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-15-6-21","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1623753331","published_date_view":"Jun 15, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 charts that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Probability of Debt Outperforming Equity:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948656/fqm5wti3c42junifdrup.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 654px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Compound for US Data</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investing in Fixed Deposit, Debt Funds etc. gives mental peace. But they underperform equity significantly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 1 year, there is 30% chance that FD/ Debt Funds will beat Equity and the probability keeps falling every year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors should move out of their comfort zone and invest in equity if time horizon is more than 10 years.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Rally in Small Cap and Mid Cap:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948678/kimbhlqgh0wd9nlej1ct.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 652px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Ngen for Indian Equity</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Small Caps and Mid Caps have done phenomenally well in last 1 year with return of more than 100%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, since Jan 2018, Small Caps and Mid Caps are still trading below Large Caps.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Seems like more steam for upward rally is left in Small Caps and Mid Caps.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Fall in US Equity Volumes with Opening of Economy:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948700/wdhejdjarcfs7xrbayec.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 597px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Bloomberg</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity Volume in US has been falling continuously as economy has been opening.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">People are now stepping out from their homes for holidays, shopping and work.&nbsp;They have less free time for stock market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This trend will most probably also play out in coming months for India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) State wise Registered Stock Market Investors in India:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948722/l0co8nk3lbtdnjkgmw4p.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 795px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Finshots</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Only 6.9 Crores Indians are investing in the stock market. This is 5% of India&rsquo;s total population.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So many people are missing on wealth creation through Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">West and South India have more equity investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) What is the right Time Horizon for Equity?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948747/jqxobenddkg656y17omh.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1211px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Deutsche Bank for US Data</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to the above chart, the right time horizon is atleast 10 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Chart shows annual real returns by decade for the US Market for the last 200 Years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Three decades show negative real return: 1910-19, 1970-79 and 2000-09</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Decade of 2010-19 was one of the best.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948849/qx5lfaf7mmgiyg4vrfrt.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (15/6/21)","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (15/6/21)","seo_description":"Investing in Fixed Deposit, Debt Funds etc. gives mental peace. But they underperform equity significantly.\r\n\r\nIn 1 year, there is 30% chance that FD/ Debt Funds will beat Equity and the probability keeps falling every year.\r\n\r\nInvestors should move out of their comfort zone and invest in equity if time horizon is more than 10 years.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948847/o8xkq6zvynigwsyhshis.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"156","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-3","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1622630461","published_date_view":"Jun 02, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5&nbsp;charts&nbsp;that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Relationship of Inflation and Portfolio Performance:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687948976/jfvx0rttaxmozxuoz1tk.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 582px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; JP Morgan for US Data</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Everyone is worried about rising inflation and its impact on investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per US Data,&nbsp;in rising inflation, all investments do well. Emerging Market Equity, REITs, Gold etc all give good return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Inflation is good for investors but unfortunately bad for poor people who have to pay higher for buying food and goods.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Real Estate Prices and Inventory of homes:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949003/p5o5a5ddy2fseynf99mt.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 764px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Real Estate Prices are hitting an all time high.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Lot of Investors in India are expecting a similar trend for India.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Residential Inventory for sale is running at an all time low since 2000.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India has huge unsold residential real estate inventory. Will take ~4 years to liquidate</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Ratio of Sensex Market Cap to BSE 500 Market Cap:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949055/eqpxmfngp68sdfyxvnsh.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 616px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; SBI AMC</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sensex dominance has been reducing lately and we are seeing a broader market rally. Hopefully, this will continue.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This plays well for Mid Cap and Small Cap.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This also explains the Alpha generated by Fund Manager</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Economy and Stock Market have cycles:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949081/qtzkjuwyqnn3nwhragwj.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 554px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Compound</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In different phases of market, different type of stocks and strategies work.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A single theme or strategy is always not right. Its important to change portfolio and strategy based on the change in market cycle.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Expected increase in Interest Rates:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949106/a2tvpc5rdckcjzdkdzzm.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 630px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Indian 10 Year G Sec is expected to move to 6.5% from current yield of 6% by March 2022.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As RBI winds up liquidity measures provided for pandemic, yields will start moving up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949204/pci2zyrtkrsy7fq5ylil.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_description":"Everyone is worried about rising inflation and its impact on investments.\r\n\r\nAs per US Data, in rising inflation, all investments do well. Emerging Market Equity, REITs, Gold etc all give good return.\r\n\r\nInflation is good for investors but unfortunately bad for poor people who have to pay higher for buying food and goods.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949202/rbzrueob5i3mppyvyh6g.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"157","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-2","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1621334822","published_date_view":"May 18, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 charts that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Stock Market and Economy are two different things:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949347/qhyfjqalghu7x9qxzcze.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 582px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">*Source &ndash; Motilal Oswal</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The overlap between the Stock Market and Economy is less. If you see businesses around affected due to Covid but stock market going up, then primary reason for same is that lot of businesses listed in stock market are not affected due to Covid.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Correlation of Stock Market vs Other Asset Classes:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949376/auietr2wyzwdktbwpu1j.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 523px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">*Source &ndash; PGIM</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Commodities and REITs which used to have low correlation with Stock Market in the past, have now become significantly correlated with Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Only Bonds and Gold have negative or no correlation with Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The correlation between asset classes continues to change with time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Movement of Nifty, Mid Cap and Small Cap since Jan 2018:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949398/tpjfmij4j6ldbooaglu8.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 469px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">*Source &ndash; Motilal Oswal</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Despite huge rally for Small Cap in the last 1 year, they are still trading below the level of Jan 2018.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">From valuation perspective, Small Cap is still attractive for investment.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Movement of Core Inflation in the US:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949428/ytfabqhzcp4heqhnkjp4.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 715px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">*Source &ndash; Compound</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Core inflation in the US has moved up to ~3%, its highest level in the last 25 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Is this inflation transitory due to pent up demand after lockdown or this is structurally long term? This is the single biggest question which will determine the future direction of equity market in US and India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Drawdown in Bitcoin:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949449/bgyn7ngyodtvlzergirm.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 556px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">*Source &ndash; Coindesk</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Bitcoin Price has fallen from ~64000 to ~44000 which is a drawdown of 32%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Historically, drawdown of 30% is common for Bitcoin and a correction of 90% also happens sometimes. There is no gain without pain.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Take care and stay safe.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949536/vcf9jpwkxmylcnkhpmlr.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_description":"The overlap between the Stock Market and Economy is less. If you see businesses around affected due to Covid but stock market going up, then primary reason for same is that lot of businesses listed in stock market are not affected due to Covid.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949534/kwrgkqswgzmxqwne9cuh.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"158","title":"Beware of the Infodemic – Your Attention Matters!","slug":"beware-infodemic-attention-matters","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1621248747","published_date_view":"May 17, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The pandemic has made way for the concurrent burgeoning of the infodemic. And this infodemic is more severe at times. Infodemic usually means excessive, irrelevant, unreliable information that spreads rapidly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investor&rsquo;s attention to information is an essential factor in learning and decision-making processes. Limited cognitive resources hinder human thinking capacity and lead to continuous tension among the multiple information channels competing for limited mental resources.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949605/yloopl0zkymnamf2ml24.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 563px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Limited attention acts as a critical source of friction in financial markets.&nbsp; In this infodemic, it becomes challenging for an investor to process the information rationally and make decisions (as we expect in theory). Thus, challenging the foundations of the established economic and financial theory, rationality in the decision making.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For the traditional models to work, investors must update his/her belief accurately on receiving new information. &nbsp;Investor&rsquo;s inattention to the relevant news may result in underreaction. For instance, the frog-in-the-pan hypothesis states that investors under-react when small amounts of information arrive in the market relative to large quantities of information arrival.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Focusing on these cognitive and emotional aspects helps in investigating actual financial behavior and is vital for success. An important question to be asked is &ndash; Whether the popular news is relevant news or not. Is it just the media attention driving investment decisions? Is the return on any investment asset the result of new information being conveyed?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One strand of theoretical literature also explores the&nbsp;<strong>no-media premium</strong>. With less visibility and less media coverage, neglected stocks often earn more than the recognized stocks to compensate their investors for being imperfectly diversified.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is easy to gauge investors&rsquo; attention by looking at the google search volumes and trends. Investors exhibit &lsquo;limited attention&rsquo; behavior, and financial intermediaries predict this behavior and exploit it.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">More often than not,&nbsp;<strong>familiarity bias</strong>&nbsp;is at play. Even if international investing options (with noticeable diversification gains) are available, the investors prefer &lsquo;familiar&rsquo; investments of their own country, region, state, or company.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With an influx of information and misinformation, the&nbsp;<strong>Gambler&rsquo;s Fallacy</strong>&nbsp;plays out, where investors see patterns where none exist.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So dear investors, you may follow the following tips for surviving this pandemic as well as the infodemic (which may be more damaging than the pandemic itself, causing panic)&nbsp; that is all around us:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Do not spend too much time on social media, and do not believe in any unverified information.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Keep up with the basics and know that common sense trumps everything else. There is no secret known only to the lucky few privileged ones hiding it from the rest of us.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Being hyper-focus on a specific investment class or security within narrow frames is not the best way to make financial decisions.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please do not violate the principle of fungibility when it comes to money. To say money is fungible means that all money is the same regardless of its origins or intended use.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Beware of mental accounting &ndash; treating money obtained from salary and capital gain differently is illogical.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Do not forget the&nbsp;<strong>Stock Dale Paradox</strong>: Balance the realism (Get vaccinated) and optimism (This too shall pass). The simplest explanation of this paradox is hoping for the best and acknowledging and preparing for the worst.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Your attention is valuable &ndash; spend it wisely!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\nDr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949702/cpfjf55dt49bqgipbb41.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Beware of the Infodemic – Your Attention Matters!","seo_keywords":"Beware of the Infodemic – Your Attention Matters!","seo_description":"Limited attention acts as a critical source of friction in financial markets.  In this infodemic, it becomes challenging for an investor to process the information rationally and make decisions (as we expect in theory). Thus, challenging the foundations of the established economic and financial theory, rationality in the decision making.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949699/bpgn4leod1efdrnsndh8.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"159","title":"YOLO – The New Investment Mantra??","slug":"yolo-the-new-investment-mantra","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1620298511","published_date_view":"May 06, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The mood is sombre all around us. Life has changed a lot in past few months. Death is no more an abstraction for most of us, it has hit us very closely by impacting our near and dear ones. People across all age groups, and more recently the younger ones, too are getting severely impacted by the pandemic. We all plan and invest for the future &ndash; our future, our children&rsquo;s better future. Is the heightened uncertainties, like the one being witnesses currently, calls for changing the plan?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The idea of FIRE (Financial Independence, Retire Early), originated in the 1990s, adhered to delayed gratification. The individuals of this thought process saved roughly about 50% of the monthly income for 20 -30 years to meet their goal of creating a sufficient retirement corpus. This need is different for each individual based on current income, geographic location, the investment mix (faith in the stock market!).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949822/epr6m9w85mjlrqkhqywj.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 846px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The pandemic has brought in extreme uncertainties, the approach of YOLO (You Only Live Once) is the new mindset. The focus has shifted from the destination to the journey. People want to live their best life NOW instead of reaching the magical number of 60 (retirement age in India). So, does it imply that we all should shun the FIRE approach? We should take expensive vacations, go to fancy restaurants, buy the latest iPhone, splurge on luxury cars, etc. (Of course, after the lockdown)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Unfortunately, the answer to this question is not so straightforward. As per the statistics, roughly about 20% of the population in India will hit the conventional retirement age of 60 by 2050. When it comes to preparedness for the same, most people rely on their children to provide them the necessary financial support. Typical investments done in retirement planning by an average Indian are in the PPF and NPS, with few looking into alternative avenues. However, rising inflation rates, coupled with declining interest rates, present a challenge for the investors. Time is running out for the young and old alike when it comes to retirement planning. The combined assets under management (AUM) of the National Pension System (NPS) and Atal Pension Yojana increased to 33.09% year-on-year (y-o-y) to touch ₹5.59 trillion as of February 2021. As of the end of February 2021, the total subscriber base was at 4.14 crore, up from 3.40 crore in February 2020 (a y-o-y increase of 21.85%). Sadly, it&rsquo;s not enough.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949851/wpvwa2z6f5b4aqpisnxw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 540px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Government of India&rsquo;s recent announcement to cut the interest rates on the small saving schemes should act as a premonition for reduced rates on these instruments in the future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687949876/qfavipusjzesm628uw2o.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1064px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is clear that in this dynamic and challenging environment, one can achieve nirvana only by following the middle path.&nbsp; Instead of ditching the FIRE in its entirety, embrace the FI &ndash; financial independence.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">FIRE may not be for everyone, but YOLO cannot be the answer for everyone! Some may perceive early retirement as freedom, but others may not. Work is not always about money but also a part of our identity and our role in society.&nbsp; But securing a financial future, having financial freedom, and physical, mental, and emotional well-being is essential for everyone.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Few key takeaways to achieve the desired Financial Independence &ndash;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Wealth is a function of our spending habits. Take control of the amount of money you spend. Remember small amounts matter &ndash;&nbsp;<em>The</em>&nbsp;<em>Latte effect. T</em>he small amount of regular discretionary expenses is burning a hole in your wallet. Analyze how much you spend in a month on that daily coffee, eating out, amazon purchases and unused subscriptions, etc. Reducing these expenses might help you contribute positively towards the environment too. This connection between wallets and environmental conservation may be a good motivation to begin.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Do not underestimate the power of compounding. Use your financial resources efficiently. Make your money work with you. The sooner you start, the less amount you have to save overall.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Be financially disciplined, not necessarily frugal. Avoid owing money to your future self.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One cannot over-emphasize the importance of being financially literate, irrespective of age, gender, and occupation.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Have a well-diversified investment portfolio. Intelligent investing along with discipline is sure shot a recipe for success. Take cognizance of the changes in the risk-taking ability, tax structures, inflation, riskiness of the asset class, new emerging investment avenues.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the end, it&rsquo;s all about balancing &ndash; having a good life while preparing for a safe and secure future. Live life to the fullest &ndash; spend time with family, take care of physical and mental health. Have the financial breathing space to live life on your terms &ndash; shopping, traveling, painting, starting a business, working part-time, or doing something you enjoy. So my dear investors, &lsquo;you live only once&rsquo; may seem an attractive thought in present tumultuous times, but if you are Financially Independent, trust me, you&rsquo;ll live every day!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Taunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950029/prmuuzro0wucd6p11vzd.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"YOLO – The New Investment Mantra??","seo_keywords":"YOLO – The New Investment Mantra??","seo_description":"The mood is sombre all around us. Life has changed a lot in past few months. Death is no more an abstraction for most of us, it has hit us very closely by impacting our near and dear ones. People across all age groups, and more recently the younger ones, too are getting severely impacted by the pandemic. We all plan and invest for the future – our future, our children’s better future. Is the heightened uncertainties, like the one being witnesses currently, calls for changing the plan?","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950027/i5zkalpeslkqifnoc6lb.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"160","title":"Pandemic Lessons – Investment Hygiene & Portfolio Sanitisation","slug":"pandemic-lessons-investment-hygiene-portfolio-sanitisation","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1619434878","published_date_view":"Apr 26, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950145/ag0fvynxlyg0jbuq14p4.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 720px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The Covid catastrophe seems to be far from over &ndash; the so-called second wave across the country is creating havoc. The surge in Covid cases has led to the health systems reach saturation level. The fear of a lockdown and its impact on business activities has been visible in the recent plummeting of the stock market.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And with the recent surge, the rebound in economy seems delayed and slow. However, like last year and always, it would be best for the investors to not panic and sell off their equity portfolios. A longer-term investment horizon is required to reach the desired returns. On the contrary, it is an excellent time to invest in equity on the days of significant fall.&nbsp;Like 2020, equities, fundamentally, will bounce back.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Our economy has shown signs of resilience always. We will reminisce about 2020 as the year coronavirus took over with devastating effect on human lives. Covid-19 has triggered a change in our way of life, augmented many existing trends and kick-started new ones.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This backdrop of Covid further heightens the requirement of prudent financial planning. Portfolio should be structured on the basis of risk profile, aspirations, cash flows etc of the family.&nbsp;A good financial planning helps with optimal mix of Equity, Debt, Real Estate and Alternate investments &ndash; a perfect balance of safety, liquidity and return.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The need and importance of insurance for risk management is high. Sadly, in India, insurance is still sold as a financial product rather than being bought by people to protect against uncertainties. The Economic Survey 2020-21 shows that insurance penetration (premium as a percentage of GDP) continues to be at a dismal level of 3.76 per cent in 2019, a marginal increase from 2.71 per cent in 2001. Insurance becomes a priority only when one experiences the uncertainties in life first hand, up and close, which is very common in the present times. Be it simple term insurance or medical insurance; it will be wise to safeguard aspects of health and life.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A perfect hedge for an emergency, approximately equal to 12 to 24 months of expenses &ndash; should be invested in fixed income products which has high liquidity. With economy expected to recover this year, demand for goods will go up, this will lead to higher inflation and interest rates. In rising interest rate scenario, its better to stay invested in Debt funds which have maturity of upto 1-2 years. Avoid Fixed Deposit/ Bonds/ Debt Funds with a longer tenor. The amount can be reinvested at a higher rate as the interest rate goes up in next 6 months to 18 months.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It has become challenging for the investors to navigate through this bygone year, with certain tendencies creeping in the investor behaviour. It&rsquo;s essential to sanitise the portfolio based on the risk appetite and investment horizon. Equity exposure should be as per asset allocation policy. Revisit the asset allocation of portfolio and make changes as per variances. Have diversified equity exposure across International, Large Cap, Mid Cap and Small Caps. Move away from the higher risk debt funds and move towards more stable debt funds with higher-rated papers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Being emotionally strong, with Covid all around us, is most important. At times, not doing anything and staying put also is an intelligent thing to do. We do not have to react to every volatility of the market at all times. Let the world and situations around us subside; investments are there to grow &ndash; sometimes at a rapid pace and at times a bit tepid. Avoid herd behaviour, bring rationality in most of the decisions taken in such scenarios. You are a different investor from others in the market. The investment horizon, return expectation, risk appetite, etc.&nbsp; is all different for each investor.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So my dear investors, in the current uncertain times for the world, it is critical to maintain investment hygiene for sustenance in the long run. Clean and sanitise your portfolios, keep your distance from high-risk investments and if you are prone to herd biases, quarantine yourself from the markets on days of high volatility! When it comes to investment decisions,&nbsp; the bygone year has brought to the forefront the need for financial portfolios that can help navigate the tough times with ease.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Stay Safe &ndash; both you and your monies!&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;<br />\r\nDr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950205/vhhj5shh9zulkeqq0hch.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Pandemic Lessons – Investment Hygiene & Portfolio Sanitisation","seo_keywords":"Pandemic Lessons – Investment Hygiene & Portfolio Sanitisation","seo_description":"Being emotionally strong, with Covid all around us, is most important. At times, not doing anything and staying put also is an intelligent thing to do. We do not have to react to every volatility of the market at all times. Let the world and situations around us subside; investments are there to grow – sometimes at a rapid pace and at times a bit tepid. Avoid herd behaviour, bring rationality in most of the decisions taken in such scenarios. You are a different investor from others in the market. The investment horizon, return expectation, risk appetite, etc.  is all different for each investor.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950203/c5qusk8kp1yjk98jlgd2.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"161","title":"No More Taper Tantrums, Please!","slug":"no-more-taper-tantrums-please","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1616497415","published_date_view":"Mar 23, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The recent surge in US-yields has been spooking the equity and debt markets &ndash; bringing back the memories of 2013. It&rsquo;s a feeling of deja-vu, and the scare of the return of taper tantrum!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To understand this, let&rsquo;s take a quick relook of 2009-2013 financial-economic scenario.&nbsp; The US Federal Reserve executed Quantitative Easing (QE) (made large purchases of bonds and other securities) in response to the Global Financial Crisis of 2008-09. This policy pumped up the liquidity in the financial sector and maintained stability to promote economic growth. The stability in the financial sector encouraged lending, consumption and investment in the economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Tapering, on the contrary, means gradual reduction in the amount of money the Fed pumps into the economy. Taper Tantrum, was last witnessed in 2013, when the US Fed&rsquo;s announcement that it would taper its massive bond-buying programme that had been on since the global financial crisis led to a sudden sell-off in global stocks and bonds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950306/qxguzybro4ghremvvv3k.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 1138px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This triggered capital outflows and currency depreciation in many emerging market economies that received large capital inflows. This episode earned the nickname taper tantrum. Taper because the Fed decided to taper its quantitative easing program, and tantrum because of the short-lived angry reaction of the investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The recent scare of &lsquo;taper-tantrum&rsquo; seems to have overtaken the pandemic crisis as the top most risk that is alarming the investors across the globe. The trade-off between inflation and interest rate, is a perpetual conundrum to solve for all central banks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And US Fed is no different. With the rising inflationary expectations, the US FED have may have to tighten policy sooner than planned. This expectation has triggered a widespread sell-off in government bond markets &mdash; which investors worry could get worse.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The US 10-year Treasury yield, one of the world&rsquo;s most closely watched interest rates, has risen past 1.6 per cent, up from 0.9 per cent at the beginning of the year, as investors sold the debt.&nbsp;Meanwhile, the 10-year break-even rate, a key measure of inflation expectations, now sits near its highest level since 2014.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950328/hdfgojkdoeljvxabojh8.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 657px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With this spike in US yields and rising inflationary expectations, traders have worried about a repeat of the taper tantrum of 2013. The post-Covid period was marked by massive fiscal spending and substantial monetary easing by the US and other economies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">But as expectations of a stronger economic recovery have gained ground, inflation in commodities has been rearing its head. The possibility of inflation has also fuelled concerns that the US Fed will have to reverse its quantitative easing and raise interest rates sooner rather than later. This has given rise to the possibility of a new &lsquo;tantrum&rsquo;. The chart below depicts that the emerging markets have been spooked at the very thought of the new &lsquo;tantrum&rsquo;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950351/ynm3zmc2qyty0agcptw6.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 606px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India, too bears the brunt of any such policy development in the US. The last time when US Treasury yields rose sharply in 2013, it triggered an outflow of capital from emerging market economies spread over several months beginning in May 2013.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In India, foreign institutional investors pulled out money from both equities and bonds leading to rupee depreciation by over 15 per cent. This had forced the RBI to raise interest rates to prevent the capital flight.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the current times as well, with a massive government borrowing plan lined up for 2021-22, an oversupply of government bonds without a commensurate demand for them has pushed up G-sec yields. The inflationary concerns (rising crude prices) and the possibility of appropriate policy action (such as a rate hike) by the RBI are fanning the fears.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the 2013 taper tantrum, the impact on the stock market was short-lived. This time, the markets seem overvalued and investors fear that the rise in yields can become the trigger for a prolonged market correction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Nonetheless, investors need not panic. It&rsquo;s important to embrace the volatility &ndash; both in equity and debt markets. Rising interest rates will benefit the short term debt instruments as the coupon will rise So, stay invested. Our Indian economy is rebounding on robust fundamentals to a sustained growth trajectory &ndash; those who stay in the markets &ndash; will surely be the ultimate gainer in times to come!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950432/n1kiaamvuco1gmzbazvi.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"No More Taper Tantrums, Please!","seo_keywords":"No More Taper Tantrums, Please!","seo_description":"To understand this, let’s take a quick relook of 2009-2013 financial-economic scenario.  The US Federal Reserve executed Quantitative Easing (QE) (made large purchases of bonds and other securities) in response to the Global Financial Crisis of 2008-09. This policy pumped up the liquidity in the financial sector and maintained stability to promote economic growth. The stability in the financial sector encouraged lending, consumption and investment in the economy.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950430/aqizco8dhznd1dxbdkwn.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"162","title":"Equity & Debt Market Volatility – Stay Put to Win","slug":"equity-debt-market-volatility-stay-put-to-win","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1615892840","published_date_view":"Mar 16, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&ldquo;You only have to do a very few things right in your life so long as you don&rsquo;t do too many things wrong.&rdquo; &ndash; Warren Buffet</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At times it is smart to stay put. To not move. To do nothing. In a soccer penalty shootout, there is a 33% chance each that the shooter hit the ball to the right, left or straight. If the goalkeeper jumps in anticipation on either side, there is little probability to save the goal. However, if the goalkeeper decides to stay put, there is a 33% chance he saves the goal!!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As investors, we can learn from this situation at times. In times of high volatility, like the current prevailing situation, it may be prudent for the investors to just stay put. Do not stop the SIPs, do not enhance the SIPs, do not do bulk profit booking, do not switch funds. The short run volatility and the after effects of the pandemic will gradually ease out and the economy will track back on a sustainable growth path. At both equity and debt markets, the investors can take it easy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The recent capital flight from the Indian stock markets can be attributed to rising US yields. This was primary driven by rising commodity prices and fear for rising inflation.&nbsp; However, investors must stick to the current allocation across equity and debt to tide over the volatility &ndash; all asset classes have temporary blips and changing asset classes without much rational thinking can be catastrophic to the targeted return goals. At times staying put &ndash; sticking to the long run though &ndash; pays stronger.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950532/d7obpbvkkesxbtsbv4hv.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 606px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is critical to stay cautious both on the equity and debt parts of the portfolio. On the equity front, stay invested for a long term &ndash; the markets seem bullish in the next few years. Book profits gradually and make entry at dips. However, excessive profit booking may also not be advisable. Where will the fresh funds be parked in the current economic scenario? An already high stock market or a debt fund at in a rising interest rate scenario or a fixed deposit earning about 5%?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The impending effect of rising inflation could be the reason that most believe. As&nbsp;growth comes back not just in India but globally, inflation is being seen to rise.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950555/yutppgkesxeflzqqmvia.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 701px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rising yield (or falling bond prices) happens when bond investors dump existing bond holdings in expectation of high-interest rates in forthcoming bonds. For growth, the government needs funds and often resorts to borrowing from the market to meet the shortfall. Higher borrowing programme of the government is the main reason for upward movement in yields.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, if the spike in the yields continues in near future, it may be better for investors to shift funds within the debt fund category. &ldquo;Investor who require the money in the next 6 months to one year, can look to redeem from the high duration products and invest in low duration products.&rdquo; First-time investors can consider investing in mutual fund schemes in the ultra short term, Low duration and money market category.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Major sources of return for a debt fund are accrual (the interest component) and mark to market (MTM) valuations, done regularly.&nbsp; As yield level moves up, valuations are adversely impacted on an immediate basis. Overtime, accrual moves up too. A longer horizon helps in absorbing the MTM losses, allowing the interest rate cycle to take a full circle and even out the interim volatility. As per the expectations, interest rates will rise over the next year or so, short maturity debt is preferred over the long-term debt.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The important question here to be asked is how long investment horizon is long enough??&nbsp; Unfortunately, there is no one correct answer. However, as a ballpark, investment horizon equal to the portfolio maturity is thought-out as safe.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So dear investors &ndash; focus on the quality of your portfolios &ndash; both equity &amp; debt, do nothing till the volatility eases out, and stay invested for a longer tenure to reach the targeted return.&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950614/nxa722kl1rv3ka1qfqy5.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Equity & Debt Market Volatility – Stay Put to Win","seo_keywords":"Equity & Debt Market Volatility – Stay Put to Win","seo_description":"At times it is smart to stay put. To not move. To do nothing. In a soccer penalty shootout, there is a 33% chance each that the shooter hit the ball to the right, left or straight. If the goalkeeper jumps in anticipation on either side, there is little probability to save the goal. However, if the goalkeeper decides to stay put, there is a 33% chance he saves the goal!!","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950612/vwgckdprcrjyjjmvhic0.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"163","title":"Let’s bond with the Bonds !!!","slug":"lets-bond-with-the-bonds-india","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1613473916","published_date_view":"Feb 16, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The equity markets are at all-time highs &ndash; Nifty breached 15300 while Sensex crossed the 52000 mark. The equity markets are being propelled on strong budget response for infrastructure push and structural reforms, calibrated support from RBI to maintain sufficient liquidity in the system along with increased global inflows that have boosted the confidence in the Indian equity markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Though this is great news for equity investors and they continue to reap benefits of the high returns, it becomes critical for a prudent investor to not get complacent in such &lsquo;opportune&rsquo; times. It is the right time to rejig portfolios and ensure appropriate diversification across asset classes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The bonds markets or debt funds have performed well in last couple of years as the interest rates were on a downward trajectory. RBI has been slashing the repo rate (currently at 4%) to support the dwindling GDP growth and infuse in the liquidity in the economic system.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, now as signs of normalcy begin to appear with respect to the pandemic receding, an active vaccination drive, favourable macro-economic indicators, a sharp rebound and sustainability in the GDP growth is expected. And with this, the interest rates are expected to move with an upward bias in months ahead.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Budget 2021 brought in a reality check for the bond markets &ndash; the government announced borrowing plans for financial year 2021-22. Even in the recent Monetary Policy Committee meeting, though the rates were kept constant, it was hinted that the interest rate may start moving northwards in the next financial year in view of stable growth, rising inflation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">RBI has also hinted towards orderly normalization of liquidity by phased increase in cash reserve ratio by 100 basis points to 4% by May 2021. This should gradually lift the yields up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950908/zrw78f69anj9sx70o5wq.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 809px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As the global economy enters a new phase of its V-shaped recovery central bankers and policy makers anticipate a faster return to pre-covid GDP path. Emerging markets growth is likely to rebound on the back of both domestic and external tailwinds. Against this backdrop, the chart below depicts the expected movement of inflation and repo rate in the next few quarters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950938/ycuyfmcfyoqfpndwvr7o.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 829px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">But that does not mean we start parting way with the bond funds. As we expect interest rates to move up gradually (and prices to go down), why should we bond with the bonds? Because it&rsquo;s a good buying opportunity at dips.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The interest rate movement is cyclical &ndash; so the long term investors need not panic &ndash; just realign the return expectations for the coming few quarters. Investors may move towards the short term bond funds &ndash; as interest rate move up these funds will benefit from the regular churning of the funds with high interest rate papers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And as the upward interest rate cycle stabilises, the investors can lock-in for high rating (AAA) long term bond funds &ndash; by locking in a higher coupon rate. Investors in bond funds need not panic &ndash; they must hold on till the investment horizon. New investments in the long term bond investments may be avoided for the time, however, shorter term bond funds should provide the adequate diversification from equities.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This season of love, my dear investors, we must bond with the bonds&hellip;for this bond provides more stability and lasts longer!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950997/eeveikrychv3cpyf4nlh.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Let’s bond with the Bonds !!!","seo_keywords":"Let’s bond with the Bonds !!!","seo_description":"The equity markets are at all-time highs – Nifty breached 15300 while Sensex crossed the 52000 mark. The equity markets are being propelled on strong budget response for infrastructure push and structural reforms, calibrated support from RBI to maintain sufficient liquidity in the system along with increased global inflows that have boosted the confidence in the Indian equity markets.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687950995/xymbl2ld1whmfyqay3tz.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"164","title":"Is Gold Really a Shining Investment?","slug":"is-gold-really-a-shining-investment","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1612955803","published_date_view":"Feb 10, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The year 2020 was the year of Gold and Covid 19; Gold was glittering with the increasing Coronavirus cases in India and across the globe. In early 2020, we experienced a new high of Gold price and slump of equity market due to lockdown, Indo-China face-off, job losses etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951071/vi3sbzckrkfbyzilm4yu.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 605px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If we talk about Gold, Indians are sensitive about this precious metal. They are overly attached with it. As per India&rsquo;s customs, Gold is part of every important ceremony or occasion. But the question that arises is, whether gold as an investment is still a shining asset?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Before delving deeper to discuss the comparison with other asset classes, let us discuss the factor affecting the prices of gold.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The global factor that affects the Gold price is&nbsp;<strong>global uncertainties</strong>, which refers to political or geopolitical uncertainty across the world.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Central bank monetary policy</strong>&nbsp;has a strong impact on Gold prices. Central banks such as the US Fed, ECB, and Bank of Japan, as they are key players of global economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Similarly, the&nbsp;<strong>economic growth</strong>&nbsp;of the developed nations affects the movement of gold prices.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The&nbsp;<strong>movement of currencies</strong>, specifically the US Dollar, since the price of gold is dollar denominated, is another strong influencer. There is an inverse relation between dollar tendency &ndash; as the value of a dollar strengthens, the gold prices fall globally and vice-versa.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Demand from ETF</strong>: ETFs are more than likely the smallest influencer of gold price but still account for a very sizeable share of demand for gold. Whenever there is a spurt in demand for gold ETFs, we have seen gold prices soar.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Apart from the above, as per India&rsquo;s context, the following factors impact the gold prices in India:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951093/ohfcxsirshsp80ac5wvz.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1150px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>Source: World Gold Council</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above picture is self-explanatory &ndash; increasing population, rise in income, changes in inflation rate and increase in rainfall are the factors that affect the gold price in India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>We have conducted some analysis of gold prices and Sensex. The figure below shows the movement of gold prices since 1963.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951131/lawfzlrdirf2rogyglxq.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 665px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The comparison of gold prices with BSE Sensex since 1980:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951181/odksozcevmgitgp8qlzk.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 463px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*As on 29<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;Dec 2020</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart-bar shows gold prices (LHS), and the yellow line (RHS) reflects the movement of BSE Sensex. But, if we go through the exponential trendline of both, Sensex is growing exponentially compared to gold prices.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>If anyone invested in both the BSE Sensex and gold prices of Rs. 1 Lac each, the value of the investment would be as follows:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951223/c1ikv9shuoezjys2wgu5.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 463px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*As on 29<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;Dec 2020</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 40 years, the investor had gained 10% and 16% CAGR in gold and BSE Sensex respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The volatility chart of gold prices and BSE Sensex:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951250/jlas1qh2xv9s7vvbgfxs.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 476px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*As on 29<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;Dec 2020</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per the chart, it can be clearly seen that Sensex is more volatile than gold movements. Despite of volatility, the BSE Sensex bounced back much faster than the gold price and have given higher returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The thumb rule of investment is to diversify your investment in different asset classes as per the risk profile and tenure of investment. Gold as an investment does not shine as equity, but while preparing a financial plan, some portion of the gold asset can be considered for child marriage. Further, the investment should be in ETF, gold funds and gold bonds instead of physical gold</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951360/mfmvdmzprrottvavrx06.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Is Gold Really a Shining Investment?","seo_keywords":"Is Gold Really a Shining Investment?","seo_description":"The year 2020 was the year of Gold and Covid 19; Gold was glittering with the increasing Coronavirus cases in India and across the globe. In early 2020, we experienced a new high of Gold price and slump of equity market due to lockdown, Indo-China face-off, job losses etc.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951358/datvdyqqmnm97y7cjdge.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"165","title":"Sensex Skyrockets – Is the Melt-Up Prelude to the Big Meltdown?","slug":"sensex-skyrockets-is-the-melt-up-prelude-to-the-big-meltdown","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1612783392","published_date_view":"Feb 08, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">What a historic week it has been for the Indian Stock Markets! So many firsts&hellip; Sensex has zoomed past 51000, Nifty has breached the 15000 mark, market capitalisation of BSE-listed companies crossed the historic Rs.2 lakh crore.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The two major events of the week &ndash; the Union Budget FY 2021-22 and the RBI Monetary Policy &ndash; both acted as a catalyst to the already buoyant investor behaviour in the stock markets. Sensex has jumped from 40000 to 50000 in just about three months. And over 5% since the Budget earlier in the week.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">From the lows of March 2020, the stock markets have shown sharp recovery and indicating towards the trust and confidence on India&rsquo;s sustainable and robust long term growth story. The post pandemic rebound is expected to be the highest and sharpest for the emerging economies- with India leading the foray. The chart below shows the journey of the Sensex over the years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951451/kd3bbzauhfzue8m0oiwv.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1001px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A V-shape sharp rebound is visible from the chart above. Also, the Indian economy is staging a V-shaped economic recovery. It may be seen that each sharp upturn is followed with a steep slide as well.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, is this euphoria sustainable? Is it completely attributed to the plush liquidity available within India and outside in the global economy? Is it truly supported by strong fundamentals of the economy? Is such high volatility the new normal? Or does this melt-up a big indication for an upcoming meltdown?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Melt up is a financial term that refers to a sharp improvement in the performance of the stock market due to reasons other than fundamental improvements in the economy. The improvement in investment performance is mainly driven by investor sentiment, where investors flock into buying stocks because they notice the market rising, and they do not want to miss out on the opportunity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Although most investors may be tempted to profit from the rising positions in the stock market, they should also understand that such movements last in the short term and the rising performance would be followed by a meltdown. Investors who let melt ups influence their decision are driven by emotions, and it is best to focus on doing due diligence to understand the actual value of an investment.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As &nbsp;investors, let&rsquo;s make hay while the sun shines. There is absolutely no second thoughts that the impetus announced by the government in the budget along with appropriate support from RBI will ensure a stable growth path ahead for our economy. So, we may not witness a melt-down per se, but what we may witness are few corrections coming up in the market, but that should be more of an opportunity to enter this long run rally.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The long run threats &ndash; inflation, political instability, economic factors, etc may cause a blip but are more than overcome by the strong robust positive factors working for the economy. Pandemic situation seeming under control, mega economic packages from the Government (Atmanirbhar Packages &ndash; over 29 lakh crore) during 2020, the strong impetus announced in the budget with focus on growth revival, strategic support from RBI to ensure plush liquidity in the system, improving high-frequency indicators&ndash;inflation, rural growth, pick up in exports, PMI, GST and tax collections, green shoots in capex cycle &ndash; point to strong macro recovery ahead.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So my dear investors, capitalize on the existing rally to book gains. Though, for a long-term perspective, it&rsquo;s better off making decisions based on market fundamentals. It is critical to analyze both qualitative and quantitative data to evaluate the financial health of a company and the economy before parking the funds for a longer term. Be it short term or a longer term, it seems investors in India have a long night for party ahead!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951536/eq2uc8yjl1miwgd5gonh.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Sensex Skyrockets – Is the Melt-Up Prelude to the Big Meltdown?","seo_keywords":"Sensex Skyrockets – Is the Melt-Up Prelude to the Big Meltdown?","seo_description":"The two major events of the week – the Union Budget FY 2021-22 and the RBI Monetary Policy – both acted as a catalyst to the already buoyant investor behaviour in the stock markets. Sensex has jumped from 40000 to 50000 in just about three months. And over 5% since the Budget earlier in the week.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951533/jtmrudm8dhz9nhn3szrz.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"166","title":"Union Budget 2021 – Impact on Economy, Markets and Investments","slug":"union-budget-2021-impact-on-economy-markets-and-investments","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1612437999","published_date_view":"Feb 04, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Union Budget 2021 presented by Finance Minister on 1<sup>st</sup>&nbsp;February, 2021 has created a bang on the stock market. Sensex has moved up from 46388 to 50255 which is a growth of 7.2%. Budget has definitely created a huge euphoria in the stock market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In this article, we are not going to take you through the details of Union Budget as same has been already covered exhaustively in newspapers, media etc. However, we will tell you about important implications of budget, what are the risks, how it is going to affect various investment and what is the suggested strategy for investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Union Budget of 2021 is the first budget of the decade and the first after once-in-a-century global pandemic. It holds importance because it lays roadmap for recovery of economy after contraction of 2020.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Positive Implications:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Privatization of Public Sector Banks</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Government has decided to privatize two public sector banks. After 51 years of bank nationalisation, the government has finally admitted that it should not be in the business of running all public sector banks. According to us, this is going to be the single biggest reform from this budget.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On 16/1/2021,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://alphacapital.in/blog/warning-from-rbi-tsunami-of-bad-loans-in-2021/\">through an article</a>, we had written about the expected Tsunami of bad loans in 2021. We had talked about solution to this problem being either privatization of banks or capitalization of banks by Government.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Privatization of public sector banks is in the right direction because it will help the banks to raise money from the market on their own and it will reduce their dependence on Government for money. Also, this will decrease the financial burden on Government and will also help in credit offtake from the banks for investment in the economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Intent of privatization is very good. The challenge will be in implementation of this reform. Government will see resistance from the union of bank employees and also from opposition political parties.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Increase in Capital Expenditure &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Government has decided to increase capital expenditure by ~26% in comparison to last year. Government expenditures are of two types &ndash; Revenue and Capital. Revenue expenditure is for the normal running of the Government services, interest charges on debt, subsidies and so on. Capital expenditure is the part of spending that goes into the creation of assets like roads, bridges, dams, railway lines, airports etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Capital expenditure is considered to be of good quality. As per RBI study, capital expenditure has a multiplier effect of 3.25 which means that every rupee spent on capital formation induces an increase in the GDP output by Rs. 3.25.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Following chart shows historical trend of revenue and capital expenditure:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951668/lokp5d85hn9chz9mogyp.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 364px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that revenue expenditure will reduce from 87.3% in 2020-21 to 84.1% in 2021-22 and capital expenditure will see meaningful increase.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The decade of 2011-20 was one of the slowest for India. One of the primary reason for same is that after the great financial crisis of 2009, India decided to provide consumption stimulus to economy in the form of MGNREGA (Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act&nbsp;), farm loan waiver etc. The trend continued for many years despite economy coming out of the woods. Because of continued higher spending on consumption, the investment for new assets creation was impacted and accordingly employment also took a hit. Also, this was one of the reason for consumption stocks doing do so well since 2009. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The budget of 2021 plans to reduce consumption expenditure towards MGNREGA by 34.5% and in PMAY (Pradhan Mantri Awas Yojana) by 32.1%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With expected revival of capex cycle, companies connected with infrastructure and domestic manufacturing are expected to do well. &nbsp;&nbsp;Companies related to cement, steel, metals etc are hopefully going to deliver good return going forward.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) No significant change in direct and indirect taxes &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Due to Covid stress on economy, everyone was fearful that Government will increase tax in the form of Covid Cess, Wealth Tax or Inheritance Tax. &nbsp;Thankfully, Government has not made any significant changes in personal and indirect taxes. This has led to better consistency and clarity. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We have always believed that Government should reduce taxes as this will help to reduce black economy, increase tax coverage &amp; buoyancy, increase consumption and reduce migration of HNIs out of India. Government has not reduced tax but thankfully they have not increased tax.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">From 1<sup>st</sup>&nbsp;April 2021, Employee provident fund contribution of more than 2.5 Lacs per annum will attract tax on interest income. &nbsp;This was tax exempt till now. This has made EPY relatively less attractive. However, pre tax return of 8.5% and post tax return of ~5.7% is still better than other fixed income avenues. So investors can continue with the same. However, its suggested to revisit your asset allocation policy and plan for incremental investment in EPF &amp; Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For ULIP Insurance policy with premium of more than 2.5 Lacs, the maturity proceeds will now become taxable. This makes Insurance for investment unattractive. Insurance is always good for risk coverage and accordingly term plan should be taken for same. Investors are suggested to avoid using Insurance for investment.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Important announcements but needs to be watched:&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Creation of Development Finance Institution (DFI)&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; Government has announced creation of a Development Finance Institution (DFI) for infrastructure financing. The plan is to lend Rs 5 lakh crores over the next three years through this DFI.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One of the key reason for pile up of bad loans in banks is that they were made to lend to long term Infrastructure projects. There was asset liability mismatch. Banks get money through short term deposits, so they are not suitable for lending to infrastructure projects which have tenure of 10-20 years. Banks are more suitable for retail and working capital lending.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">DFI is a good solution for infrastructure financing but the problem is that in India we have tried DFI experiment in the past and have failed miserably. IDBI, IDFC, IFCI and IL&amp;FS are some of the DFIs which have failed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A big problem with DFIs is that they suffer from lending due to Crony Capitalism (Favourable lending due to advantageous relationship between business houses and government officials).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So what is special about the proposed new DFI. As per finance minister, the new DFI will be professionally managed. We are going to watch this carefully and hope that it indeed gets professionally managed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Creation of Asset Reconstruction Company or Bad Bank:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Government has announced creation of Asset Reconstruction Company(ARC) which will be set up to take over the existing bad loans (NPAs) of PSU banks, manage them and sell them to alternate investment funds and other potential investors. The details about creation of this ARC is yet to become available.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This can be a good move if new ARC can have right professionals who can focus on making high recovery from NPAs. This can also free up employees in PSU Banks to focus on better lending. Again, right implementation of ARC is they key here. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Government Borrowing Plan:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 2020-21, the tax revenue collection has significantly fallen and to finance the expenditure, Government has increased the borrowing significantly. The fiscal deficit for 2020-21 is projected to be at 9.5% of the gross domestic product (GDP). This is the highest fiscal deficit figure between 1970-71 and now. For 2021-22, the fiscal deficit is projected to be at 6.8%. (Higher than expected)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Fiscal Deficit as percentage of total Government expenditure</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951692/xgnsizz38hlksyo4chng.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 648px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above charts shows that out of total money spent by Government, ~54% will be borrowed money for 2020-21 and ~43% for 2021-21. Long term average is around 35%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Supply of the bonds in the market for borrowing by Government:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687951711/ixgcrxqp2abaphmrqxhx.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 523px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart clearly shows huge increase in borrowing by Government through bonds since 2020. Ideally, this should have led to increase in interest rates. But this has not happened due to support from RBI in the form of loose monetary policy and printing of money to buy Government Bonds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Movement of Interest rates in future will depend on support from RBI. As economy recovers, RBI will be gradually winding up the monetary support which it had given in 2020 due to Covid crisis. However, we feel that RBI will continue to support Government borrowing program and most probably will ensure that there are no sudden spikes in interest rates. High Interest rates will increase interest cost for Government and will further lead to higher fiscal deficit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We will get more visibility about RBI support in the next Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) meeting which is scheduled to be held on 5<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;February 2021.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;We need to be careful about following Risks:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The fiscal deficit reduction plan proposed by Government is stretched. Government is planning to bring fiscal deficit down to 4.5% by 2026. This means that Government plans to run high borrowing plan for a long time. &nbsp;This will lead to high Debt/GDP ratio.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To support high borrowing plan, RBI will have to run loose monetary policy and print money to buy bonds for long. This is definitely going to be inflationary. &nbsp;If inflation &amp; interest rates goes up and growth does not oblige, then we are going to fall in a big debt trap. Hopefully, good GDP growth will come if plan is executed well.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We will need global support in the form of low interest rates, FDI inflow and FII inflows for smooth execution of the plan. Any external shock like taper tantrum of 2013 can create problems.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Impact on Equity and Debt:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to us, the budget is a good plan on paper which has been made with good intentions. The key to success is smooth execution of the plan. If the plan is implemented properly and without delay then we can see a good boost to the GDP growth of India and significant increase in corporate earnings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Equity:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity markets should do well if the execution happens as per plan. Revival of capex should lead to cyclical sectors doing well. Companies connected with infrastructure and domestic manufacturing are expected to do well. Banking and PSU stocks have recently gone up with expectation of privatization and credit offtake.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity Funds which use value strategy and invests in cyclical sectors should hopefully start performing now.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A big challenge for equity market is high valuation. Market is expensive and carries high risk of correction on negative news.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its suggested for investors to stick to their asset allocation plan and keep doing profit booking with every rise in markets.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Debt:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2020 was a good year for debt market as they benefited from falling interest rates.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We are now at the bottom of interest rate cycle. Due to huge borrowing plan from Government and expected inflation, the yields will have upward pressure.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Fixed income will see some volatility in short term due to rise in interest rates. But from long term perspective this should be fine, as increase in interest rate will lead to better return from debt.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors are suggested to stay invested in short end of the yield curve and avoid long term bonds or debt funds.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its suggested that within debt, the focus should be on very high quality portfolio. No compromise should be made on quality as bad loans are expected to rise in 2021.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We are keeping our fingers crossed and hoping that the proposed plans in budget are implemented. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687952588/jyql2eufcfwrnnh1yo5n.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Union Budget 2021 – Impact on Economy, Markets and Investments","seo_keywords":"Union Budget 2021 – Impact on Economy, Markets and Investments","seo_description":"In this article, we are not going to take you through the details of Union Budget as same has been already covered exhaustively in newspapers, media etc. However, we will tell you about important implications of budget, what are the risks, how it is going to affect various investment and what is the suggested strategy for investors.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687952585/iqrisrdexi4mrmbtk4mv.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"167","title":"Warning from RBI – Tsunami of Bad Loans in 2021","slug":"warning-from-rbi-tsunami-of-bad-loans-in-2021","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1610970226","published_date_view":"Jan 18, 2021","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity market has been seeing a fantastic rally since March, 2020 and the rally has been continuing in 2021 as well. We all know that the primary reason for equity rally has been global liquidity which is due to huge stimulus from US and other countries.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We also know that there is a huge disconnect between stock market and the economy. Covid-19 and the consequent lockdown had a devastating effect on economy. &nbsp;The GDP declined by 23.9% in Q2 of 2020. Thankfully, Indian economy has been seeing a good and better than expected recovery.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One unsolved puzzle has been that despite lockdown, negative growth in GDP and businesses being hit significantly, we have not seen loan defaults and banking crisis. The pertinent question before us is whether there is any impending risk in our financial system.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>In 2020, two important developments happened for banking sector. They were as under:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">RBI allowed restructuring of loans for everyone by offering moratorium (Postponement of payment)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Supreme Court on 3/9/20, directed the banks that loan accounts which hadn&rsquo;t been declared as a bad loan shall not be declared as one, until further orders.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to above developments, recognition of bad loans by banks was postponed and the banking crisis was avoided. However, this was only postponed to future and someday it was supposed to come back to hound us.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The time of reckoning came sooner than expected when recently (January 11, 2021), RBI released Financial Stability Report (FSR). The FSR report is an important and exhaustive report on health of economy and financial sector.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The key takeaways from report are as under:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Gross bad loans on bank balance sheets could rise to 13.5% by 30th Sept, 2021 as compared to 7.5% in September 2019.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the worst case scenario, the gross bad loans could rise to 14.8%&mdash;Almost double the size of the current bad loans.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In absolute numbers, total bad loans as of March, 2020 stood at ~Rs. 9 Lac Crores.&nbsp;<strong>It is expected that bad loans will double to ~Rs. 18 Lacs Crores by September, 2021.</strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At aggregate level, banking sector will be able to handle the stress. But at individual level<strong>, 5 Banks won&rsquo;t be able to meet the regulatory minimum requirements and will come under stress.</strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>RBI projection of bad loans:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687952718/cc8mws8lsnji2nwbddfb.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 619px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source : FT</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The bad loans becoming double to ~Rs. 18 Lacs Crores and some of the banks coming under severe stress are big red flags and we need to be careful about them. Would also like to highlight that in the past, RBI has been conservative in predicting the bad loans. Actual number of bad loans have been higher in most of the times.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>So what does this means to investor. According to us, following are the implications for investors:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><u>1) GDP Growth</u>&nbsp;&ndash;</span>&nbsp;</strong>Because of huge bad loans, the banking losses will increase. Banks will have to do provisioning for these losses from their capital. This will lead to reduced equity capital and will hence reduce the credit off take (Giving of loan) by banks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to weak balance sheet of banks, the banks will not be in a situation to give loans to corporates for new projects. This will slow down the investment in economy and will lead to slow down in GDP growth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Similar situation has been playing out for India since 2014. Due to significant bad loans, banks have slowed down in giving out loans to corporates for investment and this has been one of the primary reason for slow GDP growth in last 7 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The solution to this problem is that either Government should capitalize the PSU banks or privatize the PSU banks. Both of them are not happening as Government doesn&rsquo;t have enough money to capitalize the PSU banks and they don&rsquo;t want to privatize the banks because they run various social loan programs through PSU banks and also because it&rsquo;s a political issue to privatize the banks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Overall, bad loans will impact GDP growth in years to come for India. Investors should keep this in mind when setting up expectations of return from Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong><u>2) Fixed Income/ Debt</u></strong>&nbsp;&ndash;</span> Since bad loans are expected to go up, we may see defaults from corporates, NBFCs and even banks. So investors have to be very careful about their debt portfolio. Next few years, investors should not chase higher return on debt portfolio and should only focus on high quality. Investors should contend themselves with lower returns from fixed income investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At Alpha Capital, we believe that for debt portfolio, investors should not touch any fixed income product which is yielding 1% more than your bank FD return. Of course, there can be exceptions when risk return reward is in favour of the investor. Our experience, has been that&nbsp;<strong>&lsquo;There is no free lunch&rsquo;</strong>. If someone is offering even 0.1% extra return on debt then it comes with some additional risk. Its important for investors to understand and analyse the products carefully.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Accordingly, following is suggested for various fixed income products:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>a) Debt Mutual Funds &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>Its suggested that we stay invested in only those debt mutual funds which have very high quality portfolio. We did a lot of restructuring for all clients between March and May of 2020 within debt portfolio to ensure that we exit all funds with risky papers. As of now, we are in very good situation and we have ensured that our debt portfolio is safe and very high in quality. Going forward, we are going to further closely monitor this space because sometimes even very high quality papers become junk (Example &ndash; IL&amp;FS, DHFL, Yes Bank etc).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>b) Bank Fixed Deposits &amp; Bank Balances &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>These are mostly safe but Latin phrase&nbsp;<strong>&lsquo;Caveat emptor&rsquo;</strong>&nbsp;which means&nbsp;<strong>&lsquo;Let the buyer beware&rsquo;</strong>&nbsp;is more valid here. 10 years back, the perception was that anything which is backed by Government is safe and that Government will always protect investors. But now the narrative is changing. Government is now asking investors to read the documents carefully.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the case of Yes Bank AT1 Perpetual Bonds, Rs. 8415 Crores of bonds became Zero for investors when Yes Bank went into restructuring. When this was challenged in Chennai High Court, then the RBI in its affidavit categorically stated that AT1 Bonds had the feature of its value becoming Zero in case of trouble in the Bank and the same was communicated to the investors. Hence, the bank was not liable to pay the investors for any kind of loss.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per RBI, bank fixed deposits and bank balance is protected by insurance of upto Rs. 5 Lacs. Anything beyond this is at risk. Now this amount will only come at risk when the underlying bank comes under stress and defaults. Government in the past has communicated that it will protect bank depositors. But keeping &lsquo;Caveat emptor&rsquo; in mind, it is suggested that investors should stay away from banks which are under stress or are expected to come under stress in future. These banks normally offer higher return on bank balance and fixed deposits. Its fine to earn low return for few years and stay invested in only high quality banks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>c)&nbsp;</strong><strong>NCD, NLD, Perpetual Bonds</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Because of low interest rates in deposits and other fixed income investment, instruments like Non Convertible Debentures (NCD), Nifty Linked Debentures (NLD), AT1 Perpetual bonds are becoming available with relatively better return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors are required to review them with magnifying glasses and understand the default risk carefully. Issuer of underlying paper and terms of the product should be carefully examined to understand the risk. Stay away from them if something doesn&rsquo;t feel right as there is no point in taking unwanted risk for extra return. It is better to take higher risk in equity where return payoff is proportional and higher.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">3) Equity&nbsp;&ndash;</span>&nbsp;</strong>As explained above, bad loans will have an impact on GDP Growth of India. This should fundamentally affect corporate earnings and equity returns. Will this lead to equity correction or fall? We don&rsquo;t know. Its very difficult to predict the movement of equity in short term as equity market also gets influenced by liquidity and sentiment. If global liquidity continues for long, &nbsp;market can also keep going up accordingly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Always remember &ndash;&nbsp;<strong>&lsquo;Markets can be irrational for a very long time&rsquo;</strong>. Investors should definitely be careful and watch the investment closely. Book profit with upward movement of market and buy when markets are correcting. We feel volatility will be high in 2021 and will give good opportunity to investors to take advantage and generate better returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Are banking stocks going to be affected?&nbsp;</strong>Bank stocks have already been hit in the last 1 year, which can be seen as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687952749/g1ir3pzxgsweulvnzc1r.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 654px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source : Ngen</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per the above chart, Nifty in the last 1 year has given a return of ~18.5% and during the same period, banking Index has given a return ~0%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its very difficult to say whether the worst is over for bank stocks. Could be possible that they fall further from here or even start recovering from here after the under-performance of last 1 year. Our suggestion will be that we should let the equity fund managers take this call based on their analysis and outlook.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2021 is definitely going to be an interesting year. Markets are expected to be volatile. We are excited and ready to handle any crisis. Crises and crashes always throw opportunity for big gains.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Wishing you a great and fantastic year ahead.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953110/i3sqltdljfzyo9qdsalm.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Warning from RBI – Tsunami of Bad Loans in 2021","seo_keywords":"Warning from RBI – Tsunami of Bad Loans in 2021","seo_description":"Equity market has been seeing a fantastic rally since March, 2020 and the rally has been continuing in 2021 as well. We all know that the primary reason for equity rally has been global liquidity which is due to huge stimulus from US and other countries.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953108/aiwz7pobvphrtpkgmeox.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"168","title":"What’s Your New Year Resolution??","slug":"whats-your-new-year-resolution","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1609415661","published_date_view":"Dec 31, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953327/jevdgootutb6gdsd41pw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 727px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The landmark year 2020 comes to an end. Landmark because of a million reasons &ndash; which are usually witness only in a lifetime. And it paves way for a new hope for the upcoming 2021.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And like every year, new beginnings are marked by celebrations, fanfare and fervour with friends and family. An unmissable part of every new year are the new year resolutions that we all make.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, my dear readers, this new year 2021, with the experience of what we saw in the last 10 months &ndash; I urge you all to make a promise to yourselves to be more financially responsible. Business/ Job stability is important; however, financial stability is more crucial. Consumption is a necessity, however, only after adequate savings and appropriate investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, if you haven&rsquo;t started thinking on these lines yet, there is no better time than new year to safeguard your future financially. The keyword is INVEST. As they say &ndash;<strong>&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">the best time to plant a tree was twenty years ago and the second-best time is now.</span></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For the first time investors &ndash;&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>to start is important</strong></span>&nbsp;&ndash; add a few financial products like mutual funds, provident fund,&nbsp; gold bonds etc in your basket. &nbsp;The right thing is to begin investing right away, regardless of how much money you save. These small investments balloon into a large corpus over time due to compounding. Optimal mix of traditional and unconventional mix of financial products are out there to be explored and benefitted from.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">While investing money in various financial products is important.<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">&nbsp;<strong>What is more important is to be financially literate.</strong></span>&nbsp;Financial literacy is our ability to understand how to use money as a tool to help us craft successful lives by the standards that matter to us &ndash; Distinguishing between needs and wants; Making smart money choices; Setting and saving for goals.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Being financially independent is of paramount importance to everyone. Working professionals ought to spend time understanding their salary structures; everyone (including women) should manage their finances on their own,&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>make mistakes and learn from them for the future, and save enough to have a buffer to meet contingencies</strong></span>.&nbsp;Having this knowledge supports our ability to make prudent financial decisions throughout life and to respond competently and confidently to the inevitable financial uncertainties that we all face.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A big shout to the parents, who must have showered gift on their kids on Christmas/ New Year. The moment we assume the role of a parent, building a financially secure future assumes top priority, impacting the way we view, spend, save and invest our finances. You can (and should) make sure that you have enough to give your kids a good start in life. But remember it is just a start.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is important for parents to realize that the struggle to secure the child&rsquo;s future is pointless if the child is not taught how to manage these finances.&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Teaching children how to manage money is one of the most important responsibilities parents have</strong></span>.&nbsp;It&rsquo;s never too early to begin teaching children the basics of finances &ndash; How money works. What are earnings, savings and investments, What happens when you buy something? What exactly does a bank do with your money? How do taxes work? What are investments? How do investments grow? How is money created? Why does the value of investments increase with time while that of a car or a phone decrease? Why were prices of things low in the past? Why will they be higher in the future? Etc&hellip;..</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, start grooming your child today. This knowledge is more useful than money is &ndash; and it could also be something that is passed from generation to generation long after you and I are gone.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If you have been on your investment journey for long, it is likely that you have enough corpus with you and if it is invested wisely, it would have grown in value with time. It is always comforting to have the financial flexibility with time and options on your side.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Money allows people to live longer and healthier lives, better nutrition and better medical care, more free time and more meaningful labor&mdash;more of just about every ingredient in the recipe for a happy life. Yet, the relationship between money and happiness (quality of life) is not that simple.&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">The key to happiness is in the way we spend it</span>&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; basically using the acquired wealth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The focus of saving money should be to enhance your wealth without compromising on your personal freedom while creating financial security. Though it is common sense and sounds easy but more often than not it is difficult to follow.&nbsp; Mindless saving trades off the present for the future. It is important to know the difference between hoarding and saving. Hoarding can be understood as an exaggeration of an otherwise positive behaviour&mdash; saving&mdash;taken to the extreme.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Some people hoard money, while others compulsively hoard objects of their interest&mdash;jewellery, gold bars and coins, unaccounted cash, etc. Over saving may not be as serious as going into heavy consumer debt. However, going to the either extreme is not healthy. No one can deny that savings is a hedge against life&rsquo;s inevitable ability to surprise the hell out of you at the worst possible moment. Everyone knows the tangible stuff money buys. But the desire for more stuff is never satisfied and we are left chasing goal posts that are constantly moving.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As Greek philosopher Epictetus said, &ldquo;wealth consists not in having great possessions, but in having few wants.&rdquo;&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\">The hardest financial skill is getting the goalpost to stop moving.</span>&nbsp;</strong>And to do that, you have to stop comparing yourself to others, and start determining what is &ldquo;enough&rdquo; for yourself.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One needs to develop the ability to balance the present and future needs, and apportion money accordingly. The most beautiful things in life are not things. They&rsquo;re people, and places, and memories, and pictures. They&rsquo;re feelings and moments and smiles and laughter. Spending need not result in material things&mdash;there are wonderful experiences the world has to offer if you choose to step out and explore. So, invest in yourself &ndash; take a course in photography, wildlife, art, theatre or in upskilling yourself from a professional perspective.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If you recognise that you have enough and some more money, learn to give.&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Beyond a point it is the act of giving that money that brings joy.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy New Year!! Invest and Spend Intelligently!!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953483/zmxmzvonlp69ttravyis.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"What’s Your New Year Resolution??","seo_keywords":"What’s Your New Year Resolution??","seo_description":"The landmark year 2020 comes to an end. Landmark because of a million reasons – which are usually witness only in a lifetime. And it paves way for a new hope for the upcoming 2021.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953477/dcenzgm27xs2jlbrlqhr.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"169","title":"Betting For or Against the Beta – Which Side are You?","slug":"betting-for-or-against-the-beta-which-side-are-you","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1609156687","published_date_view":"Dec 28, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Financial theory tells us that to earn return, one needs to take risk. But how much risk is left to the individual making the decision. At this point, the inability of human beings to properly weigh their chances of success in low probability events makes all the difference.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953572/xjca3cin01xjqyzrcwo4.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 694px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In pursuit of quick riches, we sometimes turn to lottery-like stocks: companies that trade at outrageous valuations, have exciting stories, and have the potential to be wildly successful.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Possibility effect, tendency to overestimate the chance of occurring of a possible but not probable event, is the reason why investors (especially retail investors) are attracted to these highly volatile stocks, especially with negative news around them. Overoptimism of the human race goes against them for investment decisions in stocks (though it holds true across asset classes) with lottery-like characteristics. Investors irrationally overpay for lottery-like gambles, assuming their odds are higher than in reality.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We all love these stocks because we love innovation, new technologies, and revolutionary companies. &nbsp;We all are excited to that maybe at this very moment we can find&nbsp;the next Netflix &hellip; the next Tesla&hellip; the next Apple &hellip; the next Byjus or a pharma company which could possibly come up with a drug that might fight coronavirus. However, these stocks are like lottery tickets. They pay off BIG &hellip; or they eventually go to zero. It&rsquo;s a gamble. These smaller, younger companies more often belong to sectors like Pharmaceuticals &amp; Biotechnology, Technology Hardware &amp; Equipment, and Software &amp; Services. Penny stocks or financially distressed stocks that are either in or near bankruptcy also exhibit lottery like characteristics.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Everyone knows the odds are terrible, but the prospect of great fortune has always been, and will always be, very seductive.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953594/khskdyd4nf216r59xes8.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 721px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On the other hand, Warren Buffet swears on Low Volatility Investing &ndash; giving enough evidence in support of the Betting against Beta anomaly. A discussion on Buffet&rsquo;s Alpha highlights the Buffett&rsquo;s returns appear to be neither luck nor magic but, rather, a reward for leveraging cheap, safe, high-quality stocks over a long (very long) period of staying invested.&nbsp;<strong>Beta anomaly is regarded as one of the most puzzling phenomena in the history of finance as it negates the fundamental notion that a higher return can only be earned after taking more risk.&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Betting against Beta or Low volatility is simply a way of buying stocks which rank low on standard deviation or volatility over a look back period of 6-12 months. Stocks that would rank high on this factor would be stocks where most investors under-react to information being fed to them on a regular basis, owing to the certainty bias. When an outcome is likely, people tend to underestimate its odds. This bias has been named the certainty effect.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per financial theory, we would expect over a long period, high beta stocks should have done much better than low volatility and low beta stocks. However, when we see the returns of Nifty Low Volatility 50 Index (The least volatile security in the index gets the highest weight) and Nifty High Beta 50 Index (The security with the highest beta in the index is assigned the highest weight), the reverse holds true. Research studies also offer evidence in support of the existence of beta-anomaly (long leveraged low-beta assets and short high-beta assets) in the Indian equity market also.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953616/cz6yjahumfbcns8y5opl.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 508px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The study titled &ldquo;A Lottery-Demand-Based Explanation of the Beta Anomaly,&rdquo; which appears in the December 2017 issue of the Journal of Financial and Quantitative Analysis explains: &ldquo;Lottery investors generate demand for stocks with high probabilities of large short-term up moves in the stock price. Such up moves are partially generated by a stock&rsquo;s sensitivity to the overall market&mdash;market beta. A disproportionately high (low) amount of lottery demand-based price pressure is therefore exerted on high-beta (low-beta) stocks, pushing the prices of such stocks up (down) and therefore decreasing (increasing) future returns.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, what does this really mean for us investors?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To formulate a strategy in the context, think of a barbell approach of investing. As per the barbell strategy, the optimal way is to strike a balance between reward and risk while investing. That is, to invest in the two extremes of high risk and no risk assets while avoiding middle-of-the-road choices. Some sectors are available at extremely discounted valuations &ndash; banking sector, consumer discretionary, energy and industrials, led by government spending and domestic consumption, a combination of both. Profit booking in safety/ comfort sectors like FMCG. One has to have defensive stocks to beat the volatility, but as you move to a full-blown recovery globally and in India, you need to be shifting towards cyclicals and the banking sector. The PSUs have been unloved for a long time and the valuations are compelling.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Strategizing &amp; Happy Investing!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953695/irj4oinp4xgwmfaxji26.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Betting For or Against the Beta – Which Side are You?","seo_keywords":"Betting For or Against the Beta – Which Side are You?","seo_description":"Financial theory tells us that to earn return, one needs to take risk. But how much risk is left to the individual making the decision. At this point, the inability of human beings to properly weigh their chances of success in low probability events makes all the difference.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953693/cxeiawnc57kwj3buybee.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"170","title":"Understanding Bitcoin – Its a Bubble or an Asset for Investment","slug":"understanding-bitcoin-its-a-bubble-or-an-asset-for-investment","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1608552100","published_date_view":"Dec 21, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Bitcoin has been the best performing asset class of 2020 with a return of 238%. Since 12th March 2020, Bitcoin has given a return of 373%. The movement of Bitcoin in 2020 can be seen as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953851/tfmpev4wosztuiekvyma.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 515px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Source &ndash; Coindesk</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">As price of bitcoin continues to go up, more and more people are talking about the same. There are a lot of unanswered questions around Bitcoin and through this post I have tried to answer them.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>1 ) What has been the historical performance of Bitcoin?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953880/supi79cjkse0ixtjauel.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 412px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">*Source : 99bitcoins.com</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">In 2010, the price of 1 Bitcoin was 5 Cents or USD 0.05. Today, each bitcoin is trading at USD 23,600. This is a phenomenal growth and no other investment has given similar return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">In the last 10 years, Bitcoin has given an annualized return of ~207% per annum. For reference, during same period, Nasdaq in USD has given annualized return of ~20% per annum and Emerging Markets Equity in USD has given an annualized return of ~3% per annum.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>2) How Volatile or risky is Bitcoin?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Following chart shows major corrections in Bitcoin from all time highs</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953899/oxg0nt152utdsh3ki7dd.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 648px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Source : CharlieBilello</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The above chart shows that in 2010 and 2011, the value of Bitcoin fell by ~94%. In 2018 and 2015, the value of Bitcoin fell by ~85%. In 2010, the value of Bitcoin fell by 72% in just 4 days.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The above chart clearly shows that Bitcoin is not for a faint hearted person. Bitcoin is highly volatile and short term losses can be significant and very fast.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The good news which above chart also gives is that the recovery is quick and it always touches new high. If an investor is able to handle the volatility then Bitcoin rewards him/ her with a new high and better returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>3) What is Bitcoin and its price movement is dependent on what factors?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Bitcoin is a virtual and decentralised currency that can be traded or used over the internet. Bitcoin is not backed by any country or central authority. Its an open source network whose power and functions are distributed to the users in internet.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The value of Bitcoin is purely derived on the basis of demand and supply. The supply of Bitcoin is limited and already known. A total of 21 Million Bitcoins will be produced by the year 2140. Presently, approx 18.57 Million Bitcoins are in supply.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The supply of Bitcoin since 2009 can be seen as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953943/tk45lq0ljua4wpyne05c.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 519px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Source : blockchain.com</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Demand of Bitcoin is dependent on number of people using or investing in Bitcoin. As the usage and acceptance of Bitcoin goes up, the demand goes up and eventually bitcoin price moves up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The following log price graph shows movement of Bitcoin price against number of people using Bitcoin:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687953983/jubshok3ox6lyqiboraq.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 574px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">*Source : Katusa Research</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">There&rsquo;re approximately 100 million people using bitcoin now.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Since supply of Bitcoin is limited and known, its more about demand and future usage of Bitcoin. Investors are betting that in long term, usage will be higher and so price of Bitcoin will be also higher.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>4) Bitcoin is a Commodity or Currency?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Technically, Bitcoin is both Commodity and currency. It functions as both a medium of exchange and a commodity with a finite supply.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">However, in current scenario, as far as use case is concerned then its more popular as a commodity like a digital version of Gold.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Presently, its not being used popularly as medium of exchange because of huge volatility in price and longer time taken to do transactions through Bitcoin. But in few years, hopefully, both volatility and transaction time will get reduced and it will become more acceptable as medium of exchange.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The below chart shows median time taken for each Bitcoin transaction which is currently at ~15 minutes</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687954008/mb9gvrsgxq70quruzzvs.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 712px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">*Source: Katusa Research</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>5) Why did Bitcoin price go up in 2020?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Bitcoin has seen a fantastic growth in 2020. The growth is not driven by mass retail investors or speculation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Following chart shows Google search trends for Bitcoin and movement of Bitcoin Price.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687954030/yk0ks9xsgfkvupbqjvxc.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 732px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Source &ndash; Coindesk</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Back in 2018 and 2019, a lot of people were searching about Bitcoin. The Google Search surge is in line with the Bitcoin rally. But 2020 rally has not been accompanied with Google searches by mass retail investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The primary reasons for the rally of 2020 are as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>a) Fiscal Stimulus by US Fed in March 2020</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Huge Fiscal Stimulus by US Fed led to increase in printing of US Dollars and increase in global liquidity. To protect against the purchasing power of cash, investors moved money into assets like Gold, Equity and Bitcoin.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Graph showing US Fed&rsquo;s Balance sheet expansion for stimulus:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687954051/ij6ag3p0ahm03kmlokff.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 520px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">*Source &ndash; FRED</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>b) Participation of Institutional players &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Paypal recently announced that their customers will be able to use Bitcoin to transact with their 26 million merchants around the world. Square has recently invested 1% of their total assets in Bitcoin. Another US company MicroStrategy has invested USD 250 Million in Bitcoin as well.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687954076/udq86ogtjgmcavmteogi.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 477px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Source : Dr. Wealth</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>6) Whats the legal status of Bitcoin in India?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">In early 2018, India&rsquo;s central bank, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) announced a ban on the sale or purchase of cryptocurrency by entities regulated by RBI.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">In 2019, a petition had been filed by Internet and Mobile Association of India with the Supreme Court of India challenging the legality of cryptocurrencies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">In March 2020, the Supreme Court of India passed the verdict, revoking the RBI ban on cryptocurrency trade.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">So, currently, its legal in India to trade and invest in Bitcoin. However, a new law by Government of India to ban Cryptocurrency cannot be ruled out in future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>7) What are the risks involved when investing in Bitcoin?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Some important risks of Bitcoin are as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">a) The biggest risk is that all the Governments will be against Bitcoin. Since Bitcoin reduces the power of Countries to print money at their own will, no Government would like Bitcoin to be popular. So most probably Governments are going to ban or try reducing the public usage of Bitcoin.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">b) Bitcoin can be used for money laundering and terrorist financing due to the anonymous nature of cryptocurrencies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">c) Bitcoin is highly volatile and investors should be comfortable to see a loss of 95% in a very short period of time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">d) Bitcoin is prone to hacking and scams. Its not easy investing and storing the bitcoin. Since its digitally stored, its always exposed to digital frauds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>8) What should be the portfolio strategy for Bitcoin? Does it makes sense to invest?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">If investor is comfortable with the above mentioned risks then he/ she can consider investing in the Bitcoin.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Only that money should be invested in Bitcoin, which investor is comfortable to lose completely and which he/ she can forget for 10-20 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">From an Asset Allocation perspective, an allocation of upto 0.5%-1% of total investible surplus can be considered in Bitcoin.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The advantage of having Bitcoin in portfolio is that it can deliver asymmetric returns for overall portfolio. In 10-20 years, Bitcoin will either become Zero or can become 10 to 100 times. For an investor who is investing 0.5%- 1% of his/ her wealth, the loss will not be significant if value becomes zero but if the value goes up by 10 to 100 times then return contribution in portfolio can be huge and very meaningful.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">In case you decide to take the plunge in Bitcoin then it will be ideal to build exposure gradually in phases since there has been a huge rally recently. This will help in reducing the market timing risk.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">The most important recommendation for investors considering to invest in Bitcoin is that they should spend good amount of time reading about Bitcoin and understanding the fine points in detail. Knowledge and conviction of Bitcoin will help them in handling the volatility well and take right decisions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Happy Investing!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal CFA, CFP, CAIA. Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687954339/usuzwpiahfochuo7qe9z.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Understanding Bitcoin – Its a Bubble or an Asset for Investment","seo_keywords":"Understanding Bitcoin – Its a Bubble or an Asset for Investment","seo_description":"Bitcoin has been the best performing asset class of 2020 with a return of 238%. Since 12th March 2020, Bitcoin has given a return of 373%.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687954303/mbnimk38owjoxowpdhzh.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"171","title":"The GDP Dichotomy – Recession or Recovery?","slug":"the-gdp-dichotomy-recession-or-recovery","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1606674600","published_date_view":"Nov 30, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The covid-19 crisis has hit the world economy hard. The GDP numbers across the world have plummeted to levels never seen before. The second quarter numbers for FY 2020-21 have been released for India. It&rsquo;s a negative 7.5% &ndash; indicating contraction in the economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Now, here is a dichotomy! On technical terms, two consecutive contractions in an economy mean a recession. So, a contraction of 23% in Q1 followed by the contraction of 7.5% in Q2 puts India in its first ever &lsquo;recession&rsquo; &ndash; a term economists refer to a situation of negative growth caused by massive slowdown in economic activities. This fact makes the investor in me glum and morose.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687955641/ohzwryl5ty0l9ckjbmxw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 731px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, on the contrary, the dichotomous thought is the strong rebound &ndash; indicating a sharp recovery &ndash; almost a V-shaped recovery. From the nadir of negative 23.9% GDP growth in the previous quarter, the economy rebounded to negative 7.5% in the July-September period. The growth numbers beat the estimates of most economists &ndash; across the three components as well. Manufacturing depicted 0.6 per cent growth in July-September after it had shrunk by a massive 39 per cent in the preceding quarter. Continuing its strong resistance, the agriculture sector grew by 3.4 per cent, while the trade and services sector showed lower-than-expected contraction at 15.6 per cent.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Though the recovery has been sharp, for Q2, India&rsquo;s among the worst-performing major advanced and emerging economies. It seems India is in for a tough fight as it attempts to curtail rising covid cases, revive consumption demand, boost investment and create jobs. As per the data, only&nbsp;China&nbsp;seemed to have a positive growth rate with 4.9 in the July-September quarter of FY2021. The GDP of&nbsp;US&nbsp;stands at (-)2.9 percent, while for&nbsp;France its (-)3.9 percent. Despite making a recovery,&nbsp;UK and&nbsp;Germany&nbsp;saw a contraction of (-)9.6 and (-)4 percent respectively. While&nbsp;South Korea, Russia&nbsp;and&nbsp;Japan, the GDP contracted by 1.3, 3.6 and 5.8 percent, respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687955665/blyr7jb4okrhpkf0h5cu.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 411px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This dichotomy in the interpretation of the GDP numbers can be extended to the stock markets. On one hand, the current surge in the stock markets may seems unsustainable &ndash; may lead to volatility in the next few weeks, however it seems certainly sustainable over the long run. Most of the stocks, both in the mid-cap and small-cap, space have revived to pre-covid levels.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With economic reforms planned out, it seems the long run rise has just begun. As the vaccine development news pick up gradually, the green shoots for the economy will be more visible. This would create a robust path ahead for our stock markets. India will continue to be prominent player in the global economy, even as the covid concerns recede. Backed with improved domestic fundamentals and confidence of foreign capital, the stock markets are expected to see new highs in the next fiscal.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Look for opportunities in these temporary volatile times. The global investor is bullish on India in the long run. Let&rsquo;s look for the entry points at every sharp fall, book profits in portfolios that didn&rsquo;t work well even in the pre-covid times and stay invested through SIP/STP formats for the longer run. So, my dear investors, let&rsquo;s enjoy the party while being cautious.&nbsp;<strong>Abhi to party shuru hui hai!</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687955730/m8hznazf2gcz5pragmdg.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The GDP Dichotomy – Recession or Recovery?","seo_keywords":"The GDP Dichotomy – Recession or Recovery?","seo_description":"Now, here is a dichotomy! On technical terms, two consecutive contractions in an economy mean a recession. So, a contraction of 23% in Q1 followed by the contraction of 7.5% in Q2 puts India in its first ever ‘recession’ – a term economists refer to a situation of negative growth caused by massive slowdown in economic activities. This fact makes the investor in me glum and morose.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687955728/llpo7gsa6v1z6yifprge.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"172","title":"Indian Equity Market is in Comfortable or Overvalued Zone – Analysis","slug":"indian-equity-market-is-in-comfortable-or-overvalued-zone-analysis","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1606221352","published_date_view":"Nov 24, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Indian Equity market has seen a phenomenal uptrend since 24th March 2020 which can be seen as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956009/yqmq5go7ymfotoqhzm6o.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 658px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Ngenmarkets, as on 23/11/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that Nifty 50 has given a return of 68.97% since 23/3/2020. During the same period, Mid Cap Index has given a return of 69.25% and Small Cap Index has given a return of 82.39%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">After experiencing the above rally, investors are apprehensive about the valuation of equity market and concerned about probability of correction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In this analysis, we will try to analyse the movement and valuation of Indian Equity market so that investors can take informed decision regarding their portfolios.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Movement of Indian Equity since 1st January 2020:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956034/dcfgevf6weyxef7nalqw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 647px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Ngenmarkets, as on 23/11/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that Nifty 50 has given a return of 5.5% since 1/1/2020. During the same period, Mid Cap Index has given a return of 9.59% and Small Cap Index has given a return of 17.38%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It can be clearly seen that investors have recovered all their losses in Equity due to Covid related volatility of March, 2020. Small Cap &amp; Mid Cap stocks have performed better than large cap stocks during the same period.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Movement of Indian Equity since 31st January 2018:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956057/jn0dejh2gfljo2opxhdv.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 657px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Ngenmarkets, as on 23/11/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that Nifty 50 has given an absolute return of 16.61% since 31/1/2018. During the same period, Mid Cap Index has given a return of -5.34% and Small Cap Index has given a return of -13.54%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the past ~30 months, Indian Equity has hardly given any return. Few stocks in Nifty have moved up but broader equity market is still in negative territory. Especially, Mid Cap and Small cap are definitely in losses and they present an opportunity for investment.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Equity Sectors Performance in the last 12 months:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956077/kxji3iaoil0faa9yzbib.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 553px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Ngenmarkets,&nbsp;as on 23/11/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that in the last 12 months, defensive sectors like Pharma and IT have given good returns but other cyclical sectors like Banking, Utilities etc. are still in negative territory. This clearly shows that the recent rally of last 8 months is not broad based, few sectors have benefited far more.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The performance of cyclical sectors are dependent on the growth of economy. They perform well when economy grows. With opening of lockdown and positive progress on vaccine, cyclical sectors are expected to start performing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Cyclical sectors have started doing well in the last 3 months and hopefully the trend is expected to continue.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><u>The above 4 charts clearly shows that equity market has definitely gone up in the last 8 months, but Indian equity investor has hardly made any money in last 3 years. Also, the rally has not been broad based. Mid Cap, Small Caps and Cyclical sectors are still down from their previous highs and offer good opportunity for investment.</u></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Lets look at valuation of India Equity Market now.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Market Capitalisation to GDP Ratio:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956099/sr0evdidavqmj7tnv0q2.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 429px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Motilal Oswal Research, as on 30/10/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that Market Capitalisation to GDP (also known as Buffett indicator) for India is at 80 (As on 31st October 2020) . The long term average for the ratio is at 75. The current value shows that Indian equity is overvalued by ~7%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>PB Ratio of Nifty 500:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956600/jdtxr1martrjsmlowxza.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 363px;\" type=\"image\" /></span><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Trendlyne, as on 23/11/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that PB Ratio of NIFTY 500 is presently at 3.41. The long term average of the PB Ratio for India is at 3.1. Based on this information, it can be said that Indian Equity is overvalued by apporox 10%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">PB Ratio is a good valuation ratio and has become more relevant these days because corporate earnings have seen a huge short term correction due to Covid and has thus made PE Ratio irrelevant for time being.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Indian 10 Year G Sec Movement:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956223/zmz0rttvmejyotmjxp6d.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 447px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that Indian 10 Year G Sec which is an indicator of long term interest rate in India, has fallen from 8.2% in Sep 2018 to current rate of 5.9%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The fall in interest rate of ~2.3% in the last 2 years has made Fixed Income/ Debt investment less attractive.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Global Supply of Bonds with Negative Yield:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956251/udjyajsvlpjkzqufarqy.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Globally, the total market value of negative yielding bonds, rose to $17.05 trillion in November 2020, the highest level ever recorded. Approx 26% of the world&rsquo;s investment grade debt is now yielding sub-zero interest rate.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Because of reduced interest rate on bonds, debt has become less attractive and investors are globally moving their money to equity and other alternate assets. This has led to surge in FII equity investment in India which can be seen from following chart:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956275/ujalpvge5fao3ifu2vnz.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 459px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Moneycontrol, as on 22/11/20</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that Foreign Institutional Investors (FII) have been investing in Indian Market almost every month and Indian Equity Mutual Funds have been selling every month. Since 1st April 2020, FIIs have made a total investment of ~Rs. 1,42,212 Crores and Indian Equity Mutual Funds have sold ~Rs. 54,528 Crores.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Conclusion:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Indian Equity market has given phenomenal return since 23rd March 2020. However, most of this movement has happened as a recovery of Covid market correction. On a three year basis, Indian Equity market has hardly given any return, Mid cap and Small cap&nbsp; Indexes are still trading below their level of 31st January, 2018.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Valuation indicators like Market Cap to GDP Ratio and PB Ratio indicate that current valuation is ~10% above their long term average. However, its important that we consider this in respect to attractiveness of other asset classes. Interest rate in India has fallen by approx. 2.3% in last 2 years and has made fixed income less attractive.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Globally, ~26% of investment grade bonds are trading below zero interest rate which is leading to inflow into equity markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to us, Indian Equity market is in fair value &amp; comfortable zone now considering the low interest rates in India and globally. Hence, investors should stick to their Asset Allocation policy and stay invested accordingly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing!!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956808/dwxd1hlhvis4y8demxca.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Indian Equity Market is in Comfortable or Overvalued Zone – Analysis","seo_keywords":"Indian Equity Market is in Comfortable or Overvalued Zone – Analysis","seo_description":"Indian Equity market has seen a phenomenal uptrend since 24th March 2020 which can be seen as under:","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687956806/bre1xbsrcaqqw1k1qg8p.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"173","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (3/11/20)","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing-3-11-20","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1604408158","published_date_view":"Nov 03, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please find below&nbsp;5&nbsp;charts&nbsp;that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) US Tech is not in Bubble Zone like 2000:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957112/vdcgbwtqzzhuoo0aj5wm.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1229px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">Source: JP Morgan Research</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Technology Index has become ~10 times since 2009. The Index also has the record of falling by ~80% during the tech meltdown of 2000. The question is whether US Tech is again in bubble zone now and will it correct.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Correction can happen anytime, market necessarily don&rsquo;t have to reach the previous bubble zone for correction. However, presently, US Tech Index is definitely not in bubble zone similar to the level seen in 2000.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the percentage share of tech companies in market cap of S&amp;P 500 Index vs earning contribution of tech companies in S&amp;P 500 Index. In 2000, the weight of tech companies in S&amp;P 500 Index was 33.6% but earnings contribution was only 16.3%. In 2020, the weight of tech companies in S&amp;P 500 Index is 28.2% but earnings contribution is 23.7%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It can be clearly seen that in 2000, the earning contribution of tech companies in Index was almost half of their weight. But in 2020, the earning contribution is almost similar to their weight.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Trump VS Biden &ndash; Proposed Spending Plan</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957150/ksarrstigdwiyp06la9v.webp\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 577px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; MRB Partners</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the proposed spending plan of Trump and Biden if they become President of the United States of America. Both Trump and Biden plan to increase their spending on the economy by printing more money. This will lead to increase in inflation and increase in asset prices.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Biden plans to increase the tax collection by raising the corporate tax rates which may have a negative impact in short term on corporate profitability. Biden also plans to spend heavily on infrastructure, education etc which will have positive impact on the economy in long term.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) India&rsquo;s Export growth has been 3rd highest between 1995 and 2018</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957182/gjcserxmyb6pabvemsud.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 734px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Research paper by Arvind Subramanian &amp; Shoumitro Chatterjee</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Between 1995 and 2018, India&rsquo;s overall export growth has averaged 13.4 percent annually, the third-best performance in the world among the top 50 exporters, nearly twice the average world growth and not far behind China&rsquo;s growth of just over 15 percent.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Contrary to wide belief, Indian export has done well primarily supported by service industry and high skills manufacturing. The only weak area for Indian export is low skill manufacturing like apparel, textile, leather, footwear etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Low skill manufacturing is what helped the export of countries like Vietnam, China and Bangladesh. India has a huge advantage in terms of low cost labour but it doesn&rsquo;t gets benefit of the same due to bad labour laws. Indian Government should relax labour laws to increase employment and enable faster growth of low skilled manufacturing exports.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Impact of US Dollar on Global Stock Markets</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957203/khzgmtjl1aersvyde6ht.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1210px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; JP Morgan Research</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows movement of US Dollar Index (USDX) since 1995. The US dollar index isn&rsquo;t just a movement against Indian Rupee (INR) but it&rsquo;s a measure of the value of US dollar relative to the value of a basket of currencies of the majority trading partners of US.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that US Dollar Index weakened between 2000 and 2010, this was also the time when emerging market equity was doing well and US equity struggled. Between 2010 and 2020, US Dollar Index became stronger and during this time emerging market equity struggled and US equity did well.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So it can be said that US Dollar Index has positive correlation with US equity and negative correlation with emerging markets equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Make a correct prediction about the movement of US Dollar Index and you will be able to pick the right equity market to invest.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Household Savings &amp; Public Sector Borrowing:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957256/m8pvkbne90exrmb0rj26.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 662px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\">*Source &ndash; Book &ndash; Bad Money: Inside the NPA Mess by Vivek Kaul</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the movement of household savings and public sector borrowings as percentage GDP of India. The chart shows that household savings has been falling and public sector borrowing has been increasing gradually.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to higher borrowing and lower savings, longer term Interest rate continues to be high in India despite almost zero interest rate globally.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to limited scope of further borrowing, Government has been reluctant in providing fiscal stimulus. Any additional fiscal stimulus has to be funded by printing of money by RBI which will lead to high inflation. The retail inflation in India is already at 7.34%. Government cannot afford to risk any higher inflation because high inflation is one of the biggest reason for political parties losing election (Read UPA).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957394/h04h4bx0ep38ljoukr0d.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (3/11/20)","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (3/11/20)","seo_description":"The above chart shows the percentage share of tech companies in market cap of S&P 500 Index vs earning contribution of tech companies in S&P 500 Index. In 2000, the weight of tech companies in S&P 500 Index was 33.6% but earnings contribution was only 16.3%. In 2020, the weight of tech companies in S&P 500 Index is 28.2% but earnings contribution is 23.7%.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957392/ssoijta2gn29v0aypci5.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"174","title":"The Election Cacophony – Trump vs Biden Drama","slug":"the-election-cacophony-trump-vs-biden-drama","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1604063276","published_date_view":"Oct 30, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Politics is a major factor impacting economics all over. The entire world is curiously following the Trump-Biden drama ahead of the upcoming presidential elections of the super power United States of America.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Historically, it has been proven that the swings in the stock markets from New York to Singapore, Tokyo to Mumbai are enormous during the times of huge political events. The past shows that out of the only time the equity markets had fallen 3 months and 6 months after the election was in 2008 due to the subprime crises. And in 2001, which is exactly after 1 year of the US election, markets had fallen due to the US terrorist attacks on WTC.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The rest of the time, markets have cheered the outcome and the one-year gains have been at an average gain of more than 15 percent. So as the trend suggests, the likelihood of equity markets to fly is higher irrespective of Trump or Biden be in power.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957563/n7rd3vp0fnerw2rz8ujh.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 417px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">More so, whether Trump or Biden wins, the pandemic impacted macro-economic strategies may not digress much. The Federal Reserve&rsquo;s low-interest policy is expected to continue, especially in the near-term. This will boost the capital flight to emerging markets specially India, China, Indonesia etc. in search for higher returns. This is a big plus for Indian markets as it would result in the continued inflow of cheap capital into Indian stock as well as debt markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957587/jateggmqzxzeedbqxcob.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 563px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As seen in the above chart of US Dow Jones and Sensex, the historical pattern suggests that both share a high degree of positive co-relation. Both Trump and Biden have promised bigger stimulus, irrespective of who wins, the announcement of it will lead to a boost in the US stock markets. Since both the indices are positively correlated, Indian markets too shall remain on an upward trend supported by global sentiments. Hence, in the medium to long run, there are prospects of money flowing into the Indian Capital markets post-election.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Further, the election cacophony closer to home is equally music to the ears (pun intended!). Closer to home, we have the Bihar state elections coming up shortly. Who-so-ever be the next Chief Minister, the sharp swings in the stock markets are likely to be the trend in the coming weeks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is proven by past data analysis and research that high volatility is associated with the markets during elections. However, the volatility is more of a short term phenomenon and gradually the election-driven volatility (and returns) die down over the medium to long term. The table below depicts the returns on BSE Sensex values, 6 months before the Lok Sabha elections and 18 months post the Lok Sabha elections. The returns have been happily positive in almost all cases. Markets cheer up from the short term volatility gradually.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957610/g66ziqbjx4n8sf5kwknl.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 780px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Therefore my dear investors, let us not get distracted by the election cacophony around us. Stick to the fundamentals, stay away from the noise. It&rsquo;s time to be an intelligent investor and not a prudent punter! The markets would be volatile in the next few weeks. Identify your picks. Let&rsquo;s bite in to grab your pie of the cake at low levels. And book profit if markets touches new high in short term.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">And what about the elections in all this cherry picking? &ndash; May the best man win!</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957683/frdshpvytqelyk3vodc7.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Election Cacophony – Trump vs Biden Drama","seo_keywords":"The Election Cacophony – Trump vs Biden Drama","seo_description":"Historically, it has been proven that the swings in the stock markets from New York to Singapore, Tokyo to Mumbai are enormous during the times of huge political events. The past shows that out of the only time the equity markets had fallen 3 months and 6 months after the election was in 2008 due to the subprime crises. And in 2001, which is exactly after 1 year of the US election, markets had fallen due to the US terrorist attacks on WTC. The rest of the time, markets have cheered the outcome and the one-year gains have been at an average gain of more than 15 percent. So as the trend suggests, the likelihood of equity markets to fly is higher irrespective of Trump or Biden be in power.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957680/i8umde4ehd3rvmpnneuo.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"175","title":"Last shot in the arm for the Economy – The Festival Season!","slug":"last-shot-in-the-arm-for-the-economy-the-festival-season","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1603112896","published_date_view":"Oct 19, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">That time of the year is here again. The time when the festive spirit covers the entire country. In the economic jargon, the consumption and investment boost during these times.&nbsp; And this phenomenon is true all across the world &ndash; where in the consumer sentiment is a critical factor driving the economy. And consumer sentiment is in turn driven by several factors &ndash; a major one being cultural beliefs and festivities. The multiplier effect of the festivals is huge. Around this time of the year, sales of textiles, automobiles, consumer durables, electronic goods, jewellery, real estate and food picks up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957823/ov4wwou75vs5ju0957vb.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 898px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Even the unorganized sector benefits substantially. Artisans, who mostly reside in rural areas, see significant growth in their sales with greater employment as a cascading effect, owing to increased emphasis on sustainable consumption. The economic importance of the festive season lies in the fact that consumers tend to spend more during this period, with several upgrading their products. This expected consumption boom leads to an increase in industrial activity and investments, while also increasing employment across the nation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, that time this year may be different than ever before. With the pandemic engulfing a major part of year already, the upcoming festivities seem to be the last ray of hope for the economy. Businesses are optimistic that the season may see a revival for the sales and put behind the demons of the pandemic. The current season is likely to be bumper for the e-retailers much more than the traditional stores. The youth of New India enthusiastically increase online sales as e-commerce giants like Amazon, Flipkart, Jiomart give heavy discounts this season to boost sales. While markets haven&rsquo;t been performing too well in the recent past, nonetheless, investors are still hopeful. Diwali is closely attached to stock markets and Dhanteras for gold investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957846/tfwo3bw9aisgyp8zlbnj.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 525px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">People tend to invest on these auspicious occasions with the thought that the investment will multiply our wealth in many folds. Both Indian exchanges, NSE and BSE open the trading window for about an hour on the eve of Diwali and term it as &lsquo;Muhurat Trading&rsquo;. It is considered auspicious to invest on this day.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957917/gmhnukes7nnfqsy5jmsa.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 856px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Market folklore is abundant with the discussion on systematic pattern observed by the stock market during this time. This tendency of financial assets returns, inconsistent with maintained theories of asset-pricing behaviour is popularly known as the calendar anomaly or the seasonality effect. Since the level market efficiency varies from market to market, the nature and strength of the anomalies are different too. Globally, most common calendar anomaly is the January effect, which illustrates higher expected returns in the month of January than the rest of the year.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957960/lyx8ykyh3edfbdbetxs2.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This outcome of Diwali in India is a corollary of the Christmas effect in USA or the Ramdan effect in Middle East countries or the Spring Festival effect in China or &lsquo;Dekansho-bushi&rsquo; effect in Japan which illustrates higher expected returns during these festivals.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Understanding of the reasons behind this seasonality or anomaly offer the investors the chances to earn extraordinary returns.&nbsp;<em>Misattribution bias</em>&nbsp;provides support to this argument<strong><em>.</em></strong>&nbsp;It refers to the tendency of a decision maker to misattribute her/his mood to the financial decision making. This implies that the same situation can be assessed differently in different moods.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687957983/z5rqxckagjuhk1py4m5m.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 662px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Increased liquidity comes into play for the investors with their annual bonus and accumulated savings boosting consumer demand and hence the industrial production, and induced a positive mindset for the investors in the stock market. Interestingly, Chen and Chien (2011) affirm that the increased liquidity makes the investors less risk averse.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The economic scenario in the forthcoming months of 2020 is expected to fare better than the rest of the year on account of lower prices in the prior month, used as a base for calculating returns. The investor&rsquo;s exuberance may not be the same as the previous year. But amidst these difficult times, there still would be some silver lining. Intelligent trades can be executed to make good returns this season. Investors can take advantage of conditions in the event of market anomalies to gain abnormal returns on investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So dear readers and investors, it is time to cash in the upcoming calendar effect with prudent analysis and cautious planning. This Diwali amavasya<em>,&nbsp;</em>lets gets ready to dance in the dark!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agrawal</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958061/jj0hrjgmo0kvxptcjeao.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Last shot in the arm for the Economy – The Festival Season!","seo_keywords":"Last shot in the arm for the Economy – The Festival Season!","seo_description":"That time of the year is here again. The time when the festive spirit covers the entire country. In the economic jargon, the consumption and investment boost during these times.  And this phenomenon is true all across the world – where in the consumer sentiment is a critical factor driving the economy. And consumer sentiment is in turn driven by several factors – a major one being cultural beliefs and festivities. The multiplier effect of the festivals is huge. Around this time of the year, sales of textiles, automobiles, consumer durables, electronic goods, jewellery, real estate and food picks up.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958059/l6hqbtwfztn7wk9u9j4l.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"176","title":"Who Won? – I Did. OR Did I?","slug":"who-won-winners-curse","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1601472135","published_date_view":"Sep 30, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The Indian Premier League is flavour of the season. I would rather say a much-needed elixir for all the cricket lovers amidst the pandemic and the dwindling economic scenario. The players are auctioned and the most preferred player takes home a hefty booty. But does winning the most sought-after player generate the expected performance on the field? Yes may not be the correct answer every time. Pat Cummins, the most expensive and sought-after player in the current season of the IPL was hit for 49 runs off his 18 balls recently. So, readers, does the auction winner actually win?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This is popularly known as the phenomenon of Winner&rsquo;s Curse. The bidder who wins an auction typically pays more than the asset is actually worth as repeated bidding results in overpaying for the asset, way more than the intrinsic value or true worth of an item. Regrettably, the winner&rsquo;s curse is typically most often realised after the fact. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Without going into details of the concept of economic game theory, the winner seems to be &lsquo;cursed&rsquo;, owing to incomplete information and bidder&rsquo;s emotions. At its core, the winner&rsquo;s curse is a combination of cognitive and emotional friction. The buyer is victorious in owning whatever asset they are&nbsp;bidding on. However, the asset is likely worth far less in resale value after ownership due to different factors affecting the purchase and influencing its value in the future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958618/ccqbgiprfr5lccdyhk6u.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 618px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The asset may be an IPL player, a piece of art, real estate, jewellery or a stock! The stock market is also one big auction, where one bids and the highest bidder wins and is the owner of that financial asset.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Pricing of IPOs is often marred by the winner&rsquo;s curse phenomenon. Companies want to sell their shares at maximum price. No wonder, IPOs come when stock market is in bull phase and when sentiment of investors are running high.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The recent changes by SEBI in the allocation of multi-cap mutual funds will push up the prices for many mid-cap and small-cap stocks. Everyone has commenced re-adjusting their portfolios to cherry-pick the most coveted mid &amp; small-cap scrips. But is the overreaction leading to the price hike justified in the intrinsic values of these companies?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is often argued that investors become excessively optimistic (pessimistic) about future news announcements after a series of good (bad) news and send stock prices to unjustifiable high (low) levels. Once subsequent news becomes known, it is likely to contradict this optimism (pessimism) leading to the correction of mispricing in the long-run.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As prudent investors, it is imperative to evaluate your BATNA &ndash; Best Alternative To A Negotiated Agreement. If your best alternative to winning the auction is to not win the auction, then tailor your bidding accordingly to head off the &ldquo;need to succeed&rdquo; at all costs. Thus, emotions, irrationalities, rumours, and other subjective factors can push prices far beyond their true values. To avoid becoming the next victim of the winner&rsquo;s curse, follow these three principles:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Knowing the true value or the fair price of the asset you are bidding for is quite crucial before you even go for it. Appropriate research and analysis should be done to be clear in the mind, not get swayed and stick to the decisions made</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Demarcate between your emotional mind and the rational mind. As soon as you start placing your first bid, you should know where to draw the line. This would help you hold your grounds more firmly.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Be sure of how important it is for you to win. Rational arguments are always better when you are in a confused state of mind.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So dear investors, let&rsquo;s stay away from &lsquo;winner&rsquo;s curse&rsquo; and be rational winners that are blessed with the alphas in their returns!&nbsp;<img alt=\"????\" draggable=\"false\" role=\"img\" src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/14.0.0/svg/1f642.svg\" style=\"height: 15px; width: 15px;\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958745/bikwpcfuuwb1wra2zddr.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Who Won? – I Did. OR Did I?","seo_keywords":"Who Won? – I Did. OR Did I?","seo_description":"This is popularly known as the phenomenon of Winner’s Curse. The bidder who wins an auction typically pays more than the asset is actually worth as repeated bidding results in overpaying for the asset, way more than the intrinsic value or true worth of an item. Regrettably, the winner’s curse is typically most often realised after the fact.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958744/qbc4hqnoixpk9afwrlw7.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"177","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (17/9/20)","slug":"charts-interesting-stories-markets-investing","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1600349185","published_date_view":"Sep 17, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please find below&nbsp;5&nbsp;charts&nbsp;that tell interesting stories on Markets and Investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) New SEBI guidelines to benefit Small Cap, Mid Cap and Multi Cap</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958908/wk0ng6vigvedwfsntdrm.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 867px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source- Ventura Securities</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per new SEBI Guidelines, Multicap Mutual Funds will have to compulsorily invest 25% each in Large Cap, Mid Cap and Small Cap by 31st January 2021.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per the above chart, currently, Multicap Funds have investment of ~7% in Small Cap and ~17% in Mid Cap Fund. Because of this new guideline, ~Rs. 39,000 Crores is expected to move into Mid Caps and Small Caps from Large Caps.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The whole amount may not move because some schemes will also change their category. But overall, its a good positive move for Mid Caps and Small Caps.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In 2018, a SEBI guideline on categorization had led to outflow from Mid Caps and Small Caps which had impacted their performance.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Earnings Yield for Equity in India:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958930/adz1jumqbas4o5gawjaq.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 277px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; ICICI Securities Research</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the Earnings Yield (Earnings of company divided by share price) of companies across different market capitalization.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Presently, yield for Small Caps is 5.9% and for Mid Cap its 5.2%. This is better than the yield of Large Cap which is currently at 4.1%. The margin of safety is higher for Mid Caps and Small Caps.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Also, the current yield in equity is close to the bond yields, this will lead to money moving from bonds to equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Performance of Indian Equity in 2020:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958953/sh6ed1gsdhnz6gwtli0d.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 628px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Ngen Research</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the movement of Large Caps, Mid Caps and Small Caps since 1st January 2020.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Small Caps and Mid Caps have delivered better return in comparison to Large Caps in 2020.This is a good rally for Small Caps and Mid Caps after underperformance in 2018 and 2019. Hopefully, the rally will continue.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Sensex performance in US Dollar terms for last 13 Years:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958977/znzu1j6b0kek9e3fug0f.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 722px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Investing.com</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows historical movement of Sensex in US Dollar.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sensex in Dollar is still at almost 2007 level. This means that there has been no wealth creation for Indian equity investors in the last 13 years. In rupee terms, Sensex has given a CAGR Return of ~5% in last 13 years. The return of ~5% in rupee has come due to devaluation of rupee against US Dollar.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the last 13 years, US equity market has given a CAGR return of ~11.5% in rupee denomination.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Microsoft Share Price:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687958996/acsrnvlsycpy7sc0r55s.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 631px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Ritholtz</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the Microsoft share price percentage change from the peak.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Microsoft was in a drawdown for 15 years between 2000 and 2015. The stock did not give any return in 15 years. The stock also crashed by ~75% from the peak in 2009.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, during these 15 years, Microsoft as a company performed well and had good growth in earnings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Share price growth and earnings growth of a company are two different things. The divergence can be high in shorter term.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Market timing and long term view is important for wealth creation.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Take care and stay safe.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959101/jj2b0gu3es8fhcfkxyjs.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (17/9/20)","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (17/9/20)","seo_description":"As per the above chart, currently, Multicap Funds have investment of ~7% in Small Cap and ~17% in Mid Cap Fund. Because of this new guideline, ~Rs. 39,000 Crores is expected to move into Mid Caps and Small Caps from Large Caps.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959099/ql1igko7som0roudnqqf.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"178","title":"The Indian Economic Jungle – Pink Flamingos following the Black Swan!","slug":"the-indian-economic-jungle-pink-flamingos-following-the-black-swan","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1600090312","published_date_view":"Sep 14, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Readers we are not planning to take you through a virtual jungle safari. But, it seems the financial world we live in is no less than one in the current times! The Covid-19 catastrophe has led to an unprecedented fall in the GDP growth numbers for India. We may consider the break-out of this devastating pandemic a black swan event. But the consequences that we are facing and may continue to face on the macroeconomic front are the jarring pink flamingos following the atrocious black swan (pun intended)!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959344/nn7qwoogmep9elacwojo.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 788px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Black Swan, a popular term in the financial jargon, refers to a highly improbable event with a major impact. On the other hand, Pink Flamingos refer to a predictable event that is ignored due to cognitive biases of a senior leader or a group of leaders trapped by powerful institutional forces. So, if the pandemic break-out is the black swan, the &lsquo;obvious&rsquo; macro-economic spill-overs are the pink flamingos. As an investor, we must learn to deal with both while on this financial safari. The plummeting of the GDP growth rate, increasing upward pressure on the inflation, RBI&rsquo;s monetary policy actions, corporates slow pace of reviving the production, and more are all the contagion effect of the pandemic. We must not be surprised by these pink flamingos rather be prepared for these macroeconomic shocks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The Black Swan event usually sits at the tail of the financial curve. If we plot out that chart, the &lsquo;tail risk&rsquo; appears on either side of the mean. Tails refer to the end portions of the distribution curves, showing the probabilities of variety of outcomes. The tail risk represents the chance that a dramatic, unexpected event can cause a significant swing in value. These &lsquo;black swan&rsquo; events are rare, but very important. However, what takes the centre stage are the tails, and most of us investors are rather worried about the left tails only. We must sharpen our focus on not what tail risk is but what it means for the investment decisions. It is both critical and smart to not ignore these highly impactful and highly improbable events!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Making investment decisions based on the expected outcome as measured by the averages can lead to huge portfolio losses. One can often make money in trades that have horrible remote loss scenarios but excellent expected returns. Extreme outcomes with low probability should be given importance in such situations. This is an important learning from such &lsquo;black swan&rsquo; events. As nonagenarian Warren Buffett mentions &ndash;&nbsp;<em><strong>&lsquo;Many people don&rsquo;t think deeply enough about the&nbsp;consequences&nbsp;of&nbsp;remote loss scenarios. Instead, they only focus on&nbsp;weighted average expected returns&nbsp;which look so good because the&nbsp;weights&nbsp;of the remote loss scenario are so&nbsp;small&nbsp;in the expected value table.&rsquo;</strong></em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The black swan is an occurrence where nothing in the past could convincingly suggest it could have happened and its impact is massive. Economies have stalled, markets have plunged and there is widespread panic across asset classes. The macroeconomic tail risk i.e. the left tail of the distribution is positively correlated with slack in financial conditions. Financial conditions create downside risk to the economy. And when the distribution is not normal, all the analysis based on this assumption of normality fails.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959366/j2m8ddy8y65j3se016jr.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 672px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Left tail events have had a devastating impact on portfolio returns, impeding investors&rsquo; potential to achieve their financial objectives. How well we manage these unlikely outcomes largely defines us.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959390/lg1bwxuyxw89dhw5vitw.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 635px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As an investor, we must be aware about the tail risk, and not be influenced by averages and standard deviation but focus on what appears to be realistically possible. We must identify our degree of risk tolerance &ndash; whether your portfolio has the capacity to bear losses up to and including the left tail or not. If you have that risk appetite then stay invested for the long term. It is often difficult to find refuge or seek protection in any asset class in the financial upheaval but while you do security selection &ndash; look for extreme volatility/ values in the returns, and the frequency of its occurrence, i.e. how fat the tail is and with that awareness make the investment decision. Another alternative is to identify sectors which are antifragile. In simpler terms, the sectors that gain in this VUCA (&ldquo;Volatile,&rdquo; &ldquo;Uncertain,&rdquo; &ldquo;Complex,&rdquo; and &ldquo;Ambiguous.&rdquo;) world. These sectors &ndash; the known knowns are our pink flamingos as well in the current scenario. In contrast to the downside beta, one can look at tail beta, which measures co-movement with the market if the downturns are extreme.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, readers, let&rsquo;s not get swayed by the black swan event we are in. These tail risk events should be hedged appropriately and treated as an opportunity to make higher returns. Besides, it&rsquo;s more critical to keep our eyes open to the pink flamingos that shall follow.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Here&rsquo;s wishing us all abundant luck to survive the Indian Economic Jungle!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Best Regards</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959461/fzusfam8xbdpm0rqjudy.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Indian Economic Jungle – Pink Flamingos following the Black Swan!","seo_keywords":"The Indian Economic Jungle – Pink Flamingos following the Black Swan!","seo_description":"Readers we are not planning to take you through a virtual jungle safari. But, it seems the financial world we live in is no less than one in the current times! The Covid-19 catastrophe has led to an unprecedented fall in the GDP growth numbers for India. We may consider the break-out of this devastating pandemic a black swan event. But the consequences that we are facing and may continue to face on the macroeconomic front are the jarring pink flamingos following the atrocious black swan (pun intended)!","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959458/ru0qcewbzxxgdcarulua.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"179","title":"Risk Reduction in Equity","slug":"risk-reduction-in-equity","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1599226673","published_date_view":"Sep 04, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the last 6 months, Indian Equity has experienced the highest volatility in its history. Sensex fell from ~41500 to ~26000 and now has bounced back to ~39500 level. The same can be seen as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959550/njjgjp6oirso5kvxl8ev.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 448px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Market corrected due to Covid in March, 20. Since then it has recovered primarily because of global liquidity and also because equity market is forward looking.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We took advantage of this market volatility by buying equity when Sensex was at ~35000 and ~28000. Also, the monthly SIP &amp; STPs of last 6 months have got invested in equity when market was down.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>We feel that equity market may experience some volatility in short term because of following reasons:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Presidential elections on 3rd November, 20</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">There is a risk that recovery of Indian economy and corporate earnings may not happen as anticipated.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity market has gone up by 50% from the bottom of March 2020 in just 5 months. This is very fast.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Risk of reduction in global liquidity</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We feel that the worst is behind us and even if any correction happens then it won&rsquo;t be deep like what we saw in March, 20.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>However, we continue to be bullish on Indian Equity from a long term perspective and feel that it will give high returns because of following reasons:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">From economy perspective, every day is going to be a better day because we will be getting closer to vaccine and unlocking of economy will continue.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The valuations are fair and not expensive. Specifically, large cap is fairly valued and mid &amp; small caps are undervalued.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Indian equity market has not given meaningful return in last 10 years and mean reversion may happen soon.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Low commodity prices, low interest rate, devalued rupee and ample liquidity is good for the Indian economy and will help in faster recovery.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Keeping the above scenario in mind, it is recommended that we reduce the risk in our equity portfolio by taking following actions:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sell 10% of current equity exposure.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Redeploy the above redemption proceed back in Equity in a staggered manner through 10 months STP</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Reduce exposure in Indian large cap and US funds (If completed 3 years)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Redeploy through STP in Indian focused, multi cap, mid cap, small cap and emerging market funds.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Only those equity funds to be exited which are exit load free and have low tax.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">There is also a possibility that we may not see any correction and equity market continues to go up. We would like to emphasise that this is an equity risk reduction strategy which will help us in reducing the volatility in portfolio and may also help in getting better return if market corrects.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959663/ojq4u9kprwrfbycfjdeg.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Risk Reduction in Equity","seo_keywords":"Risk Reduction in Equity","seo_description":"In the last 6 months, Indian Equity has experienced the highest volatility in its history. Sensex fell from ~41500 to ~26000 and now has bounced back to ~39500 level. The same can be seen as under:","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959661/vgpn6y0bn62zs34sxmv5.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"180","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (1/9/20)","slug":"charts-markets-investing","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1599054067","published_date_view":"Sep 02, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 charts that tell interesting stories on markets and investing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Global Growth Rate in Q2</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959789/ixehsdlzcjxqe69rykfa.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 1290px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>#Source &ndash; Charlie Bilello</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India reported a GDP growth of -23.9%. This is worst performing among major global economies. The primary reasons for same are strict lockdown and very less fiscal stimulus by Government.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Business Resumption in India:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959813/y52ztp8sl1rvxdsjzhee.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 723px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that the Business Resumption Index of India is currently at 75.7% in comparison to pre Covid level. There has not been meaningful improvement in last 2 months.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This is going to be challenging for India especially when the daily number of Covid cases are highest in the world.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Historical Earnings of Nifty Companies:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959833/qjxxht6lejpwfj9urysr.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 392px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>#Source &ndash; Trendlyne</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the historical movement of earnings for Nifty companies. The corporate earnings were almost flat between 2014 and 2019. These were wash out years for India Incorporation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to Covid, the earnings have fallen significantly. Corporate earnings in India need to bounce back significantly and have a lot to catch up.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Technology adoption in US households:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959866/rjmbsgubhveb9vs3uk9d.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 763px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the adoption rate of new technology in US. Electricity took almost 50 years to reach out to everyone. Adoption of recent technologies like Social Media and Tablet has been very quick.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This means that disruption due to technology is happening faster. Big tech companies like FAMANG (Facebook, Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, Netflix, Google) need to continuously innovate to stay on top and new small tech companies can suddenly become big like Tesla, Spotify, Shopify, Zoom etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Daily new cases of Covid in US:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959887/hyozaorecsgfphnldhge.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 600px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>#Source &ndash; Worldometers</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the daily new Covid cases in US. The second wave of Covid cases is slowing down. This will have impact on US elections in November 2020 which may further have impact on global markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Mukesh Jindal&nbsp;CFA, CFP, CAIA, Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959986/p6imnvebyecc11mvv3jy.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (1/9/20)","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing (1/9/20)","seo_description":"This means that disruption due to technology is happening faster. Big tech companies like FAMANG (Facebook, Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, Netflix, Google) need to continuously innovate to stay on top and new small tech companies can suddenly become big like Tesla, Spotify, Shopify, Zoom etc.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687959984/bphztsxr9xecysw9udka.webp","created_at":"Jun 28, 2023"},{"blog_id":"181","title":"RBI’s Conundrum: Growth vs Inflation","slug":"rbi-conundrum-growth-vs-inflation","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1598763760","published_date_view":"Aug 30, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Though the dichotomous policy puzzle of growth versus inflation may not be new for the Reserve Bank of India, in the present pandemic times, the complexity to manoeuvre through this policy maze has amplified manifolds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><a href=\"https://alphacapital.in/blog/the-covid-catastrophe-an-opportunity/\">Covid-19</a>&nbsp;has adversely impacted the entire world with most economies and industries are under severe stress. India being no different. The GDP growth is expected to slip in the negative for the FY 2020-21, first time in the history of independent India, squashing our dream to be a $5 trillion economy by 2023.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">To revive economic growth, there are two major policy tools &ndash; the fiscal policy and the monetary policy. Readers, lets take you through some basics of macroeconomics for you to better appreciate the dilemma of our policy makers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The economic policy puzzle is best solved by having an optimal mix of the monetary policy and the fiscal policy. RBI spears ahead the monetary policy while the Government takes care of the action at the fiscal policy front.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The amalgamation of the two policy framework can be explained from the IS-LM framework (popularly know as Hicks-Hansen model). The IS-LM framework is the key for the economy to tide over the current growth-inflation stand-off. Both the IS and LM curve are drawn on the interest rate &ndash; output space.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688015696/emykxwnp0ivxrvl1mmca.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 698px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The IS curve is the Investment Savings Curve for the economy representing the goods market that gets moved when the fiscal policy changes. An expansionary fiscal policy shifts the curve outward while a contractionary fiscal policy shifts the curve inwards.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Similarly, the LM curve or the Liquidity &amp; Money Supply curve (representing in the money market) is the tool with the RBI to move the output and interest levels of the economy. An expansionary monetary policy such as reduction in interest rates shifts the LM curve to the right while a contractionary moneraty policy shifts the LM curve to the left.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Coming back to the current situation being faced by India. Already, prior to the pandemic, not all was hunky-dory with the economy. The economic growth was slipping and RBI had initiated gradual reduction in the key policy rates to revive growth. Since February 2019, the repo rate had been gradually reduced from 6.25% to 5.15% in October 2019. And then further from 5.15% to 4% post the advent of the pandemic. However, is it really translating into the economic growth revival? Only time will tell.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688015730/ldaisukljuejxmjlotmk.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 712px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Though RBI has managed to pump in liquidity in the system through its various measures, in the current economic scenario this may be necessary but not a sufficient action to revive growth keeping the inflation within the tolerable limits. An optimal stitching of the fiscal policy along with the monetary policy is what is required at this juncture.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Continuous reduction in interest rate is not desirable &ndash; this will lead to a surge in inflation if the economic production does keep pace, leading us into the vicious circle of stagflation. Since the monetary policy measures start showing results in the economy with a lag of a few quarters, it is prudent to hold on the rate cuts, let the decisions seep in the economic system, and let the fiscal policy measures be used to boost government spending and increase investment and consumption demand for the economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So readers, it is time to trust our experienced policy makers to make the right changes in the macroeconomic variables that would overhaul the entire cycle and bring India back on the desired growth trajectory.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Taunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688015828/mm4u40jlywidmlwcff8u.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"RBI’s Conundrum: Growth vs Inflation","seo_keywords":"RBI’s Conundrum: Growth vs Inflation","seo_description":"Covid-19 has adversely impacted the entire world with most economies and industries are under severe stress. India being no different. The GDP growth is expected to slip in the negative for the FY 2020-21, first time in the history of independent India, squashing our dream to be a $5 trillion economy by 2023.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688015805/kl85jaf3q7fjacbo6mha.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"182","title":"Equity Market & PB Ratio – Valuation and Performance Analysis","slug":"equity-market-pb-ratio-valuation-and-performance-analysis","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1597814232","published_date_view":"Aug 19, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016135/feibg9han5oco5refwzz.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity Market has seen a good rally after correction in March, 2020 due to Covid. The biggest question running in the mind of investors right now is whether equity exposure should be reduced. In this article, we try to figure out the answer to this question by using the indicator PB Ratio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Price to Book (PB) Ratio helps in understanding how many times the stock is trading over and above the company&rsquo;s book value. The PB Ratio is calculated by dividing the current market price of stock with book value per share of the company.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">PB Ratio is a good indicator for valuation of a company or the broad equity market. If PB Ratio is trading at a value higher than long term average of the ratio then asset is overvalued. Similarly, a value below long term average is a sign of undervaluation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the current Covid times, the valuation indicator PB Ratio has become more meaningful especially because PE (Price to Earnings) Ratio has become irrelevant. The corporate earnings have fallen because of Covid and lockdown. This correction in earnings is short term and not structural. The earnings will again bounce back after 2-3 quarters. Since earnings have fallen, the PE Ratio has automatically gone up and is giving a false indication of overvaluation. Its better not to use PE Ratio till the time earnings normalize.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Here, we have tried to analyse the valuation of equity market on the basis of PB Ratio and the implications of same on future expected return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Current and long term average of PB Ratio for Nifty 50 &amp; NSE 500:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016155/bd8wmslzde2e3utx5svt.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 396px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that current PB Ratio of Nifty is 3.21 and median PB Ratio is 3.4 (Median is favoured over average as it reduces the impact of outliers). Since current PB Ratio is below long term median, it can be said that Nifty is undervalued.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Similarly, for NSE 500 which is a broader and preferred index, the current PB Ratio is 3.05 and median PB Ratio is 3.04. This shows that broader equity market is fairly valued.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Scatter Plot of NSE 500 and 5 Years Return</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016179/itcb8kthi1f2ml1ntmqn.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 559px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above scatter plot shows the relationship between PB Ratio and investment return after 5 Years. The above chart shows that correlation between PB Ratio and 5 years return is high and both of them are inversely proportional. When PB Ratio is high then future 5 years return is low and vice versa.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Statistically, R Square (R2) which measures the strength of relationship between two variables is at 70% for the above model. In simple language, PB Ratio can predict next 5 years of return with 70% accuracy. This is meaningful and relevant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above scatter plot also shows that at current PB Ratio of 3, the future expected return for next 5 years is ~9% per annum and minimum expected return is ~4% per annum. This is a prediction with 70% accuracy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Range of Return at different PB Ratios:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016210/hzeaw3eq4m1iryladzfc.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 194px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows average, maximum and minimum 5 years return at different PB Ratios. The average 5 years return in equity is 11%. The return increases when investment is made at low PB Ratio and reduces when investment is made in high PB Ratio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Investment Implications:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The key investment implications from above study are as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1) Currently, equity market is fairly valued. The market has run up since correction in March, 2020. But despite the rally, equity market is not in overvalued zone. Its not the time to reduce equity exposure but to stay invested in Equity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2) Exposure in equity should be changed based on PB Ratio valuation. Future 5 years expected return is inversely proportional to PB Ratio. Accordingly, exposure should be increased in equity at low PB Ratio and decreased at high PB Ratio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">3) Since, current PB Ratio of NSE 500 is close to long term average, investors are recommended to stick to their policy Asset Allocation.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Neeru Seal &amp; Dr. Mukesh Jindal</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016322/butr0idmm2sqtwhhzixy.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Equity Market & PB Ratio – Valuation and Performance Analysis","seo_keywords":"Equity Market & PB Ratio – Valuation and Performance Analysis","seo_description":"In the current Covid times, the valuation indicator PB Ratio has become more meaningful especially because PE (Price to Earnings) Ratio has become irrelevant. The corporate earnings have fallen because of Covid and lockdown. This correction in earnings is short term and not structural. The earnings will again bounce back after 2-3 quarters. Since earnings have fallen, the PE Ratio has automatically gone up and is giving a false indication of overvaluation. Its better not to use PE Ratio till the time earnings normalize.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016320/a8huix9oovgqvflorf8e.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"183","title":"Let’s Take A Time Machine – Conversation in Future","slug":"lets-take-a-time-machine-conversation-in-future","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1597728332","published_date_view":"Aug 18, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016411/aabexkepnpxxhv3bauhr.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 810px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It&rsquo;s Diwali 2025. Shweta &amp; Akshay are driving for their annual card party get-together with friends. An excerpt from their conversation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: I love this car! Every time I drive this, it feels so good &ndash; it&rsquo;s absolutely amazing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: I am sure! Glad we went ahead for this couple of years back. These E-vehicles have totally changed the landscape of automobiles in our country.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: Certainly&hellip; and also helps our country save in a few billion dollars of all the oil imports!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: Haha&hellip; Yea&hellip;true&hellip;. Mr. Economist Husband! You can bring in the economics in everything we talk.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: Yea&hellip;it&rsquo;s my job my darling Educationist!! Haven&rsquo;t you felt the remarkable changes in your work area? The entire education sector has lapped up to technology like never before. What seemed as a stop-gap arrangement to maneuver through the pandemic blues few years back, has become the new normal now.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: Yea, the education landscape has totally changed post the pandemic of 2020. I see my students &ndash; face masks, sanitizers, social distancing and maintaining hygiene with greater caution. All this has been engrained so well to the young children. They are hands on the technology &ndash; and most exciting is they are more concerned and more aware about the social health and environmental issues. The virus outbreak of 2020 seems to have changed so much for us Indians. It was so scary back then&hellip;. I often reminisce about the chaos year 2020 brought in for us.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: Chaos year??!! You always like to look at the glass as half empty. Look at the positive side as well. I see an opportunity that could have been reaped much better. Look at all the progress our economy has made since then. In May 2020, who would have imagined that Sensex would cross the iconic 50000 mark by 2022 and who be nearing the 60000 mark by 2025. Its over 100% jump in the Sensex from the nadir it created during the covid-19 impacted period in 2020. Sitting today I can easily say that it was really silly for most of us to stop all our SIPs at that time. By the time we decided to resume our SIP investments, we had lost out on most of the sharp dips &ndash; which could have been such lucrative entry points.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: Yea&hellip; you are right. It&rsquo;s really important to keep calm and not panic during such times. In hindsight it truly feels good for our slightly delayed but cautious investment decisions. After all,&nbsp;<em>Better late than Never</em>. An even analysis proves this &ndash; be it the Global Financial Crisis of 2008 or the Covid-19 impact in the world markets, the volatility experienced during those few months scared most of the investors. But if we behave as long term investors, we must zoom out on the entire chart of the equity markets &ndash; that clearly highlights the recovery, rebound and rise of the markets, indicating its resilience from such shocks.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: True&hellip; look at our portfolios. We have made such good gains since 2020. The investments made then are reaping us good returns. You must thank those investments for our last year&rsquo;s Masai-Mara&rsquo;s adventures!!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: Haha&hellip;.absolutely&hellip; it was so much fun!! And look at the other asset classes as well&hellip;gold..?? It has shown such amazing returns over the last few years. I am so glad we made those investment in 2019 in the Sovereign Gold Bonds. We are benefiting from regular returns plus the appreciation gains.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: True&hellip; that&rsquo;s why it&rsquo;s important to sensibility diversify the investment portfolio. And always believe in strategic SIPs, and not just standard SIPs. Enter the market &ndash; whatever be the investment asset &ndash; at the right time! Look at ESG investments that had become the flavor of all investors five years back.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: Absolutely&hellip;even we try to sensitize our children at school about the environment related issues. The world has been witnessing so many environment related issues &ndash; global warming leading to bushfires in our forests, melting of glaciers causing unprecedented floods, earthquake catastrophes, and so much more. The corona virus totally shook the entire health system of the world &ndash; sensitizing people and corporates towards social responsibility took a totally different meaning since then.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: Yes, after all we all are stakeholders of this planet. We must take care of it and keep the same in mind while making prudent investment decisions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: The market has rewarded stocks with steady business performance and quality growth, irrespective of their market capitalisation. Companies with good, clean managements were rewarded handsomely by the markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A: Also, look at the pace at which investments in international equity and digital assets has risen in last five years! We couldn&rsquo;t envisage this rapid growth at that point in time. These are becoming an acceptable asset class for any retail investor&rsquo;s portfolio diversification!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">S: Absolutely! Lesson learnt &ndash;&nbsp;<em>One should&nbsp;<strong>ACT</strong>&nbsp;not&nbsp;<strong>REACT</strong></em>.&nbsp;<em>Long-term investment success is almost totally a function of how one emotionally handles declines in the equity market, as opposed to how one&rsquo;s portfolio handles them.</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Shweta and Akshay may still take some time to reach their destination. Meanwhile, let us not miss the bus!!!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Swing back to the present now &ndash; August 2020, and catch up on the opportunities that are being thrown up in the markets.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016506/mc51a5g14tcl1jd5hivv.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Let’s Take A Time Machine – Conversation in Future","seo_keywords":"Let’s Take A Time Machine – Conversation in Future","seo_description":"Yea… you are right. It’s really important to keep calm and not panic during such times. In hindsight it truly feels good for our slightly delayed but cautious investment decisions. After all, Better late than Never. An even analysis proves this – be it the Global Financial Crisis of 2008 or the Covid-19 impact in the world markets, the volatility experienced during those few months scared most of the investors. But if we behave as long term investors, we must zoom out on the entire chart of the equity markets – that clearly highlights the recovery, rebound and rise of the markets, indicating its resilience from such shocks.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016504/o2hyamorxud3qxdaxloh.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"184","title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","slug":"5-charts-interesting-stories-on-markets-and-investing","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1597123715","published_date_view":"Aug 11, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5 charts that tell interesting stories on markets and investing.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Business Resumption in India:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016644/ph2zc9roa6wzfycuuvek.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 566px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that businesses in India are now operating at 70% of pre-Covid level. The activity level had fallen to 45% in April, 20. Indian economy is showing good progress. Hopefully, business resumption Index should touch 100 in next 1-2 quarters.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Time Travel to Past for Indian Equity</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016665/v3izhvzvgm12ewl2ruwp.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 489px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Indian Equity Market is having a good rally since 24<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;March 2020. Despite this rally, the current Nifty is still at 2018 level, Nifty Mid Cap is at 2016 level and Nifty Small Cap is at 2014 level.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">There is a lot of ground to be covered by Indian Equity. Its time to stay invested in Indian Equity for long term and participate in the expected upside.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) World Equity Market Valuation</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016684/phi5ix3bmn9aycd1hepk.webp\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 857px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows Warren Buffett Valuation Indicator &ndash; Market Cap to GDP Ratio for major world economies. For India, the ratio is at 69 which was at 92 a year ago and 3 years back it was at 134. The long term average of Market Cap to GDP Ratio for India is ~70. So it can be said that Indian equity market is fairly valued.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The chart also shows that valuation for US market is stretched and China is at reasonable valuation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>4) Impact of Dollar Weakening:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016706/p2hxuyv5gptwzq7d0eqx.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 472px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Dollar has been weakening against global currencies lately because of balance sheet expansion by US Fed. US has been printing dollars to support fiscal and monetary stimulus. The US Dollar may continue to weaken if US continues with extended fiscal stimulus and may strengthen in case of recovery of economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the impact of US Dollar on different assets. When US Dollar is down then Emerging Markets and Gold get maximum benefit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>5) Covid Vaccine Status</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016747/yjr2senmmkqeneahnzqo.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 483px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the status of Covid vaccine globally. Vaccine of Astra Zeneca/ Oxford University is in Phase III and closest to approval. Chinese vaccines are also in an advanced stage. The Indian vaccines are in pre-clinical testing.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016843/yxuxlqc9rlanhhdg6mss.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_keywords":"5 Charts – Interesting Stories on Markets and Investing","seo_description":"The above chart shows that businesses in India are now operating at 70% of pre-Covid level. The activity level had fallen to 45% in April, 20. Indian economy is showing good progress. Hopefully, business resumption Index should touch 100 in next 1-2 quarters.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016839/jtp2nduzkrbliour9e62.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"185","title":"Trust the Lollapalooza Effect!","slug":"trust-the-lollapalooza-effect","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1596778454","published_date_view":"Aug 07, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016944/jtycjwack2kldnksru70.jpg\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 720px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&lsquo;If the result you are observing is a Lollapalooza, look for the confluence of multiple causes and multiple factors operating in the same direction&rsquo; &ndash; Charlie Munger</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We will shortly enter into a new world &ndash; the post COVID world. Hoping this &lsquo;shortly&rsquo; comes sooner than soon! The world economic order has been shaken and the strongest of the developed world economies are struggling to get the economic growth on track. China is bearing the brunt for the COVID created chaos and has lost out on trust of the investors. The recent border dispute with India too has dented its image in the world.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the current pandemic scenario, we have shown tremendous resilience and the entire world has looked up to India to steer ahead. We are at the cusp of rebooting the world economic growth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688016983/qkmvkdk1ihjukxciavdx.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 747px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So, what&rsquo;s working for India? Should we trust the lollapalooza effect to catalyse our economic growth engine in the next few years? Lollapalooza effect was coined by the renowned investor Charles Munger aka Charlie. He often attaches the word &ldquo;effects&rdquo; (as in &ldquo;lollapalooza effects&rdquo;) which means that multiple factors are acting together in ways that are feeding back on each other. In simple words, lollapalooza effect is an outcome which is far bigger than the sum of the parts, as in 2+2 is not equal to 4 (linear) but 22 (exponential).&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Using this mental construct of lollapalooza, one can explain the cause-effect relationship behind extreme events in the world. Not only explain, but Lollapalooza helps us understand the workings of this complex world so that we can leverage that for our benefit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Several factors are working simultaneously in favour of India: strong image in the world &ndash; stable government and leadership perception &ndash; robust macro-economic fundamentals &ndash; steady and sustained capital inflows &ndash; favourable impact on current account surplus due to the drop in oil prices &ndash; reduced terms of trade with China &ndash; looking inwards at our core strength of huge demographic dividend to be reaped from the young workforce &ndash; the rapid pace of digitization &ndash; supportive sectoral policies &ndash; good monsoons for the agriculture-dependent industries &ndash; declining interest rates to boost liquidity in the banking sector and push investment &ndash; channelling of surplus liquidity by RBI through the banking system- kick start growth &ndash; higher investments in economic and social infrastructure, and many more.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">These green shoots are clearly visible for the Indian economy to chart a sustainable growth path ahead and lead the world out of the current pandemic created economic slowdown.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017006/xo6gstogf3ljn5v2umh2.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 606px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">However, not all may be hunky-dory by getting swirled in the whirlpool of lollapalooza. We have many cognitive biases that can sway our behaviour one way or another. All these psychological tendencies work at a subconscious level. We tend to make decisions based on readily available information. Munger believes the&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>&lsquo;lollapalooza effect&rsquo;</strong>&nbsp;</span>can result in herd mentality, the more individuals follow a certain idea/behaviour, the better we consider the idea to be!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With the advent of social media, everyone has the power to shout their opinions openly. The incessant noise from the TV channels, financial newspapers etc aggravates the&nbsp;<strong>recency bias and social validation</strong>&nbsp;in an investor&rsquo;s mind. But isolated facts get you nowhere. They need to come together on a framework of theory, to become usable. In the words of Emile Auguste Chartier:<strong>&lsquo;Nothing is more dangerous than an idea when it&rsquo;s the only one you have&rsquo;</strong><strong>.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Understanding the lollapalooza effect would assist in safeguarding ourselves from committing common mistakes and help find important investment opportunities. So, focus on buying quality and growth, avoid repeating expensive errors and be more confident while investing.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dear Investors, let&rsquo;s enjoy the Indian lollapalooza music festival, dance on the beats and beware of the noise!</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017104/pm1xagtbmqwnyz21uyy7.jpg","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Trust the Lollapalooza Effect!","seo_keywords":"Trust the Lollapalooza Effect!","seo_description":"We will shortly enter into a new world – the post COVID world. Hoping this ‘shortly’ comes sooner than soon! The world economic order has been shaken and the strongest of the developed world economies are struggling to get the economic growth on track. China is bearing the brunt for the COVID created chaos and has lost out on trust of the investors. The recent border dispute with India too has dented its image in the world.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017102/xczuqq53xskekesjdjid.jpg","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"186","title":"Two Important Questions of Equity Investor in the Covid Crisis – Answered","slug":"two-important-questions-of-equity-investor-in-the-covid-crisis-answered","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1595137473","published_date_view":"Jul 19, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017300/qx5pukw4rjwbrwkj7wcp.jpg\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 713px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Everyone is going through a different journey in this pandemic. Many are under the trap of Covid Virus and many more are trapped under the side effects of Covid.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Salaries have either gone for a toss or have reduced. Businessmen are severely affected because they carry the responsibility of many other people working for their factories/organisations. Paying salary from the savings without any inflow is like cutting a heart. I wonder how long will they continue to bleed. I pray for everyones well being and fast recovery from this mayhem.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Some concerns which investors have shown during this crisis are very genuine and accordingly its important to make best efforts to guide the investor to take right steps. Therefore, I have tried to pen down the two repeated questions which I have faced lately and have tried to judiciously answer them here.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><b>1) Why&nbsp;</b><b>didn&rsquo;t</b><b>&nbsp;we come out of equity market before the Covid crisis? Why didn&rsquo;t research team pick up this crisis in advance?</b></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">From the above question, we can easily sense that the query is related to the timing of market. Entering at bottom and exiting at top is a mission which investors always want us to perform. But its very difficult to perfectly time. I would like to state this as a MISSION IMPOSSIBLE.&nbsp; This is because, advisor being human being take decisions on the basis of available information, research and from his past experience.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The reason why we couldn&rsquo;t perfectly time the exit before the Covid crisis is as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">a) The receipt of information about Covid from World Health Organization was vague. In early days, WHO communicated that Covid virus was from the family of SARS, Ebola etc. and hence was not so contagious &amp; fatal.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">b) Information from the birthplace of COVID i.e. China was improper and incomplete. They were hiding the actual infections and death toll. We all know that China is a black box as far as information is concerned. The same can be related with the fact that till now they have not declared the number of Chinese army personnel who died recently in Galwan valley clash with India.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to above stated reasons, we couldn&rsquo;t manage to exit equity market before the Covid crisis. Even the biggest of investors like Warren Buffet, Ray Dalio, Howard Marks, Rakesh Jhunjhunwala etc. couldn&rsquo;t exit the equity before coronavirus crisis.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) What is the future prospect of recovery and what strategy one should play at this juncture?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Out of 15k level correction in Sensex, 11k level has already been recovered which is 73% of recovery from the peak of 41k level. Although strength of infectious people and deaths are increasing, but still market is recovering at a good pace.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This is majorly due to global liquidity, opening of lockdowns and acceptance of new normal by adaptable humans. This fast recovery clearly shows that no one can time the market and forecast its movement perfectly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors waiting for deep bottom in the market are still waiting and has lost major upside. Therefore rather than making any financial decisions on the basis of hunches, investor must stick to strategies that have been created after research, thinking and thorough planning, which are as follows: &ndash;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">a) Stock market has seen several corrections like this in the past and eventually it has always recovered. The same can be seen in below chart. So it is certain that market would eventually recover.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017344/i5psbcexxk9xtixo0ppt.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 434px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">b) After the crisis, equity market always recovers to a new high level i.e. it breaches the previous high level to touch new peak. Economy readjusts itself to a new and growth supporting reality where interest rates are low, oil prices are subdued, rupee is weakened which supports export, business models are new &amp; evolved etc. Once economy starts moving again, big investors like FIIs deploy more than what they had taken out at the time of downturn. For example,&nbsp; in 2008 crisis, FIIs sold $12 Bn in India and while recovery they deployed $43 Bn.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">c) Reallocation strategy provides extra edge over Rebalancing strategy. Under reallocation strategy, investor increases or decreases the equity allocation after inculcating the valuation and outlook of equity market. This strategy directs investor to deploy more money in equity when market is low and at an attractive valuation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Investors will always crave for a magical solution of timing the market perfectly but real strategies to be implemented are as follows:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Hold the existing equity investment.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Don&rsquo;t try to sell equity in falling market with a hope of buying even at further lower price.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Buy equity at meaningful correction to reduce overall cost price.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Do not try for bottom buying. Buy with every fall.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Only that money should be invested in equity, which is not required for next 5 years plus.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Keep enough liquidity for short-term requirement.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Enjoy wealth creation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Akhil Bhardwaj CFP, LLB</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Partner</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Capital</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017477/upt3m2ifpjffeajsja8p.jpg","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Two Important Questions of Equity Investor in the Covid Crisis – Answered","seo_keywords":"Two Important Questions of Equity Investor in the Covid Crisis – Answered","seo_description":"Salaries have either gone for a toss or have reduced. Businessmen are severely affected because they carry the responsibility of many other people working for their factories/organisations. Paying salary from the savings without any inflow is like cutting a heart. I wonder how long will they continue to bleed. I pray for everyones well being and fast recovery from this mayhem.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017475/hkmtkpzolb1prcbwdjnj.jpg","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"187","title":"Economic Disruption or Creative Destruction?","slug":"economic-disruption-or-creative-destruction","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1594359925","published_date_view":"Jul 10, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&lsquo;Economic progress in a capitalist society means turmoil&rsquo; &ndash; Joseph Schumpeter</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The mayhem caused in the world markets by the pandemic Covid-19 is being labelled as a major economic disruption &ndash; unprecedented to the human race alive on our planet.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The economic growth rates are expected to tumble sharply to negative for most major economies of the world. But readers, the perspective is a mind game. Is this really just an economic disruption? Or, is there a bigger picture to this disruption &ndash; creative destruction?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Creative destruction is an essential fact about capitalism as affirmed by the renowned economist Schumpeter. Creative destruction has been fundamental to rapid economic growth &ndash; including structural changes. The new technology, ideas, business models have to replace the incumbent for the growth engine to leap ahead.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017645/ro6hcoq0iykkmnsbyya6.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 514px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The current world scenario can easily be termed as a pandemic triggered creative destruction &ndash; destroying old products, techniques, business models, ways of thinking, etc and leading to an emergence of a totally new revived business models, products, technologies, etc. In fact, the current pandemic situation may lead to a major shift in the world economic order.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017665/neag16veh7re5wpwseow.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 624px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The existing covid-19 caused crisis has led to disruption in various sectors of the Indian economy. The outlook for the entire markets &ndash; both equity and debt has undergone a change. The sectors have been impacted differently and several opportunities have been created for the investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Conventional businesses with relatively low entry barriers are highly vulnerable. Fundamentally, strong companies can survive in this era of disruption by proactively acknowledging and investing in disruptive innovation. Investors need to pay attention to these trends, intensifying turmoil in the economy and devote time and money for harnessing returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The &lsquo;unicorn&rsquo; and &lsquo;decacorn&rsquo; phenomenon of highly valued disruptive start-ups indicates stepping up of turbulence. 18 Indian unicorns have emerged across different sectors and industries.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Recently, Accenture, in its report for India, published &lsquo;Disruptability index&rsquo;, which measures the current level of disruption, and susceptibility to future disruption. The research found that 44&nbsp;percent of companies are currently experiencing disruption, and 38 percent are susceptible to future disruption.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Readers, several trends are the driving force behind the creative destruction, ranging from the massive disruption in retail, increased digitalization, the rise of the software-enabled online platforms to the emergence of clean energy and increased globalisation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Disruptions encompassing technological advances, cloud computing and artificial intelligence indicate further turmoil enabling quick scaling up of operations, global reach and no geographical limitations in expansion.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Globally, the energy sector has witnessed a sharp decline in its weight in the index, as cleantech is gaining prominence and oil prices are descending. Increased investment in renewable sources has for the first time exceeded the traditional energy resources i.e. fossil fuels. The S&amp;P Global Clean Energy index confirms this trend with a one-year total return of 19.20% in contrast to -38.27% by the S&amp;P Global 1200 Energy Index, as on 3 July 2020. India is no exception to this trend.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017688/oclwjk8ibdjw6nksgo4h.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 667px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This understanding of disruptive innovation can be a powerful tool in the hands of the investors, for making investment decisions. Disruption is the new constant. Thanks to technology, the speed of change is accelerating and the breadth is also widening. Identifying business models and companies which pre-empt disruption and take advantage of it will be an important determinant to earn abnormal returns.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This is the time for a patient investor to look for sectors with new emerging business models and fundamentally strong companies for sustained advantage.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017757/duhtwl3hp5wyp5dhaegk.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Economic Disruption or Creative Destruction?","seo_keywords":"Economic Disruption or Creative Destruction?","seo_description":"The economic growth rates are expected to tumble sharply to negative for most major economies of the world. But readers, the perspective is a mind game. Is this really just an economic disruption? Or, is there a bigger picture to this disruption – creative destruction?","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017755/x0yndcs6tbqmx1sswbpn.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"188","title":"The COVID Catastrophe: An Opportunity??","slug":"the-covid-catastrophe-an-opportunity","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1593755432","published_date_view":"Jul 03, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017935/mrxp3veytvdiaxtax9kx.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 807px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The entire world has been grappling with the coronavirus pandemic. The world economic growth has plummeted. The sluggishly growing &lsquo;developed&rsquo; economies have been crippled. The &lsquo;high growth&rsquo; emerging economies are expected to slip in the negative. The unemployment rates have skyrocketed. The industries and businesses have been disrupted at an unprecedented level turning most business models topsy-turvy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The world hasn&rsquo;t seen a public health hazard of this enormous scale and spread in over a century. The world will remember 2020 as the new historical divide &ndash; Pre COVID &amp; Post COVID &ndash; with all economies, sectors, lifestyles majorly impacted.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Pre COVID &amp; Post COVID Divide:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688017966/vbt4ssh0ie1oagss1wzv.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 625px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Against this backdrop, the title of our article sounds bizarre. But readers, problem means opportunity! Let&rsquo;s look down at some historical data of major disruptions the world has faced since World War II. The major crisis in the past since &ndash; Asian Crisis, Financial Crisis etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>World GDP Growth &ndash; Quarterly</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018002/vo272p2pgpiimpnvkthw.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 385px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Fed, Bank of St Louis</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Besides, India too has faced four major slumps in the last 70 years since independence. Looking at the rate at which the GDP recovers from such slumps &ndash; &nbsp;a V-shaped recovery, W-shaped recovery or a swoosh shaped recovery is expected post the current pandemic driven slowdown. It can be clearly seen from the GDP growth (%) graph depicted below &ndash; the GDP growth rate plummets sharply during these economic shocks, however, it has strong resilience to bounce back the next year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>India GDP Movement and Annual Change</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018025/z7tz6fvkn11zknp5dosj.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 531px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This is an econometric concept wherein most of the macro-economic indicators are a stationary time series. Even if we consider that the nature &amp; severity of the current pandemic crisis across the globe, economy may take some time to reach back to the same trajectory. A swoosh shaped recovery is expected for India (if not a V-shaped or U shaped).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Different Shapes of Economy Recovery</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018049/ls6athkhftcc9vaihjiw.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 845px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Also, let&rsquo;s look at the assets returns &ndash; the way they rebound post a crisis. Markets are not alien to a crisis. Globally, markets have survived various crises like natural disasters, wars, terror attacks, and have bounced back stronger. Despite the Asian Currency Crisis (1997), 9/11 disaster (2001), the Global Financial Crisis (2008), US Sovereign Rating Downgrade (2011), China&rsquo;s Economic Slowdown (2015), and COVID-19 (2020), the Sensex has grown and moved up. &nbsp;The performance of Sensex since 1994 is shown in the graph depicted below.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Sensex Movement Since 1994</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018071/cavivr4xgao0cd30o22w.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 680px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Though, the other economic shocks as indicated in the graph may have had a limited geographical spread as compared to the current covid pandemic, it would be prudent to assume a steady and gradual recovery path in GDP growth rates and parallel in the asset returns across the globe.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So readers, its not the time to panic. It&rsquo;s an opportunity &ndash; it&rsquo;s the time to prevail! As investors &ndash; hold onto your horses &ndash; stay patient, don&rsquo;t panic and stay invested. These are opportune times for India and it is likely to attract massive investments in times to come. The Indian economy has robust fundamentals and is more resilient as compared to its peers. The industry will reboot, new sectors will flourish, business models will change, the investments will grow and the consumption driven economy of india will surely chart the revived growth path in times ahead.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Certainly readers &ndash; &lsquo;Stay Home! Stay Safe!&rsquo;. But also &ndash; &lsquo;Stay Calm! Stay Invested!&rsquo;.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Tarunika Jain Agarwal Ph.D.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Alpha Research</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018197/wdhs0wuomhlhruyoy8mc.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The COVID Catastrophe: An Opportunity??","seo_keywords":"The COVID Catastrophe: An Opportunity??","seo_description":"The entire world has been grappling with the coronavirus pandemic. The world economic growth has plummeted. The sluggishly growing ‘developed’ economies have been crippled. The ‘high growth’ emerging economies are expected to slip in the negative. The unemployment rates have skyrocketed. The industries and businesses have been disrupted at an unprecedented level turning most business models topsy-turvy.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018192/vrvtullgfcuzyf1b2omk.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"189","title":"Disconnect between Equity Market and Real Economy – Explained","slug":"disconnect-between-equity-market-and-real-economy-explained","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1592200604","published_date_view":"Jun 15, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018342/cacgpo02pcpdgnqwtbxl.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 656px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the last 30 days, Indian equity market had a good rally of ~10%. The market is now up by almost 30% from the bottom level which was touched on 23/3/20.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Movement of Nifty 500 for last 6 months is as under:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018365/g9rt6bxjq06eqyfquqcs.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 473px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><em>Source: NSE</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A common question going in the mind of majority of people is that why is the equity market going up when there is so much of gloom around. The Covid cases in India are rising on a daily basis, businesses are struggling to open, job cuts are happening etc. In such a bad scenario, why is the market cheering up so much? Is there no correlation between market and economy? Are markets manipulated?</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to us, there are two primary reasons for the rise of equity market despite weak economy. They are as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Huge and timely stimulus by US Fed</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">US Economy is centre of the world, any development in US affects the world economy. The impact is far higher in financial markets because the market capitalization of US Stock market is ~44% of the world market capitalization.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since the start of Covid crisis, US Fed has been very proactive in coming out with financial stimulus to support the economy and help in faster recovery. The same can be seen in following charts:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Huge Stimulus:</strong></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018390/tn0gswnarnhs0cktitii.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 551px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><em>Source: US Federal Reserve</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that the size of US Federal balance sheet has expanded from USD 3.7 Trillion to USD 7.1 Trillion in last few months as a response to Covid crisis. The Fed balance sheet expansion happens when US Fed prints dollars and buys bonds from open market to flush the economy with excess liquidity.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In last few months, the US Fed has printed almost similar amount of money than what was printed in last 100 years combined.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Timely Stimulus:</strong></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018415/u4wgvtey1jrrfai9qjeg.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 688px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><em>Source: Variant Perception</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above graph shows the excess liquidity in US around bear markets. It can be seen that in 2020, the liquidity support in US came immediately after the start of bear market. In 2008, the liquidity support came after almost 230 days. This timely action by US Fed, helped in less negative impact to the economy and financial system.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Increase in asset prices:</strong></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Due to increase of liquidity in the economy, the money started flowing to various assets. US Equity market represented by S&amp;P 500 has rebounded and is close to all time high as shown under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018436/kshho00hm4ydmajta2fk.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 471px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><em>Source: Google</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The liquidity has moved to emerging markets as well and accordingly the emerging market Index has gone up as shown below:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018463/itksqc2s10clxxkqyg5s.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 450px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><em>Source: MSCI Emerging Market Index</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Equity market is future looking:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In first point, we tried to explain the support of liquidity which helped in quick bounce back of equity market. This must be making us think that market is primarily driven by liquidity and it&rsquo;s a bubble in making as ground realities of economy are still not good.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above possibility cannot be completely ruled out but what we also need to consider is that equity market is future indicator of the economy. Equity market leads the economy by 6-12 months. This means that equity market moves ahead of the actual GDP or earnings growth. Equity market falls before the slowdown in corporate earnings and it also goes up before the increase of earnings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The same can be seen in following chart:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018484/oswnxbfpfowhkp6olcg5.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 782px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><em>*Source &ndash; Factset, US Market</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows that during Great Financial Crisis (GFC) of 2008, US S&amp;P 500 had started going ahead much before the improvement in corporate earnings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So there is a good possibility that markets have already discounted the negative growth in GDP for 2020 and is looking at positive growth of GDP from 2021 onwards. It should also be considered that liquidity and stimulus provided by Governments across the globe is in right direction as they help in faster revival of economy, consumptions and corporate earnings.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So is the worst over for equity market and will market continue to go up from here? The answer is we don&rsquo;t know about the same and it is impossible to predict. The market may get negatively affected if there is a second wave of Covid, US-China conflict or anything which slows the global economy growth.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For investors, it is important to follow the asset allocation strategy as per their risk profile and financial plan. It is important to stay invested in equity during this course of market volatility. Timing the market on the basis of future outlook is very difficult as future movement of market is dependent on too many permutations and combinations. The right way to time the market is on the basis of valuation. Investors should buy when market falls as valuations become attractive and book profit when market goes up as valuations get stretched.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing!</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018678/laxjyaz4sunjr6cmqbar.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Disconnect between Equity Market and Real Economy – Explained","seo_keywords":"Disconnect between Equity Market and Real Economy – Explained","seo_description":"A common question going in the mind of majority of people is that why is the equity market going up when there is so much of gloom around. The Covid cases in India are rising on a daily basis, businesses are struggling to open, job cuts are happening etc. In such a bad scenario, why is the market cheering up so much? Is there no correlation between market and economy? Are markets manipulated?","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018672/og68uisxspkkvsbtsljy.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"190","title":"Debt Funds, Returns & Defaults – Should We Worry?","slug":"debt-funds-returns-defaults-should-we-worry","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1588658742","published_date_view":"May 05, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since September 2019, debt funds have been experiencing lots of turbulence. Good AAA companies like IL&amp;FS, DHFL etc. have defaulted and companies like Yes Bank, Indiabulls etc. have come under radar. In the last 1 year, some debt funds which had exposure to toxic assets have seen negative return as well.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We will try to explain what is happening in the fixed income market and if we should be worried.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>How did this crisis begin?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The chain of events can be explained as under:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The first turbulence in fixed income market started in early September of 2018 when IL&amp;FS with a loan book of ~ Rs. 91,000 crores defaulted on loan dues.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This led to dip in investor confidence towards lending to Non-Banking Financial Services (NBFC) and Housing Finance Companies (HFC). Market liquidity suddenly evaporated for NBFCs &amp; HFCs.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors started redeeming from debt mutual funds which had exposure to questionable NBFCs &amp; HFCs and this led to increased pressure on them for repayment of Loans.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The NBFCs which had lending book with predominant exposure to real estate developers, home loans and infrastructure funding came into radar. The loans given by these NBFC had a long term tenure of 5-20 Years. And now suddenly NBFCs had liquidity pressure from mutual funds, banks, investors etc for repayment of loan.&nbsp; This led to Asset Liability Mismatch (ALM).</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Even NBFCs which had good assets came into problem because they didn&rsquo;t plan their cashflows well. They were borrowing for short term from the market and were lending for long term to their customers.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">NBFCs had lent heavily to real estate developers. With real estate sector going through a bad phase, developers were themselves not in a position to payback to NBFCs. Developers started defaulting which led to vicious circle of defaults leading to loss for retail and HNI investors.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Eventually, this resulted in loss of confidence for companies like DHFL, Reliance Capital, Indiabulls, Edelweiss, IIFL, Piramal Enterprise, Yes Bank etc.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Who is responsible for all this mess?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>&ldquo;Many times the Good we create leads to Evil that destroys us&rdquo;&nbsp;</em>&ndash; Amish Tripathi</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Demonetisation, RERA and GST were some of the policies introduced by Government in the last few years with the intention of reducing black economy and for increasing the compliance. Demonetisation led to huge cash in the bank accounts of people. For better return on this cash, the liquidity started moving to fixed deposits, debt mutual funds, equity mutual funds, equity shares etc. Sudden spurge in investment led to bubble everywhere. Banks started lending money aggressively to NBFCs which further started funding the real estate developers; debt mutual funds also started lending aggressively to real estate developers and NBFCs; equity market started going through a bull run etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The processes, due diligence, financial prudence etc. all got compromised during this aggressive lending by banks and mutual funds to NBFCs and real estate developers. Unfortunately, the gatekeepers like credit rating agencies, regulators, Government officials also didn&rsquo;t react on time to stop/ restrict the creation of financial bubble.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Directly or indirectly, majority of the lending was done to real estate. The whole of real estate sector has been going through pain in the last few years because of demand supply mismatch, higher compliance due to RERA and GST, reduction in black economy due to demonetisation etc. When main borrower is going through financial trouble then all the lenders get affected. This was the crux of all the trouble.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is the future outlook?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The current financial crisis is more like a confidence crisis. There is a complete loss of confidence in financial sector. People have become very risk averse and no one is ready to lend or invest in any NBFC or HFC which have higher exposure to real estate.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The fastest way to come out of this crisis is by getting Government support. Confidence building measures for financial sector by Government can ease the pain quickly the way it had happened in 2009 after subprime crisis. The Government has recognised the NBFC crisis and has taken some measures for improvement but they are still not substantial and concrete.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If Government doesn&rsquo;t extend support then NBFC crisis may continue for some more time.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The good news is that it has been a year since the crisis began. Its a known fact that time is the biggest healer. In the last 12 months, balance sheets of NBFCs have improved, debt mutual funds have restructured their portfolios, credit rating agencies and regulators have become more active. Hopefully, we are at the bottom of crisis and things will get better.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is the impact on Debt Mutual Funds?</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Default by companies like IL&amp;FS, DHFL, Reliance ADAG, Essel, Altico etc has impacted some of the debt mutual funds which had exposure to these papers. The NAV and performance of these funds have been impacted accordingly. This has created huge fear and anxiety among investors of debt mutual funds. It is being perceived that all the debt mutual funds are unsafe.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Some of the important facts about debt mutual funds are as under:</strong><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; </strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688018958/abloti0mx4kpgs6pvkw9.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 385px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that debt mutual fund had exposure of Rs. 14,321 Crores in companies which have defaulted.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The total size of Debt mutual funds is Rs. 13,38,726 Crores.</span></li>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The total exposure of debt mutual funds to toxic companies is ~1%</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">This shows that ~99% of the debt mutual funds has not been impacted and its fine to invest in Debt Mutual Funds.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Also, decent recovery of capital eventually happens in the defaulted companies, resulting in negligible overall loss to the investor.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is Alpha Capital&rsquo;s view on Debt Portfolio?</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We believe that such kind of turbulences are a part of the economy and investment cycle. Like bull and bear run of equity, the debt market also goes through periods of crest and trough. In the downturn of debt, there will be some issues and defaults. This has happened in the past as well like in the years 2008 &amp; 2013 and it will continue to happen in future. The important part is that we need to be thorough in our risk management so that our exposure to toxic assets is on the lower side and has less impact on portfolio return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its important to understand that debt funds have advantages like tax arbitrage (Debt funds get taxed at approx. 5%-10% whereas fixed deposit gets taxed as per income tax slab), has high liquidity, better return etc. The down cycle of debt which comes in every 4-6 years will have a negative impact of ~1%-2% in that year. If the negative impact of ~1.5% is spread across 5 years then net impact per year is approx. 0.3%. The benefit from tax arbitrage, extra return etc in debt funds is far higher than the impact cost. So overall debt mutual funds are safe and give better return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is the portfolio strategy followed to prevent unwanted risk?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At Alpha Capital our core focus is on Wealth Preservation. Once wealth preservation is taken care, we strive for wealth creation and maximization. Keeping this philosophy in mind, our research team uses the following strategy for Debt Funds:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Recommended Debt Funds/ fixed income products have following characteristics:</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">High quality of underlying papers</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Good diversification</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Large fund size</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Exposure to fund houses who have good fixed income management team and have large fixed income assets.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Low expense ratio</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The portfolio of Debt funds is monitored on a regular basis and exposure is cut wherever there is perceived risk. In the last 1 year, we have aggressively cut position in funds with exposure to IL&amp;FS, DHFL, Yes bank, Reliance ADAG etc.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Should we worry about debt funds?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We feel that investor should be aware about developments but should not worry till the time portfolio is being actively managed and risk management processes are being followed. Volatility is part of investment and its impact reduces as the tenure of investment increases.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019236/u5e9rthk3b8eihv4n6wp.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Debt Funds, Returns & Defaults – Should We Worry?","seo_keywords":"Debt Funds, Returns & Defaults – Should We Worry?","seo_description":"Since September 2019, debt funds have been experiencing lots of turbulence. Good AAA companies like IL&FS, DHFL etc. have defaulted and companies like Yes Bank, Indiabulls etc. have come under radar. In the last 1 year, some debt funds which had exposure to toxic assets have seen negative return as well.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019234/mfqidilstvvq1dtiqybm.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"191","title":"Mutual Fund Ratings – Are they relevant for Investment?","slug":"mutual-fund-ratings-relevant-investment","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1588140852","published_date_view":"Apr 29, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019349/ews6vnminnb5lmmcyfyq.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the last 5 years, mutual funds have become very popular in India. The primary reasons for the growth of mutual funds are bull run in equity market, underperformance of real estate, awareness through aggressive marketing and demonetisation.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Awareness of mutual funds is good because it provides to investor a simple, well regulated, low cost and professionally managed product for wealth creation.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><u><strong>Today, there are as many as 44 fund houses in India which together offer more than 2,500 mutual fund schemes</strong>.</u>&nbsp;Selecting the best mutual funds to invest from this huge list and creating an efficiently diversified portfolio can be a challenging task.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If an investor does a Google of the phrase &lsquo;Best Mutual Funds to Invest&rsquo; then he will have hundreds of financial websites sharing the recommended list of funds. The bigger challenge is that we should trust which website for selection of funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One of the most common source for selection of mutual funds is the star rating given by websites likes&nbsp;valueresearch, moneycontrol, morningstar,&nbsp;crisil,&nbsp;businessline, livemint,&nbsp;etc.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Majority of the times, rating is given on the basis of past performance of a fund. If a fund has done well in 1 year or 3 years period then fund gets higher rating.<u>&nbsp;<strong>Rating the mutual funds on the basis of past performance with an objective to predict the future performance is liking driving a car by using the rear view mirror.</strong></u></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Past performance of schemes are important as it tell us about historical movement and consistency of performance. But using the past performance as the most important criteria can be very dangerous.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Lets</strong><strong>&nbsp;take some sample cases to understand the implications.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Credit defaults in debt funds:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the last 1 year, debt funds have seen lots of turbulence because of defaults by companies like IL&amp;FS, DHFL, ADAG, Essel, Sintex etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Following is the list of some of star rated debt mutual funds which got impacted in last 1 year:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019375/rbmchmbvnzmjxmn3vatj.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 526px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that 5 star rated debt funds like BOI AXA Credit Risk Fund and Baroda Treasury Advantage Fund gave a negative return of -44.53% and -18.69% respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The average return of all debt funds during this period was 7.05%. Clearly, high star rating of funds couldn&rsquo;t help investors in getting better return than average. Instead, there was huge erosion of wealth even for very conservative investors.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Mid cap and small cap volatility:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The period between Sep&rsquo; 13 to Jan&rsquo; 18 was a golden period for mid caps and small caps. By the end of 2017, small and mid caps had got heated up with valuations becoming highly stretched. It was time to book profit and reduce exposure in this category.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Based on superb past performance, the rating agencies had given high ratings to mid and small caps in late 2017 and early 2018 which led to huge inflow into mid and small cap category.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Following is the list of some of star rated small and mid cap mutual funds which got impacted in last 2 year:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019398/r6ujdgwysoiccnmkrpw0.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 564px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that how 5 and 4 star rated funds delivered huge negative return between -10% to -30% in the period 2018 and 2019 when average return of Equity mutual funds during the same period was 6.95%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors had to suffer huge losses as they invested in mid and small cap funds in peak of the market of late 2017 and early 2018 based on high ratings given by various websites.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Conclusion:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above analysis clearly shows that high mutual fund rating given by various websites like&nbsp;valueresearch, moneycontrol, morningstar,&nbsp;crisil,&nbsp;businessline, livemint,&nbsp;etc. doesn&rsquo;t provide any meaningful assurance for stable and good return in future. Having a blind faith in these ratings can lead to huge losses for portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The mutual fund ratings are relevant as they talk about quality of performance of the fund in the past. But ratings only should not be used for future prediction of return.</strong></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors should not rush into investment by just looking at mutual fund ratings, instead proper homework and analysis should be done.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Following parameters should be used for selection of funds:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Fund management team &ndash; Who is the fund manager. What&rsquo;s his investment philosophy, how is the consistency of performance. How has he done in different market conditions. The factors contributing to his return and how well the risk management is being done. Continuity of fund management team.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The quality of institution which is managing the fund. Corporate governance and pedigree. What are the checks and balances.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Past performance of fund. Consistency in performance. Risk adjusted return delivered under different market conditions. Sources of return.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Expense and fees of the fund.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Quality and structure of the portfolio.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above analysis can be slightly time consuming, but since hard earned money is involved,<u>&nbsp;<strong>its always better to do some analysis and homework so that we are aware about what we are entering into and there are no unwanted surprises.</strong></u></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its also high time for the regulator of securities in India i.e.&nbsp;<u><strong>SEBI to overhaul the mutual fund rating business in India so that ratings are more robust and investors don&rsquo;t end up making wrong investment.</strong></u></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing!</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019825/psjoqwo0ddjolyb7osor.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Mutual Fund Ratings – Are they relevant for Investment?","seo_keywords":"Mutual Fund Ratings – Are they relevant for Investment?","seo_description":"The above analysis clearly shows that high mutual fund rating given by various websites like valueresearch, moneycontrol, morningstar, crisil, businessline, livemint, etc. doesn’t provide any meaningful assurance for stable and good return in future. Having a blind faith in these ratings can lead to huge losses for portfolio.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019823/fusxyacbi2qavcxxspzq.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"192","title":"The Impact of Corona virus on Indian Economy and Personal Finance","slug":"the-impact-of-corona-virus-on-indian-economy-and-personal-finance","category":"Financial Planning","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1587882236","published_date_view":"Apr 26, 2020","discription":"<h3><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Economies across the world, including India have been hit hard by the Corona virus crisis.&nbsp; On 24<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;March 2020, Prime Narendra Modi ordered a nationwide lock down for twenty-one days; the entire country comprising 1.3 billion population have been stayed put at home, as a necessary step to minimize the virus spread.</span></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The fear of the virus and the lock down had a tremendous impact on businesses, ranging from commercial establishments to education, travel sector, events and entertainment.&nbsp;&nbsp; A UN report has stated that India is going to be one of the top 15 worst-affected economies with a trade impact of US$348 million.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">When WHO declared the novel corona virus as a pandemic, Indian stock markets suffered the worst crash since June 2017. Stock markets have behaved erratically, while they posted worst losses in history on March 23, 2020, two days later after the announcement of the lock down, they posted their highest gains in 11 years, adding $66 billion to investor wealth. But on April 1, 2020, the markets slumped dramatically again.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India&rsquo;s lock down also means the world&rsquo;s largest lock down, which translates into all factories, shops, markets being closed, public transport shut and construction work coming to a grinding halt.&nbsp; While lock down may be a temporary phase or may need to be imposed later depending on the complexity of the situation, the Indian economy is moving at a snail&rsquo;s pace due to the COVID 19 impact.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On March 27, Moody&rsquo;s Investor Service brought down India&rsquo;s estimate of GDP for the year from 5.3 percent to 2. 5 percent.&nbsp; Due to social distancing and avoidance of public-related activity, the travel and live events industry have been the worst hit. The live events industry has estimated a loss of Rs. 3000 crore and the tourism industry is staring at a loss of Rs. 15000 crores for the months of March and April, alone.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On March 26, finance minister Nirmala Sitharaman announced a $23 billion package to tackle the slipping financial situation in the country, by providing sector-related incentives, funds for food security, healthcare and extensions for tax deadlines. On March 27, the Reserve Bank of India introduced sharp interest rate cuts and other measures to introduce credit available for affected businesses with an injection of $52&nbsp;billion (Rs. 374,000 crore) to the economy.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The country&rsquo;s premier private bank HDFC in its treasury reports a loss of Rs. 10 lakh crores in the first half of 2020. This translates into a slashing of 74 percent of the real GDP within the time frame.&nbsp;&nbsp; According to the report, the next quarter will be positive but still weak. The report said the service sector was the most hit, especially during the lock down because of lack of delivery of non-essentials.&nbsp; The impact on manufacturing industry has not been much, especially for essentials like food, beverage, medicine and pharma products.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The RBI has also announced a cut in the Repo-rate by 75 basis points, with a 90-bps cut in the reverse Repo-rate to curtail the effects of the pandemic on the economy.&nbsp; Due to this move, banks are in a position to pass the rate cut benefits to customers.&nbsp; Banks also deferred payments of EMIs on various loans including home loans, auto loans, for a period of 3 months, under the term laid by the COVID 19 RBI package.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>How should one plan&rsquo;s one personal finance during COVID 19?</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With lock down and various restrictions being imposed time to time to battle the Corona virus, there is a looming fear of late salaries, pay cuts and even worse, job losses.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;It is important to have an emergency corpus equivalent to 6 months of expenses, including EMIs. If you do not have an emergency fund right now, start saving proactively for the next two months, so that you have funds to bank upon for dealing with uncertainties like pay cuts and job loss.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In any case due to the pandemic, going out for entertainment, travel and eating out at fancy restaurants have been cut down. This saved money can be used to fund your emergency corpus.&nbsp; Avoid splurging on smart TVs and cars or going for another EMI during this period and divert the money towards creating an emergency fund.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Park your funds in liquids funds or ultra-short-term funds, where you can get better interest rates than your savings account.&nbsp; Keep investing in your mutual funds SIP. Only when it is very difficult due to paying off certain loans, can you skip it temporarily. But if you can, continue to invest in mutual funds, because it is smart thinking to invest when the market is on the low, because you can buy more units with the given price. When the market moves up, the value of these units will rise, helping you maximize your wealth creation process.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Ensure that you are well insured individually and as a family.&nbsp; Imagine the impact if there is a job loss and a health crisis.&nbsp; If you are a family of four people, invest in a&nbsp; good family floater cover of at least 5 lakhs to begin with. There are a lot of super-top plans which come to play when the base sum insured is used, which you can take advantage of.&nbsp; You can also go for a critical illness policy cover, which provides instant emergency cash, when faced with a major illness.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For an individual living in a metro city, a minimum health insurance cover of Rs. 5 lakh is needed.&nbsp; Just because your office has a health insurance program in place, doesn&rsquo;t meet you don&rsquo;t need to have one.&nbsp; If there is a job loss, the cover provided by the employer is lapsed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Do not stop paying your EMIs and honor them as much as possible, because stopping your payments an affect your credit score.&nbsp; You can ask the lending bank for a temporary stoppage on your installments, without late charges or penalties.&nbsp;&nbsp; Since interest rate on unsecured debt like credit cards are the highest, make sure that you always pay your credit card bills. And as much as possible, limit use of credit cards in tough times, unless necessary.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019963/lo7i6ozcz5ghoebqdaq9.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Impact of Corona virus on Indian Economy and Personal Finance","seo_keywords":"The Impact of Corona virus on Indian Economy and Personal Finance","seo_description":"Economies across the world, including India have been hit hard by the Corona virus crisis.  On 24th March 2020, Prime Narendra Modi ordered a nationwide lock down for twenty-one days; the entire country comprising 1.3 billion population have been stayed put at home, as a necessary step to minimize the virus spread.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688019957/v9pi1x9in2lvlf652i5n.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"193","title":"How to Save Income Tax in the Financial Year 2020-21","slug":"how-to-save-income-tax-in-the-financial-year-2020-21","category":"Tax Planning","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1587709566","published_date_view":"Apr 24, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Many of us fear filing our income taxes; one of the main reasons is lack of adequate knowledge on the various sections that help us in saving our taxes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">While some of us are aware of Section 80C of the Income Tax Act, which is a popular one considering it is highlighted the most in various articles, there are many more deductions available under other sections that can be immensely helpful in reducing our taxes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Let us go through the current income tax rates and find out the applicable rates as per the annual income.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Income Tax Rates (Simplified)</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Income tax rates for individuals below 60 years of age are as follows &ndash;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">No tax on income up to Rs. 2.5 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 per cent on income between Rs. 250,001 and Rs. 5 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">20 per cent on income between Rs. 500,001 and Rs. 10 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">30 per cent on income above Rs. 10 lakh.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Income tax rates for individuals who are senior citizens (aged 60 years but below 80 years of age) are follows &ndash;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">No tax on income up to Rs. 3 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 per cent on income between Rs.300,001 to Rs. 5 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">20 per cent on income between Rs. 500,001 and Rs. 10 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">30 per cent on income above Rs. 10 lakh.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Income tax rates for individuals who are super senior citizens (aged 80 years and above) are as follows &ndash;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">No tax on income up to Rs. 5 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">20 per cent on income between Rs. 500,001 and Rs. 10 lakh</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">30 per cent on income above Rs. 10 lakh.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Claiming Tax Deductions through Section 80C</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Section 80C of the IT Act (Income Tax Act) is one of the most common routes used by individuals to save tax on income. According to this section, HUF/Hindu Undivided Families or individuals can seek a maximum tax deduction of INR 1.5 lakhs from the gross income, for investments or expenditures made in specific areas, and then calculate the total taxable income for the specific financial year. It is important to note that the tax deduction can be claimed by an individual or HUFs only if the investment or expense is made in the financial year that the tax return is filed.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">When the tax deduction is claimed, the total gross income on which taxes need to be paid becomes less as compared to the real income. For instance, if your yearly income is INR 7.5 lakhs and you have invested/spent INR 1.5 lakhs on the specific areas which are allowed for tax deduction as per the laws, then the total taxable amount after the deduction will be INR 6 lakhs. Thus, you will need to pay taxes on INR 6 lakhs of income after the deductions instead of INR 7.5 lakhs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>For Rs. 1.5 lakh invested towards tax saving, here is the tax deduction claimed under Section 80C</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;Income Tax Rate</strong></span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Tax Deductions</strong></span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5 per cent</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">7800</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">20 per cent</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">31,200</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">30 per cent.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">46,800</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>Tax savings are inclusive of cess at 4 per cent.</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Section 80C of the IT Act explained</strong></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Section 80C of the IT Act is one of the most common options used by tax payers to save on income tax. In addition to specific kinds of investments, individuals and HUFs can also avail of tax deductions on specific expenses under this section. Presented below are some details about Section 80 C of the Income Tax Act.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Most of us put our monies into PPF/Public Provident Fund, insurance policies, and ELSS/equity-linked savings schemes, etc. to reap the benefits of tax deduction under 80C. However, there is also a host of other tax saving investment choices that we fail to take into account. As mentioned above, tax savings can be availed for not just investments but also for certain kinds of expenses. But, such expenditures have to be made in the same financial year as the tax year so as to be able to avail of the tax deductions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is important to understand the below listed facts when trying to claim a tax deduction under Section 80C of the IT Act:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The tax bracket plays a major role in determining the amount of money that can be saved as tax deduction by individuals and HUFs under Section 80C. Thus for instance, before the tax was calculated, if the earnings subtracted from the gross total earnings fell in the 25 percent tax slab, then it would the total tax amount that would be saved.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For example, if the total gross income for a financial year is INR 11 lakhs and you avail of tax deductions of INR 1.5 lakhs as per Section 80C, then the total earnings that would be taxable will be INR 9.5 lakhs. This would decrease the total tax that has to be paid by INR 46,800 (tax savings inclusive of cess at 4 percent)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Also, if the yearly earnings of a person are under the taxable limit, then such a person will not be able to avail of any tax benefits under Section 80C for any expenses or investments as that person is not liable to pay any taxes in the first place itself.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If there are any capital gains as part of the income then it cannot be used to claim tax deduction under the expenses/investment aspect of Section 80C. Thus, if all your earnings are made of just capital gains, then you will not be able to use the section to make tax savings.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Listed below are some of the options that tax payers can invest in to avail of tax deductions under Section 80C of the IT Act:</strong></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investments in different kinds of provident funds like VPF, EPF, superannuation funds, or PPF</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">EPF/employees&rsquo; provident fund is part of salary that gets deducted and is eligible for tax deduction claim. But interest of over 9.5% on EPF is taxable. Also, contribution of over 12% by employer on EPF is taxable. Extra contribution by employee to provident fund is called VPF/voluntary provident fund and is eligible for tax deduction.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">PPF/Public provident fund is a government scheme and eligible for tax deduction under 80C. Interest is assured but not fixed and is set every quarter. Interest is tax free and the maturity period is 15 years.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Payment of premiums to ULIP, life insurance, annuity plans</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Life insurance premium payments for spouse, children and self are eligible for tax deductions under 80C. Life insurance for in-laws or parents is ineligible.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">ULIPs offer life insurance coverage as well as equity investment benefits. Since it offers life cover, the charges levied are higher than ELSS or PF. ULIP investments are eligible for tax benefits under 80C.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Contributions to KVP/Kisan Vikas Patrika, NSC/National Saving Certificate, Post Office 5-year Term deposits/POTD, SCSS/Senior Citizen Savings Scheme, and 5-year fixed deposits in bank.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">People who are 60 years old or older can invest in SCSS. People who are between 55 years and 60 years old and have taken retirement under a Special Voluntary Retirement Scheme or a VRS/Voluntary Retirement Scheme are also eligible for SCSS within three months from the date of retirement. Retired defense people can invest in SCSS only till they are 50 years of age. Interest is set and paid every quarter. Unclaimed interest does not earn extra interest and is liable for taxation. Investment in SCSS is eligible for tax deduction under 80C.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">People can invest INR 100 on NSC and there is no maximum limit. NSC investment is eligible for the maximum tax benefits available under 80C. Interest earned is reinvested into NSC till the last year of maturity. The interest is annually compounded and the rate is revised every quarter.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Fixed deposits in scheduled banks for 5 years are eligible for tax deductions under 80C.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">POTDs are just like fixed deposits in banks. Tax deductions are available for only 5 year POTDs and not for those with lesser maturity periods. Interest is set every quarter, compounded every quarter, and paid every year. The investment is eligible for tax benefits, but the interest earned is taxable.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sukanya Samriddhi Account (SSA) for girl child under 10 years old.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In this government scheme, parents can open an account for their daughter younger than 10 years of age. All deposits to the account are eligible for 80C tax deduction. Deposits to SSA can be made for only two daughters, but 3 in case the first delivery consists of twins. Parents need to keep depositing a minimum of INR 250 and a maximum of INR 150000 per year for a period of 15 years into the account. Interest rate on the deposits changes every year. Maturity occurs in 21 years; thus parents do not have to make any deposits for the years between 16 and 21.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Repayment of the loan principal amount taken for construction or purchase of a house</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">EMIs for home loans consist of two components, the principal and the interest. The former is eligible for tax deduction under section 80C. Tax benefits on interest payment can be availed under section 80EE and section 24 of the IT Act. If the EMIs cover the maximum tax benefit limit of INR 1.5 lakhs under 80C, then you do not have to make any investments to avail tax deductions.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investment in a mutual fund like a notified ELSS/Equity Linked Saving Scheme</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">ELSS mutual funds are eligible for tax deduction under 80C. They often offer higher returns on investment but also come with higher risk. ELSS has a 3-year lock-in period. Capital gains from it are liable for LTCG/long term capital gains taxation. The maximum tax benefit that can be availed for investment in ELSS is INR 1.5 lakhs.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Tax saving criteria as per Section 80CCC and Section 80CCD</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In addition to Section 80C of the IT Act, tax payers also need to be aware of Section 80CCD and Section 80CCC. As per Section 80CCE, the total maximum tax deduction that can be availed under Sections 80CCC, 80C, and 80CCD (1) cannot be more than INR 1.5 lakhs</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per Section 80CCD contributions to Central Government&rsquo;s pension schemes are eligible for tax deductions from the overall gross earnings. It is however vital to meet certain criteria to be able to avail the tax advantages under this section.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to section 80CCD (1) of the IT Act, deductions will be permitted on different contributions to varied notified government pension schemes if the contributed amount is not more than</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">20 percent of the gross final earnings for self-employed individuals, or</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">10 percent of the income (salary) if the person is employed by others. It may be noted that &lsquo;salary&rsquo; represents dearness allowance, which is mentioned in the employment terms, and does not include other kinds of allowances and incentives.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Besides the above listed two limitations, as per Sections 80C and 80CCD, the final amount that a person can claim as tax deduction from the total gross earnings cannot be more than the set limit of INR 1.5 lakhs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One however has to be aware of the extra tax benefit that can be availed under this section. This extra benefit is beyond the notified limit of INR 1.5 lakhs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to 80CCD (1B), a tax payer is permitted an extra deduction of not more than INR 50,000 from his/her total gross income, if he/she has made an investment in specific pension schemes. These pension schemes are the Atal Pension Yojana and the National Pension System.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Also, employers can contribute to the employees NPS account according to section 80CCD (2). Such a contribution can however be not more than 10 percent of the total &lsquo;salary&rsquo; of the employee. It may also be noted that according to the IT Act, there is no upper limit to the amount of money that an employer can contribute which would be eligible for tax deduction.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Other Deductions apart from Section 80 C</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Apart from tax deductions under Section 80C, there are many other sections under which you can save tax.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><u>Section 80D</u>&nbsp;</strong>of the Income Tax can help you save tax on the health insurance premiums that you pay. You can claim tax deduction of Rs. 25,000 per financial year for health insurance premiums that are paid for self, spouse and dependent kids.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Also, if your parents are below 60 years of age, you can claim an additional tax deduction of Rs. 25,000 in a financial year.&nbsp; The maximum deduction that can be claimed, if your parents are above 60 years of age, is Rs. 50,000 in a single financial year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Let&rsquo;s say that you are 60 years of age, and your parents are above 60 (senior citizens), then you can claim a tax deduction of Rs. 75,000 (Rs. 50,000 + Rs. 25,000) in a financial year.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If your net taxable income (total income subtracted by all deductions claimed) fall under 10 per cent, then you can save Rs. 15,600 additionally.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Income Tax&nbsp; Rates</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Tax Saved</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At 5 per cent</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rs. 3900</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At 10 per cent</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rs. 15,600</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At 20 per cent</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"319\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rs. 23,400</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>Tax savings include cess at 4 per cent.</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><u><strong>Section 80DDB</strong></u>&nbsp;of the Income Tax Act allows deductions for expenditure incurred on certain specific illnesses.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per the Rule-11DD of the Income Tax Act, the following specified diseases, under the present laws, can be claimed as deductions &ndash;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1) Malignant Cancers;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2) Acquired Immuno-Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS);</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">3 Chronic Renal failure;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">4 Hematological disorders &ndash; (a) Hemophilia and (b) Thalassaemia</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">5) Neurological Disorders with 40 per cent and above certified disability levels. These neurological disorders include &ndash;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dementia;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Parkinsons Disease</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Motor Neuron Disease</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Hemiballismus;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dystonia Musculorum Deformans;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Ataxia;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Chorea;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Aphasia</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Deductions can be claimed on the basis of the prescription for the said medical treatment from a specialist, like a neurologist, an oncologist, an immunologist; etc, depending on the specific case.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The maximum deduction that can be claimed is Rs. 40,000 in a financial year for a person below 60 years of age and Rs. 1 lakh for a person above 60 years of age.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please remember that the deduction is based on the amount received from the insurer or reimbursement provided by the employer for the treatment of the particular condition.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Let&rsquo;s say the actual expenses incurred for the treatment of a particular disease was Rs. 50,000, and there was no reimbursement given either by the insurer or the employer.&nbsp; In this case, you can claim a maximum deduction of Rs. 40,000.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">But, if the reimbursement by the insurer or the employer was Rs. 20,000, you can claim a maximum deduction of Rs. 20,000 (Rs. 40,000 &ndash; Rs. 20,0000).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If the reimbursement by the insurer or the employer was Rs. 42,000 (higher than the maximum deduction of Rs. 40,000), you cannot claim the deduction under Section 80DDB.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><u><strong>Section 80E</strong>&nbsp;</u>allows you to take advantage of deductions on interest paid on education loans.&nbsp; Apart from self, interest paid on education loan for spouse and children, are also eligible for deduction.&nbsp; Please remember the year from which the repayment starts is the period from which you can claim deduction, not the year you got the loan. The deduction can be availed till you pay the loan interest or for a maximum of 8 years, whichever is earlier.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><u><strong>Section 80EE</strong></u>&nbsp;gives you a tax benefit of Rs. 50,000 for home buyers above the limit of Rs. 2 lakh, for housing loan interest. However, there are few conditions on which this benefit is applicable &ndash;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The loan has to be taken between April 1, 2016 and March 31, 2017 (not available to home loan buyers after&nbsp; March 31, 2017)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Available only to first time home buyers</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The value of the housing for which the loan is applicable should not be more than Rs. 50 lakh.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The loan amount should not be more than Rs. 30 lakh.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Loan should be from a housing finance company or a bank.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On the time of taking the loan, the individual should not own any other residential property.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The below table gives you a snapshot of various deductions under the Income Tax and how you can save your taxes</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Section</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Deductions</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investment Instruments</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80C</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Maximum Rs. 1. 5 lakh</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">ELSS mutual fund,&nbsp; PPF, EPF, Insurance Premium, NSC, Tuition Fees; etc.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80CCD(1B)</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Max Rs. 50,000 for investment in NPS (National Pension Scheme)</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Pension Fund</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80CCD(2)</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Maximum 10 per cent of basic salary and dearness allowance</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">NPS by the employer.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80D</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Up to &nbsp;Rs. 25000</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Senior citizens, Rs. 50,000</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Health Insurance Premium and Preventive Health Check-ups</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80DD</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Up to Rs. 75,000 if disability is between 40 and 80 per cent. Up to Rs. 1.5 lakh, if disability is more than 80 per cent.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Money paid on treatment and management for differently-abled individuals</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80DDB</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Deduction up to Rs. 40,000. For senior citizens, deductions up to Rs. 1 lakh.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Expenses on specific diseases for the dependent.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80E</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">No limit mentioned, maximum up to 8 years from the period of repayment.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Interest on education loan repayment.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80EE</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Max Rs. 50,0000 subject t certain conditions.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Interest on loan paid for buying residential property.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80G</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Up to 50 percent or 100</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">per cent, depending on the amount donated. Cash donations above Rs. 2000 are not eligble</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As stated in the Income Tax Act.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80GG</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rs. 5000 per month or</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">25 per cent of total income whichever is lesser.</span></p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rent paid, in the case of HRA not received.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80 TTA</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Up to Rs. 10,000 per year&nbsp; for individuals below 60 years of age.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Interest on savings account (banks and post office)</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80 TTB</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;Up to Rs. 50,000 per year for senior citizens.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Interest on savings account (banks and post office)</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">80 U</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The same as Section 80DD</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Money paid on treatment and management for differently-abled individuals, especially for vision, hearing impairments and so on.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Section 80QQB</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Maximum deduction of Rs. 3 lakh when royalty is received in lump sum. When royalty is not received in lump sum, then maximum deduction is 15 per cent on the book&rsquo;s revenue in a particular year.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For authors (excluding the ones who write text books for schools and colleges) who have received payment in royalty.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Section 80RRB</span>\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\t\t\t<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\t\t\t</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Maximum deduction of Rs. 3 lakh.</span></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td width=\"213\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If you have registered a patent after April 1, 2003 and receive royalty income for that patent.</span></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020549/xssysphozpvcahhwvmfw.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"How to Save Income Tax in the Financial Year 2020-21","seo_keywords":"How to Save Income Tax in the Financial Year 2020-21","seo_description":"Deductions can be claimed on the basis of the prescription for the said medical treatment from a specialist, like a neurologist, an oncologist, an immunologist; etc, depending on the specific case.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020548/fg20ag9bxgrujbiz6cw9.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"194","title":"How Good Habits Can Change Your Financial Destiny During COVID 19 Crisis","slug":"how-good-habits-can-change-your-financial-destiny-during-covid-19-crisis","category":"Tax Planning","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1587451063","published_date_view":"Apr 21, 2020","discription":"<h4><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Financing planning is not just about knowing which investment instruments to invest in; it is about having the right attitude and discipline to brave tough situations and focus on your goals. In a way, financial planners are akin to psychologists or life coaches.&nbsp;&nbsp; They go beyond financial planning; they help you nurture a habit of discipline and focused attitude towards life.</span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Creating a financial plan is something any financial planner can do. But a good financial planner works on developing an individual&rsquo;s mindset towards understanding the importance of goal setting, the art of balancing investments with expenditure, and the exponential power of compounding.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We all have the ability to grow rich and contribute handsomely to ourselves, our family and our society. Being rich gives you the ability to contribute to humanity.&nbsp; As you can see in this COVID 19 crisis, it is the millionaires and billionaires with progressive mindset, who have come forward with generous donations. Why? Because they have the will and the ability to create a positive change.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Seeds of wealth are created in our habits.&nbsp; Habits are nothing but behavioral pattern that is repeated regularly to an extent that it becomes a part of our personality.&nbsp; When you do something continuously or regularly, it becomes familiar to us, so much that we can do it without much resistance.&nbsp;&nbsp; Even if it is something that we may abhor, we tend to develop a certain amount of curiosity or interest in something if we end up doing repeatedly.&nbsp; When we develop an interest, we tend to excel in that task or endeavor, till we attain a certain amount of mastery on that subject.&nbsp; This is just simple neuroscience &ndash; the more you behave in a certain way, or the perform you perform an action, the more it gets physically wired into&nbsp; your brain and becomes a part of your daily routine.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Knowledge is one of the best ways to create interest and develop the base for a good habit to thrive.&nbsp;&nbsp; When a not-so-aware individual reads or watches videos on investment benefits,&nbsp; the process of investing, the various financial products,&nbsp; the power of compounding, the facts and myths that surround investment practices; she or he understands that while the&nbsp; world of finance may not be as glamorous as entertainment, it is essential enough, and has the power to influence, leverage and positively impact every aspect of life.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Every action starts with a WHY. Once you are clear about why you want to do a particular thing, you will figure out the &lsquo;HOW&rsquo;, meaning, you will look for resources that help you reach towards the goal.&nbsp; Since you are already in the plan, you will begin to evaluate your progress, with the WHAT (what are you actually doing).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Applying the above concepts to the world of investments &ndash; the &lsquo;WHY&rsquo; is the financial goal that you have, the &lsquo;How&rsquo; is the process of achieving that goal in a particular time frame.&nbsp; For instance, the &lsquo;WHY&rsquo; may be a big house that you want to buy in 10 years, the &lsquo;How&rsquo; is the selection of the right asset-mix that helps compound your investments and the WHAT is the analysis of the returns that you can get at the end of 10 years. You can also weigh the pros and cons of a particular investment with the &lsquo;WHAT&rsquo; analysis.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Habits and discipline go hand-in hand.&nbsp; So, when you have made up your mind to invest regularly in the form of say, monthly SIPS, then you will develop the discipline to ensure that you stick to the plan, against all odds.&nbsp; True, there can be financial hurdles, missed SIPs, crises of various kinds; but if you have set your eyes on the goal, you will continue to invest in your dream. This is because times change, and nothing is constant &ndash; what takes you through is your disciplined mindset.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Let&rsquo;s say, the 40 year old Akash wants to earn Rs. 40 lakh at the end of 5 years to fund for a house.&nbsp; Here is how he can work with a good mutual fund financial planner who not only charts out a solid plan but also helps get excited about going after his goal.&nbsp; &nbsp;The financial planner, at the same time, will keep expectations realistic and give him a clear picture taking into account his risk appetite, tax slab and future investments.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&nbsp;In this case, on an average, considering a 12 percent expected rate of return, and investing Rs. 50000 per month as SIP, Akash will have invested Rs.30 lakh with earnings of 11,24,319, taking the total SIP value at&nbsp; 41,24,319. To reach this goal, the financial planner will help plan the right kind of asset mix, including balanced funds, liquids funds and equities to help him reach that figure.</span></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Of course, we cannot predict the future- the actual figure may be lesser or more than 40 lakhs, depending on various factors like market dynamics, rate of inflation, individual&rsquo;s risk appetite etc.&nbsp; However, one thing is for sure, if you stay invested, you are better off getting to that figure than just squandering money, being in a debt-trap, or keeping money in the bank with minuscule returns.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020774/empwbxaluo7cxyaly90u.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"How Good Habits Can Change Your Financial Destiny During COVID 19 Crisis","seo_keywords":"How Good Habits Can Change Your Financial Destiny During COVID 19 Crisis","seo_description":"Financing planning is not just about knowing which investment instruments to invest in; it is about having the right attitude and discipline to brave tough situations and focus on your goals. In a way, financial planners are akin to psychologists or life coaches.   They go beyond financial planning; they help you nurture a habit of discipline and focused attitude towards life.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020772/ns221hjhzbarcpnoi77t.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"195","title":"Where will Indian Equity Market go from here – Up or Down?","slug":"where-will-indian-equity-market-go-from-here-up-or-down","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1587105582","published_date_view":"Apr 17, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020871/x3b1mem6cb5thez8huqq.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 813px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A billion-dollar question running right now in the mind of all investors is that<strong>&lsquo;Where will Indian Equity Market go from here &ndash; Up or Down?&rsquo;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Last couple of months have been very volatile for both Indian and global equity markets due to Covid-19. The Sensex was at its peak on 12th Feb 2020 at 41565. Thereafter, it dropped by ~38% and then has rebound by ~12%. Sensex is still down by 26% from its peak.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Some unanswered questions in the mind of investors are:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Is the worst over for equity market?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Is the recent upward movement of 12% a false rally?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Why is equity market going up when the Covid-19 crisis is getting worst?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">How long will the crisis run, when will the level of 41565 come back?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Can market fall from here, how much worst can it get?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Lately, many economists, fund managers, brokerage houses, financial advisors, independent analysts, investors etc. have been trying to answer the above questions and make a prediction/ forecast.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">At Alpha Capital, we believe that its impossible to make a prediction about the stock market in short term. Its very difficult to correctly forecast the movement of equity in a shorter time horizon.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Any short-term view on the market is a guess work which is based on various current factors in play, movement of market in past crisis, experience of advisor etc. Sometimes the projected story plays out well and sometimes it gets missed out completely.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its impossible to predict the market in short term but its important to have a view and biasedness towards a projected story so that action in portfolio can be taken accordingly.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With this article we will try to explain the story which is running in our mind and will accordingly try to answer the question on future movement of equity market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Some of the dominant factors in play for future movement of equity market are as under:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">When will daily new cases of Covid &ndash; 19 peak out in the US</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">How much does Covid &ndash; 19 spread in India and when do things become normal.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">How many months or years will Indian economy take to recover</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The fiscal and monetary stimulus being provided by Governments and Federal authorities globally.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Low crude price and low interest tate.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The future movement of equity market will depend on how the above factors move in future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>We feel that Indian equity market may have two phases of movement. The expected phases are as under:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">1) The first upward movement in Indian equity may happen when new cases of Covid-19 peak out in the US. This may be an indicator that the worst is over for the US. The US market may start going up 1-2 weeks before the peak of new cases.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per Boston Consulting Group (BCG), the peak out of new cases in US will happen in 1st week of May. This is again a prediction, it may happen in end of May, end of April or may have already happened.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The current status of new cases in the US is as under:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020893/sxyxrdl7ksmg2fiwwb5i.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 679px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Foreign Institutional Investors (FIIs) play an important role in Indian equity market and are big market movers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The FIIs sold in Feb 2020 &amp; March 2020 and have been net buyers in April 2020 as seen below:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688020910/jlnid1ezbdii5qz4xt5o.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 266px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sensex was down in Feb and March of 2020 and has been positive in April 2020 which is similar to the movement of FII buying as shown in the above table.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We would like to highlight that FIIs are not the only movers of Indian market. Domestic Institutional Investors (DIIs), HNIs etc. are also important factors but it can definitely be said that FIIs are big movers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We feel that when new cases of Covid-19 peak out in the US, then sentiments will change and FIIs will become net buyers in India and other emerging countries. This will lead to equity market rally and help in covering most of the recent losses.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">2) The second phase of market movement will depend on how the economy of India behaves. We will need answers to the following questions:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">How long does the Covid 19 crisis run in India?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">How much of the Indian economy gets hurt because of the Covid 19 crisis?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">What kind of fiscal and monetary support is given by Indian Government and RBI?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">How long does it take for Indian economy to recover?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">When do corporate earnings start growing at good rate?</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As of now, we don&rsquo;t have answers to the above questions. The situation is changing every day. We are watching, analyzing and trying to look at various probabilities of outcomes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Based on above two phases, it can be said that future movement of Indian equity market will depend on how the Covid-19 crisis moves in US and India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We are getting better visibility of the US developments and feel that FIIs should come back to Indian market soon which will help in recovering good part of the recent losses.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The Indian part of the story is still playing out and we are hoping to get better picture soon. We are watching the Covid-19 spread in India, impact on economy and Government actions closely.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Would like to highlight that the above analysis is to form a view on the movement of equity market in shorter term. We continue to be bullish on equity with a long-term horizon of 5 year plus. We feel that the currently volatility is a short-term issue which will get resolved soon and market will continue to run upward in long term and deliver expected return.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For investor, its important to have patience and give equity enough time to perform. Short term volatility is the nature of equity and is very much expected.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Take care and stay safe.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021106/olqsc9przigzqet37icg.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Where will Indian Equity Market go from here – Up or Down?","seo_keywords":"Where will Indian Equity Market go from here – Up or Down?","seo_description":"We would like to highlight that FIIs are not the only movers of Indian market. Domestic Institutional Investors (DIIs), HNIs etc. are also important factors but it can definitely be said that FIIs are big movers.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021103/tsu7xlenqw1uefee7feo.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"196","title":"Coronavirus & Equity Market – Recommended Strategy","slug":"coronavirus-stock-market-recommended-strategy","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1586760319","published_date_view":"Apr 13, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021189/br3zkehmblcb7qggubl2.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 607px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The Coronavirus panic is spreading across the globe and has impacted economies and markets hard.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We don&rsquo;t know what will happen to markets in next few days or in next couple of months. But we feel that everything should be back to normal in next 3-9 months. There will be fear and pain in the economy which will lead to reduced spending, demand, corporate earnings and higher bad debts, fiscal deficits etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><u>But despite all these issues, economy and markets will bounce back. The good companies will continue to manufacture and offer their services</u>.</strong>&nbsp;Hindustan Unilever will continue to make soaps, Britannia will continue to sell biscuits, HDFC will continue to provide financial services etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">What is known today is that Equity is available at a discount of 30% from the peak. It&rsquo;s a good valuation to invest in good companies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><u><strong>Its important that we manage our emotions well during these volatile times. Its important to stick to the investment plan and follow the disciplined approach of Asset Allocation.</strong></u>&nbsp;This will help us in achieving better stability in portfolio and in getting better return in future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Historically, equity markets have always bounced back after every crisis. The same is visible in the following graph showing movement of US S&amp;P 500 since 1872.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021214/goqidphznat5n31tjf6g.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Nifty 500 which is a broad market index of Indian Equity has fallen from 10,057 to 6575 in last 40 days. This is a correction of ~35% from the peak. The current NSE 500 level of 6575 was last reached in November, 2014.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The recommended strategy is as under:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its recommended to hold existing equity investment. Its not the right time to sell now. If you sell now at a loss of ~30% then all the notional loss will become real and it will become difficult to recover the loss in future. All this loss will eventually get recovered if we continue to hold.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its not recommended to try selling equity now and then trying to buy back at lower price. Its very difficult to perfectly time the market. Any positive development may see fast recovery in market. World over interest rates are being cut and stimulus being provided to normalize the economy and markets.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its almost impossible to buy equity at bottom. Its recommended to buy equity with every meaningful correction and continuously reduce the overall cost price.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per our research, equity market is now undervalued by ~20%. There is still room for correction in future. However, markets may or may not correct further from here. But its important to keep enough liquidity for future equity buying.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Only that money &nbsp;should be invested in equity which is not required for next 5 years plus.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Please take care of yourself and family during these uncertain times.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing!</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021318/lnfdetrdd4vcmgk7fjgt.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Coronavirus & Equity Market – Recommended Strategy","seo_keywords":"Coronavirus & Equity Market – Recommended Strategy","seo_description":"We don’t know what will happen to markets in next few days or in next couple of months. But we feel that everything should be back to normal in next 3-9 months. There will be fear and pain in the economy which will lead to reduced spending, demand, corporate earnings and higher bad debts, fiscal deficits etc.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021316/uhfzzpcittcrqokdgdrj.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"197","title":"International Equity Exposure – Need of the Hour","slug":"international-equity-exposure-need-of-the-hour","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1584168575","published_date_view":"Mar 14, 2020","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021491/h3ed2tipcqmc4fanp6ns.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The decade of 2010-2019 has been phenomenal with respect to advancement in technology. Big industries like Auto, Media, Retail, Travel, Financial Services etc. are all getting disrupted because of new business innovations. The disruption is being led by companies like Amazon, Google, Facebook, Apple, Netflix, Tesla, Uber etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India continues to spend and consume which is mainly driven by huge middle income class but good part of the benefit is taken by the above tech companies which are not listed in Indian Stock Market. Majority of these tech companies are listed in US Stock Exchange.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Lately, the correlation between earning of companies listed in India and GDP growth of India has broken down. In the last 10 years, nominal GDP growth of India has averaged 13% per annum, while the popular benchmark index in India , the Nifty, has seen its earnings grow at ~8% per annum. Nifty has underperformed nominal GDP growth on an average by 5%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On the other hand, in America, the nominal GDP growth over the last 10 years has been ~4% and the US S&amp;P 500 earnings has grown at ~12% per annum. The earnings growth of US listed companies is ~4% per annum more than Nifty companies of India.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The primary reason for US companies doing so well is that US companies now get ~30% of their revenue from outside US. And this continues to go up every year. Majority of the innovations and tech disruptions are happening from US which are leading to faster growth for companies in US.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>This scenario is also captured in the performance of index return. Please find below the performance of US and Indian Index:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021449/blki1ylajjsqii1fvxpt.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 275px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that US Index has given ~10% per annum more than Indian Index in last 5 years.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Another big advantage of investing is US market is that the underlying investment is in US Dollar which has inverse correlation with Indian stock market. When FIIs sell in Indian market then they sell rupee and buy US Dollars which leads to US Dollar appreciating when Indian market falls. Also, because of interest rate differential between US and India, the US dollar in long term appreciates by ~3%-4% per annum.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>The above information definitely creates a beautiful picture for investing in US market but one needs to also understand the risk. Here are some of the risks we should be aware about:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Last decade was of US markets and emerging markets underperformed. The patterns tend to reverse. The coming decade may be good one for emerging markets</span><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Emerging Markets are undervalued by approx. 35% when compared to US markets.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Emerging markets have higher growth than developed markets, so in the long term emerging markets should give higher return. Its like emerging markets are mid cap and small caps of global equity markets, they carry high risk but also deliver higher return in the long term.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Keeping the above pros and cons of investing in Global market, its recommended to use the following portfolio strategy:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">International equity exposure should be seen more as a part of Global Asset Allocation and portfolio diversification.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Diversification helps in risk reduction in portfolio when assets have negative or low correlation. US markets definitely have low correlation with Indian market so it adds value. US market tends to do well at times when Indian market is not doing well.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">International Equity can be 15% of your total equity portfolio.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its recommended to have 10% exposure in US market and 5% in emerging market as well. We are also bullish on China because of the focus of country on tech innovations, artificial intelligence etc. The number of patents being filed by China is equal to US. China story will play out more strongly in years to come.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The time horizon for investment in International equity is 5 to 10 Years. So one should be ready to invest for very long term.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its not recommended to deploy lumpsum in International equity, staggered investment through SIP or STP is the best way to build exposure gradually.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Happy Investing!!</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021595/rqgze5s8t87mcjwpklsp.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"International Equity Exposure – Need of the Hour","seo_keywords":"International Equity Exposure – Need of the Hour","seo_description":"Another big advantage of investing is US market is that the underlying investment is in US Dollar which has inverse correlation with Indian stock market. When FIIs sell in Indian market then they sell rupee and buy US Dollars which leads to US Dollar appreciating when Indian market falls. Also, because of interest rate differential between US and India, the US dollar in long term appreciates by ~3%-4% per annum.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021591/hq9doi0jfodcppbrcatk.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"198","title":"The Kaizen Way of Wealth Creation","slug":"the-kaizen-way-of-wealth-creation","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1577429831","published_date_view":"Dec 27, 2019","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688021896/b5a6gopmgtzlwdzjxilv.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 720px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As we approach towards the end of decade 2010-2020, it&rsquo;s a good time to reflect on the changes which have happened in our life and to introspect the goals which we had set for ourselves 10 years back.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Time flies very fast. If you will look back and try to recollect the moments of last 10 years, you will realise that there are very few special moments that you are able to recollect. But overall, we are sure that wonderful and good things have happened in your life in this decade.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For India, the decade of 2010-2020 has been fantastic. The e-commerce, startups, smart phone, electric vehicle and other disruptions are all part of this decade. Sensex gave a return of 136% in this decade.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It&rsquo;s also a good time to plan for the next decade and set some goals around health, family, wealth, career, etc. Setting the goals is good and important as it gives life a direction and some meaning.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For some people, achievement of goals is easy as they are very focused and disciplined. But for most of the people, it&rsquo;s not easy and its like moving a huge block.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">&lsquo;The Kaizen Way&rsquo; is a popular book written by Dr. Robert Maurer. The book talks about the secret behind Japanese innovation and quality. The book is a good read and can indeed help us in moving the huge block.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per book, most intentions for change seek a transformative move&mdash;something significant to be achieved once and for all, in a short period. &ldquo;Big and bold steps&rdquo; is the mantra of many professionals and companies.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Real change, however, takes time and is difficult. We become overwhelmed with the magnitude of the effort and persistence required to lose twenty kilograms, save up for retirement or stabilize a sinking relationship. As with most New Year resolutions, we&rsquo;ll meet with success temporarily, only to find ourselves slipping back into our old ways as soon as the initial burst of enthusiasm fades out.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Maurer conceives transformative change as an endless, continuous process of gradual improvements. By breaking daunting tasks into absurdly little steps, we feel little resistance to change.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One small step leads to the next, which leads to one more, and so on&mdash;finally leading us to our goal of transformative change.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Dr. Maurer relates this approach to Kaizen, the famed Japanese system of obsessive tinkering and continuous, incremental improvement. Kaizen involves making continual, small adjustments to lifestyle to not only improve speed and quality, but also save resources. That is to say, it is a relentless pursuit of perfection by breaking it down into incremental improvements.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">People who have embraced Kaizen approach, start their everyday determined to become a little better at whatever it is they are doing than they were the day before.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Implication of Kaizen on Wealth Creation</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Wealth creation is like a water wheel and investment is like a water which is the resource to move the wheel. The key for moving the water wheel faster is to pour water on the wheel regularly and steadily and gradually increase the flow of water. The continuous flow of water creates the momentum in wheel and the speed increases exponentially as the quantum of water is gradually increased.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Similarly, for wealth creation, its good if we can begin with small regular investment to make the wheel move and gradually increase the investment for momentum to be created. For making the start, quantum of money is not relevant. What&rsquo;s important is to take the plunge and then gradually increase the saving and investment amount to create the magic.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The kaizen theory when applied to Systematic Investment plan (SIP) can lead to magical results. The same is evident as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If a monthly SIP investment of Rs. 1 Lac is done in equity fund for 20 years, then with a return expectation of 15% per annum, the future value of investment will be ~15 Crores.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul type=\"disc\">\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">If for the above SIP, if investment amount is increased by 10% every year then future value becomes ~23 Crores</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In the above example, we end up making ~8 Crores more just by making small incremental changes in SIP amount of 10% per annum.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#e74c3c;\"><strong>Wishing you lots of Kaizen and Magic in your life for the year 2020&nbsp;</strong></span><strong><img alt=\"????\" draggable=\"false\" role=\"img\" src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/14.0.0/svg/1f60a.svg\" style=\"height: 20px; width: 20px;\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022040/hfpb68qv6o1opebcy5iy.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"The Kaizen Way of Wealth Creation","seo_keywords":"The Kaizen Way of Wealth Creation","seo_description":"As we approach towards the end of decade 2010-2020, it’s a good time to reflect on the changes which have happened in our life and to introspect the goals which we had set for ourselves 10 years back.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022038/hdd3acygvqcszsihrszh.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"199","title":"Mutual Fund Size – Does it really matter?","slug":"mutual-fund-size-does-it-really-matter","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1574665352","published_date_view":"Nov 25, 2019","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022235/weupkt87wthedcblcg70.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 1080px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is innate of humans to think that big retail chains, big shops, or big media houses offer better services or goods. The logic behind such thought and belief is that businesses tend to become big only when it provides happiness to its customers. This may be true and just as well may not be true.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above belief is however far from being true when it comes to the area of mutual funds (MF).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Many investors are of the opinion that the size of a mutual fund scheme, i.e., the amount of money managed by a mutual fund house, is an important factor to consider when investing in mutual funds. This however is not true and has no actual basis to stand on. There is no intrinsic cause for a smaller fund to be worse than a larger mutual fund. If a smaller MF as compared to a larger MF of the same category shows better performance and track record, then it is but obvious that investors should opt for the smaller fund.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The reason for the above discussed belief of investors cannot be attributed to just the presumption of &lsquo;big tends to be good.&rsquo; Another cause of the belief is the fact that sellers of bigger mutual funds tend to actively promote such notions since it offers them an extra handle to advertise their MF against other funds which may be performing better.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Bigger mutual funds are better: Does it hold any real validity?</strong></span><br />\r\nA comparison of information available about the performance of varied funds shows that a slightly bigger fraction of larger MFs have better performance as opposed to smaller MFs. This observation is however scattered and quite small. There are several great smaller funds and there are several bad big MFs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Investors should take extra care to avoid falling into the trap of mistaking reason with effect. Mutual funds which have a track record of good returns over a long period of time generally become bigger due to increased influx of investor funds into them and such cash gets a longer period to increase and grow. They offered good performance and hence they eventually got bigger.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Does &lsquo;smaller mutual funds are better&rsquo; hold water?</strong></span><br />\r\nOne cannot just randomly select a big mutual fund and state that it must be good just because it is big. In a similar vein, one cannot select a smaller mutual fund with a good track record and state that its track record does not matter and one should not invest in it due to the fact that it is small. In addition to the performance of a mutual fund, there are several variables that can play a part in making a fund bigger or keeping it small.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The fact of the matter is that the marketing competence of a large fund house or the influence and reach of its parent company among MF distributors are the main reasons. There may be other variables as well. For instance, there are many equity funds which launched big on the first day itself due to their tremendously hyped NFOs at the top of the fund markets. A few these funds have been found to be lacking and give poor performance each year; however, they continue to remain big funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is also important to note that there are numerous comparatively small equity mutual funds in the MF sector which have show good performance over the long term and definitely warrant a perusal. Whenever you think that you would like to invest in this kind of mutual fund, or when praise is heaped on the fund by an analyst, then such an idea is disdainfully dismissed by the sellers of bigger funds.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sellers of larger funds often argue that comparison of an INR 500 crore fund with an INR 5,000 crore fund is not valid. Such an argument is a trick, a subterfuge. Aninvestors is not concerned about the size of a fund or whether or not a fund house measures up to the pecking order in the fund sector. If a mutual fund has given good returns over a period of time and has high rating from rating agencies, then size is irrelevant.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Does the size of a mutual fund ever matter?</strong></span><br />\r\nThere are many instances when size of a mutual fund does matter. It may also be noted that for some kinds of big equity funds, size can in fact be a disadvantage. For instance, big mutual funds with focus on mid-cap and small-cap shares may find it difficult to gather sufficient shares that they can put their money in. During the negative cycles of the share markets, such larger mutual funds may experience a double negative of poor liquidity and rapidly reducing values.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The key thing to remember is the fact that investors should not select one fund over the other on the basis of just their size, as doing so may result in you making some really bad investment choices.</span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022311/etshz1feyfrs6ogowigt.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Mutual Fund Size – Does it really matter?","seo_keywords":"Mutual Fund Size – Does it really matter?","seo_description":"It is innate of humans to think that big retail chains, big shops, or big media houses offer better services or goods. The logic behind such thought and belief is that businesses tend to become big only when it provides happiness to its customers. This may be true and just as well may not be true.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022309/cbmdxr4edoolcdfmd0ep.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"200","title":"Booster Shot for Economy, Investment, Sentiments & Returns","slug":"booster-shot-for-economy-investment","category":"General","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1569308721","published_date_view":"Sep 24, 2019","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022380/nq0smcgjiaiuave7aj5l.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 780px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Indian Economy has been struggling for the last few quarters and the near term outlook has also been bleak. Lately, the focus of government has been to tax the rich and increase spending towards social welfare.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">On last Friday, the Finance Minister, surprisingly, changed the above dynamics by announcing bold decisions to cut corporate tax rates and stimulate the flagging economy. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With this article, we will try to explain what has happened and how it impacts the investors like us.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What key announcements were made?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The government has provided a direct stimulus of Rs. 1.45 lakh crores via reduction in corporate tax rate from 30% to 22% with effective tax rate lowered from 34.9% to 25.2% (including surcharge).</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The government announced a special 17% tax rate for new companies incorporated on or after 1st Oct 2019 and starting new manufacturing facilities before March 2023.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The minimum alternate tax (MAT) rate has been reduced from 18.5% to 15% (before surcharges)</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The government has also removed the additional surcharge on capital gains for all classes of investors.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What will be the impact of above measures?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">These tax cuts are likely to help in reviving sentiments and kick start economy which have been under pressure for last few quarters.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Expenditure has now moved from government hands to corporate and we believe that corporates are better when it comes to spending.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Rs 1.45 lakh crores per annum would now be available as a stimulus to corporates who can choose among options such as keeping the higher profits, paying higher dividends, investing in capacity expansions or pass on benefits to consumers which will push up the demand.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">India will become competitive to attract global capital through FDI for setting up manufacturing plants given the tax rate is now just 15%. The tax rate is probably amongst the lowest in Asian Economies. Hopefully, Make in India will get wings now.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Corporate earnings is likely to get boost by ~10%. Lower tax and expected increase in demand makes the earning outlook better. This makes the equity valuation relatively attractive.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Corporate Investment/ Capex has been struggling in the last few years, this tax cut is likely to boost corporate savings and most probably help in reviving the much needed investment.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For banking &amp; NBFC sector, low tax rate may help in lowering of loan rates and will allow higher provisioning to adjust for the NPAs. This will help in credit growth and reduce credit/ default risk in market.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>What will be the impact on equity and debt?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Equity:</strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Performance of equity is dependent on corporate earnings which is further dependent on economy growth. These announcements will have a positive impact on economy growth and this will eventually lead to better performance of equity.&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">It is important to know that the positive performance in economy will happen in longer term. We don&rsquo;t expect significant positive change in economy in short term. It takes time for capex and new manufacturing facilities to come up.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity valuation has become cheaper by ~10% because of tax saving for corporates. The earnings will go up because of lower tax and this will lead to lower valuation multiples like PE Ratio etc.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity market has already started seeing good rally and this may continue for some time as market will start discounting future expected growth.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">By this announcement, government has addressed one of the concerns of economy. We will still face other challenges like global economy slowdown, US-China trade war, NBFC crisis, real estate slowdown etc. It will be important to track and closely watch these developments.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;Debt:</strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">By passing Rs. 1.45 Lakh crores of benefit to corporates, the government will now have to deal with increased fiscal deficit. The budgeted fiscal deficit is now expected to move from 3.3% to ~3.9%.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Higher fiscal deficit means higher government borrowings which will lead to higher interest rates in the longer end of yield curve. On last Friday, Indian 10 year G Sec moved by 15 basis points from 6.64% to 6.79%. This movement has not been on higher side till now. It will be interesting to see how it moves in new future.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Higher interest rates are good for debt investors in long term as the interest accrual starts happening at higher rate. There may be some short term pain in debt because of rise in interest rate but this short term pain is for long term good.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is the recommended portfolio strategy now?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Equity:</strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In January 2018, we were underweight in equity by 25%. We have been reducing this underweight continuously in the last 18 months as equity market has been falling. Last month, we were underweight in equity by 6%. With this new announcements, we feel that equity has become attractive and now we have increased overweight on equity to 5%.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above tactical asset allocation means that a moderate investor with a strategic equity allocation of 50% should now increase the allocation to 52.5%.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its not recommended to increase the equity allocation by lump sum investment. Its recommended to change the equity allocation in a staggered manner over a period of next 12 months through monthly SIP and STP. Investors who are highly underexposed in equity may also consider some lump sum investment.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Within equity, its recommended to invest more in multi cap, mid cap and small caps. Maximum recommended allocation in mid cap and small cap is 40% combined.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Debt:</strong></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its recommended to invest in debt mutual fund categories of ultra short term, low duration, short term and corporate bonds. These funds invest in shorter end of yield curve and don&rsquo;t get impacted significantly when interest rates rise.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its recommended to invest in funds of above recommended categories which have underlying bonds of high credit quality.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Happy Investing!!</strong></span></span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022556/xb4kc3wo5ueftbpuoagp.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Booster Shot for Economy, Investment, Sentiments & Returns","seo_keywords":"Booster Shot for Economy, Investment, Sentiments & Returns","seo_description":"On last Friday, the Finance Minister, surprisingly, changed the above dynamics by announcing bold decisions to cut corporate tax rates and stimulate the flagging economy.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022554/mzlkyjqox8dkuhmtv26f.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"201","title":"Indian Equity Market is Overvalued or Undervalued – Analysis","slug":"indian-equity-market-is-overvalued-or-undervalued-analysis","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1569136649","published_date_view":"Sep 22, 2019","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022846/wfr2jq6c2eidgnpqy5ak.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 719px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">One of the most debatable topic in Investing is about the right valuation of overall equity market. Most of the experts, fund managers, financial institutions etc. have different opinion on equity valuation and accordingly they report different numbers.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">With this article we will try to answer the questions related to valuation of Indian equity market so that we are more aware and confident about our investment decisions.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Why is valuation of equity market important?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Equity valuation tells us whether we are buying/ investing in shares at a low or high price. When we invest at a lower valuation then future expected return becomes higher and vice versa. A simple example of same is that If equity market is assumed to give ~15% in long term then money doubles in 5 years. However, if investment is made at higher valuation then it will take more than 5 years to double the money as expected return come downs.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In Jan 2008, Sensex had touched ~21,000 level and valuations were highly stretched, if investment was made at this level then there would have been no growth in investment for next 6 years. But if investment was made in Feb, 2009 when Sensex had fallen to ~8300 Level and valuations were very low then money would have doubled in 6 months.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>How to find the correct valuation of equity market?</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Finding rough valuation of equity market is not so difficult but getting a good valuation number is challenging. There are various valuation indicators like PE Ratio, PB Ratio, Dividend Yield, GDP to Market Capitalization, PE to Growth Ratio, CAPE , Bond Equity Earnings Yield etc.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The most simple and popular among these indicators is PE Ratio which is a relative valuation indicator. To judge the right valuation of equity market, an investor can compare current PE Ratio with average or fair level of PE Ratio. Example &ndash; If current PE Ratio is 24 and fair level of PE Ratio is 20 then it can be said that equity market is overvalued by 20%</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Why is it difficult to find the exact valuation and why do opinions vary?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The opinion on valuation varies because data source and methodology used for calculation are different sometimes. But it also means that we should use correct data &amp; methodology and come at right valuation because with investment decisions we can&rsquo;t afford to do mistakes.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">For simplicity purpose, from here on, we will use only PE Ratio as a reference.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Here are some of the difference in reported PE Ratios:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022868/dvjlgmbkmazkpfd07y4x.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 403px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><em>&nbsp;*as on 23/8/19</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows huge difference in PE Ratio reported by both Bombay Stock Exchange and National Stock Exchange.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In various interviews/ media articles of financial experts, fund managers, institutions etc. different PE Ratio gets reported. Sometimes Forward PE Ratio of 1, 2 and 3 years also gets used which makes the decision making even more difficult.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>How do we calculate right PE Ratio at Alpha Capital?</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We believe that if some noise is removed from the data then we can get correct and meaningful information. To find the right PE Ratio and valuation of market, we do the following:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Analyse individual stocks in each Index and create synthetic Indexes at our own level.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Remove those stocks from calculation which have negative earnings. Stocks with negative earnings increases the overall PE Ratio unwantedly.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Reduce the impact of companies which are outliers. For example some companies have very high PE Ratios because of low earnings or because of high expected growth in future. These outliers can increase the overall average of PE Ratio. Example &ndash; Trent Ltd has PE Ratio of 171. Outliers are removed by using median instead of mean as a measure for computation of average.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The synthetic index which we create gives equal weight to all stocks in the Index. Higher weightage is not given to stocks which are large by market capitalization.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Because of above smoothening of data, we get following PE Ratio for various Indexes:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688022891/f0vlj9xym66k198tah0h.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 616px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><em>*as on 23/8/19</em></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We believe that fair value of PE Ratio is 20. So based on above table, it can be said that Sensex and Nifty are overvalued by ~30%, Mid Cap is overvalued by ~25%, Small Cap is undervalued by ~8% and Top 500 is overvalued by ~6%.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its not recommended to use valuation of Sensex or Nifty as reference for overall equity market because both Sensex and Nifty represents only Top 30 and 50 stocks respectively which is a very small representative. The best index as proxy for overall equity market is Top 500.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">So based on this information, it can be said that&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>Indian Equity market is overvalued by ~6%.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><strong>​​​​​​​</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#e74c3c;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Happy Investing!!</strong></span></span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023052/xguslom1lksdl8yxyjcm.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Indian Equity Market is Overvalued or Undervalued – Analysis","seo_keywords":"Indian Equity Market is Overvalued or Undervalued – Analysis","seo_description":"One of the most debatable topic in Investing is about the right valuation of overall equity market. Most of the experts, fund managers, financial institutions etc. have different opinion on equity valuation and accordingly they report different numbers.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023051/udb4yicuvlszo7bwxlu2.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"},{"blog_id":"202","title":"Equity Market Correction – Portfolio Strategy & Action Plan","slug":"equity-market-correction-portfolio-strategy-action-plan","category":"Investment Ideas","published_by":"Alpha Research","published_date":"1566285485","published_date_view":"Aug 20, 2019","discription":"<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023164/elq7x4xkfkjmrnzsabgj.webp\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 608px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since 31st Jan, 2018, equity market has been going through correction. In the last 18.5 months, equity market indexes have seen following correction:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023275/mle4sqt8epjmwpvwtpq0.png\" style=\"width: 1080px; height: 220px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that in last 18.5 Months, Sensex and Nifty which are reflective of few top large cap stocks have not been impacted but mid cap and small cap indexes have taken a huge beating and are down by 19% and ~36% respectively.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Why did the equity market fall?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">There are various reasons because of which equity market has been correcting in the last 18.5 months. The primary reasons are listed below:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Corporate earnings have been poor in the last few years</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; The earnings for NSE 500 has been almost flat in last 4 years and has grown at ~4% p.a. in last 9 years.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Unfriendly regulatory and taxation changes</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Demonetization, tax on long term capital of equity, increase of tax surcharge on Foreign Portfolio Investors (FPI) etc.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Categorization and rationalization of equity mutual funds by SEBI</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; Clear demarcation for exposure in large, mid and small cap stocks was done for equity funds. This led to huge selling of mid cap and small cap stocks.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Stretched valuations of Indian stock market&nbsp;</strong>&ndash; Because of good investment by Foreign Portfolio Investors (FPI) and Indian Mutual Funds in the last few years, equity market had seen huge rally. Since upward market movement was not supported by similar corporate earnings growth, the valuations of Indian stock market had stretched to an all-time high. Other emerging and developed markets are now available at better valuation when compared to India.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Is the pain in equity market over?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Its impossible to predict the equity market in short term. There are too many dynamics into play for movement of equity market. With globalization, these dynamics have become more complex and hence make the prediction even more difficult in short term.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is the current valuation level of Indian equity market?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Valuation of equity market is reflected by various indicators and factors like PE Ratio, PB Ratio, Dividend Yield, expected earnings growth, volatility, company and sector outliers etc. One of the common indicator used for same is PE Ratio. The PE Ratio for top indices in India is given as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023303/yysambbqgezt20gkgn5q.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 526px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that PE Ratio is still on the higher side and has good scope for correction. The recent equity market fall has improved the valuation relatively. For example &ndash; PE Ratio of NSE 500 had gone to ~33 and the same has now corrected to 29. However, further fall in equity market from valuation perspective is possible.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What should investor do now?</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The most important thing for an investor to do now is to manage his/ her emotions by not getting seriously affected by equity market volatility. Bull and bear run are all part of market cycle and its natural for market to correct and fall. The good thing about equity is that market (Index and Mutual Funds) always bounces back. What is down today will definitely come up in future.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">A smart investor is someone who takes advantage of these market swings. He/she books profit when market goes up and buys when market goes down. Similarly, we should look at equity market correction as an opportunity for investment in low price. We should celebrate the market correction and be happy whenever market corrects. &nbsp;Good returns are made when investment is done in fallen market.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As per empirical research, average investors globally (including India) make only ~40% of Index return in long term. He/ she sells when market falls and buys when market goes up. The brief study is as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023327/rhvjpuy694exfucni8ft.webp\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 426px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows that for US market, in 30 years, the S&amp;P 500 Index gave 10% p.a. whereas average investor only made 4% p.a.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As a smart investor, we need to do reverse of what average investor is doing. We need to buy when market falls and sell when market goes up so that we make more return than Index.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What should be the equity portfolio strategy for investor?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Some of the important aspects for investor to consider when investing in equity are as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>1) Equity investment is for long term &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>Equity investment is good if investment horizon is 5 years plus. In short term equity market can be highly volatile but in long term equity market is stable and gives good return. Following is the historical movement of Sensex since launch:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023354/axcquxrh5yymamarptp3.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 385px;\" type=\"image\" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Sensex was launched in 1979 with a base value of 100. Today the value is at 37400. This means that&nbsp;<strong>Sensex has grown by 374 times in last 40 years</strong>. During this journey, Sensex has seen correction by more than 50% in short term as well but the good thing is that market always bounces back and does well in long term.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>2) Historical return of asset classes in India:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023379/yc8u0zs00tzsqrg3hqmi.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 348px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above table shows bank fixed deposit has given an annual post tax return of approx. 5.5% in the last 10 years and 20 years. In the same time period, equity has given a return of 17% and 12.9% respectively. If portfolio return has to be enhanced then equity is important in portfolio.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>3) Missing 25 best days in equity market:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong><input alt=\"\" src=\"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023403/wv128vickka138y5t9fs.png\" style=\"width: 700px; height: 390px;\" type=\"image\" /></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The above chart shows the performance of US Equity Index &ndash; S&amp;P 500 and how the performance struggles if the best 25 days of equity are missed. It shows that one needs to stay invested in equity to make good returns. Some market timing and tactical asset allocation can be good but extreme market timing can lead us to miss the few best days of market which may eventually lead to low return. Great investors like Warren Buffet, Charlie Munger etc. have made wealth by staying invested in equity. They have never completely exited equity market even in highly stretched valuations.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What has Alpha Capital as your advisor done till now?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As your financial advisor and personal CFO, we have been actively tracking the market and taking required actions in portfolio. The actions taken are as under:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">The asset allocation of portfolio between equity, debt and other asset classes have been made on the basis of your risk profile and financial plan. For conservative investor, allocation to equity has been low and for aggressive investor the allocation has been high.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Only that money has been deployed in equity whose time horizon is 5 years plus. Nothing has been deployed in equity whose requirement is in near future. So even if market doesn&rsquo;t do well for next few years, your family aspirations won&rsquo;t get affected. Liquidity has been kept in debt funds/ fixed income product for any expense which is budgeted to happen in short term.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since 2017, we have been conservative on equity market because the valuations had started getting stretched. Accordingly, profit booking in equity was done in March 2017, July 2017 and January 2018.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In January 2018 before equity market had started correcting, we had recommended that equity market is overvalued by 25% and accordingly allocation towards equity was reduced.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In anticipation of equity market correction, higher allocation was done towards large cap funds, hybrid funds and multi cap funds oriented towards large cap. These funds fall less when equity market corrects.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Fresh deployment in equity was staggered through monthly systematic transfer plans.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Liquidity has been created in portfolios by parking money in debt funds . This can be used for equity buying when market falls.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">In October 2018, when equity market had corrected meaningfully, lump sum purchase in equity was done to take advantage of low price.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Mid cap and small cap has become attractive after recent correction, and accordingly allocation is being increased in mid cap and small cap through SIP or STP.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>What is the action plan for future?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">According to our internal research, we feel equity market is still overvalued by 10%.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">We plan to buy equity with every meaningful fall to take advantage of low price. The plan is to buy equity whenever NSE 500 Index corrects by 10% or if the valuation improves because of increase in corporate earnings.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">Since October 2018, meaningful correction in equity market has not happened and accordingly recommendation for lump sum purchase in equity has not been given. The next equity buying will be done when NSE 500 Index falls from current level of 8950 to ~8100 level.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">As an advisor, we don&rsquo;t believe in churning portfolio aggressively. Too much churning leads to higher tax and exit charges. As per empirical research, over churning doesn&rsquo;t add any value in portfolio. So we will buy or sell equity only when there is meaningful movement in equity market.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:20px;\">​​​​​​​</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#c0392b;\"><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>Lets celebrate the market correction!!</strong></span></span></p>\r\n","is_active":"1","is_draft":"0","blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023683/rb0nomewm0lvydd8bbxd.webp","published_by_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1687758943/o9rxxf4fosnurb23hjsv.png","seo_title":"Equity Market Correction – Portfolio Strategy & Action Plan","seo_keywords":"Equity Market Correction – Portfolio Strategy & Action Plan","seo_description":"The above chart shows the performance of US Equity Index – S&P 500 and how the performance struggles if the best 25 days of equity are missed. It shows that one needs to stay invested in equity to make good returns. Some market timing and tactical asset allocation can be good but extreme market timing can lead us to miss the few best days of market which may eventually lead to low return. Great investors like Warren Buffet, Charlie Munger etc. have made wealth by staying invested in equity. They have never completely exited equity market even in highly stretched valuations.","seo_blog_image":"http://res.cloudinary.com/dyedkdjm1/image/upload/v1688023680/oi2tj7cij5mvdffyjtl3.webp","created_at":"Jun 29, 2023"}]
